{"timestamp": "2026-03-16T21:45:09.377161", "agent_name": "AstroDeepResearchAgent", "method_name": "load_cached_research", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "Cached research loaded from: deep_research_gpt5.4/Threonine-Run1.txt", "user_message": "Config: deep_research_gpt5.4", "raw_response": "Prebiotic Synthesis of Threonine\nMolecule-specific constraints that shape plausible prebiotic routes\nThreonine is a hydroxy-amino acid whose prebiotic formation is complicated by (i) the need to install both an amino group and a hydroxyl-bearing sidechain and (ii) the fact that two diastereomeric products are typically expected: threonine and allothreonine. The co-occurrence of threonine and allothreonine in abiotic product mixtures is explicitly reported in classic spark-discharge experiments, where both \u201cthreonine\u201d and \u201callothreonine\u201d were confirmed among the synthesized amino acids. [1]\nA key practical implication for network design is that many plausible routes do not make threonine \u201cdirectly\u201d from CO\u2082; instead, they converge on a specific aldehyde-level carbonyl precursor\u2014lactaldehyde (2\u2011hydroxypropanal)\u2014followed by Strecker-type conversion to an aminonitrile and then hydrolysis to the amino acid. This lactaldehyde-centered view is articulated both in cyanosulfidic photoredox work (where lactaldehyde is produced photochemically from nitrile/cyanohydrin precursors) and in meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin discussions (where lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the carbonyl precursor for threonine/allothreonine). [2]\nHydrothermal persistence is also a constraint: hydroxy amino acids (including serine and threonine) can undergo dehydration and other degradation pathways during diagenesis/hydrothermal exposure, which matters when evaluating vent-based syntheses or post-synthesis survival. [3]\nKnown prebiotic synthesis routes for threonine\nElectric-discharge (atmospheric / volcanic-plume) synthesis.\nA strong line of experimental evidence for abiotic threonine production comes from spark-discharge experiments designed to simulate reducing (or locally reducing) atmospheres. In the 1958 H\u2082S-rich Miller experiment reanalysis, E. T. Parker[4] and coauthors (2011, Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences) report that residues produced from a spark discharge acting on a gas mixture containing H\u2082S, CH\u2084, NH\u2083, and CO\u2082 contained a broad suite of amino acids and amines, including threonine; chiral amino acids were largely racemic within measurement uncertainty, supporting an abiotic origin (rather than modern biological contamination). [5]\nEarlier work also directly confirmed threonine and allothreonine in discharge products from mixtures including methane, nitrogen, water, and traces of ammonia. [1]\nUV-driven cyanosulfidic photoredox + Strecker assembly via lactaldehyde.\nA second, mechanistically explicit route emerges from cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry associated with Daniel J. Ritson[6] and John D. Sutherland[7] (2013, Angewandte Chemie International Edition). In this system, UV (254 nm) photoredox chemistry reduces nitriles/cyanohydrins to generate aldehydes (including lactaldehyde, the threonine carbonyl precursor), and subsequent addition of HCN and NH\u2083 yields the corresponding Strecker aminonitriles (including the (allo-)threonine aminonitrile). [8]\nA later synthesis-and-systems perspective by Nicholas J. Green[9], Xu, and Sutherland (2021, Journal of the American Chemical Society) explicitly situates this \u201clactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile\u201d step inside a broader UV-photochemical network driven by hydrated-electron photochemistry and cyanosulfidic redox cycling. [10]\nHCN-oligomer / aminomalononitrile (AMN) chemistry as an alternative C\u2013N assembly route.\nA distinct, often-overlooked proposal is that HCN oligomers provide multifunctional C/N building blocks. In this vein, George Thanassi[11] (1975, Journal of Molecular Evolution) reports that reacting aminomalononitrile (a key HCN oligomer) with electrophiles (including aldehydes) followed by hydrolysis yields a range of amino acids, including threonine and allothreonine. This route is attractive for network design because it bypasses the need to pre-form lactaldehyde in bulk; the tradeoff is that selectivity, geochemical plausibility of AMN accumulation, and competing polymerization pathways remain active questions. [12]\nParent-body (meteoritic) Strecker\u2013cyanohydrin synthesis as evidence of a natural \u201cthreonine module.\u201d\nAlthough not an Earth experiment per se, carbonaceous-chondrite organic chemistry provides a natural laboratory for reactions relevant to early Earth delivery and corroborates mechanistic plausibility. A detailed treatment in a Kyushu University-hosted report (associated with threonine/hydroxy-amino-acid analyses in carbonaceous chondrites) describes Strecker-cyanohydrin synthesis where aldehydes/ketones + NH\u2083 \u2192 imines \u2192 CN\u207b addition \u2192 hydrolysis to \u03b1\u2011amino acids, and it explicitly identifies lactaldehyde as the carbonyl precursor for threonine and/or allo-threonine. [13]\nKey intermediates and precursors that define a threonine synthesis network\nAcross the most experimentally grounded routes, threonine sits at the end of a relatively consistent intermediate chain:\nThe minimal \u201cStrecker module\u201d requires a carbonyl compound, ammonia (or another nitrogen source that can generate an imine), and cyanide; the carbonyl required for threonine/allothreonine is lactaldehyde. [14]\nIn cyanosulfidic photoredox networks, the upstream pool can be generated from HCN-derived nitriles and cyanohydrins, with hydrogen sulfide acting as terminal reductant and Cu(I) cyanide functioning as a photoredox-active catalyst/surface. Key intermediates and branch points in the Ritson\u2013Sutherland sequence include: glycolonitrile \u2192 glycolaldehyde (and formaldehyde, acetaldehyde as side/rearranged products), acetaldehyde cyanohydrin (lactonitrile-type node) \u2192 lactaldehyde, and then lactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile in the presence of added HCN and NH\u2083. [8]\nIn spark-discharge contexts, the primary \u201cprecursor-generating\u201d chemistry is atmospheric/plume radical chemistry producing HCN, aldehydes/ketones, and related C\u2013N intermediates that can rain out and further react in surface waters\u2014an explicit motivation for the volcanic-plume framing of Miller-type experiments. [15]\nA key branching control is ammonia availability: the meteoritic discussion emphasizes that ammonia-rich environments favor aminonitrile (amino acid) pathways, whereas ammonia-poor settings favor cyanohydrins and hydroxy acids\u2014directly impacting whether the threonine branch is expressed efficiently. [13]\nReaction mechanisms, conditions, yields, and selectivity\nUV photoredox \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 (allo-)threonine aminonitrile\nThe most quantitatively specified prebiotic route to a threonine precursor is the UV photoredox chemistry of Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.), which directly reports yields for lactaldehyde formation under defined conditions:\nA representative system for first-stage reduction used 10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H\u2082S, 33 mM sodium phosphate, plus solid CuCN (10 mol % relative to glycolonitrile), irradiated at 254 nm in a quartz cuvette; after 2 h, glycolaldehyde (detected as hydrate) formed in 42% yield in solution, alongside other aldehydic products including acetaldehyde. [8]\nCritically, \u201csecond-stage\u201d cyanohydrin photoreductions in the same study yield the dedicated threonine carbonyl precursor: irradiation of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin furnished lactaldehyde in 19% yield (after 2 h irradiation). Lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the Strecker precursor of \u201c(allo-)threonine.\u201d [8]\nDownstream assembly to the threonine aminonitrile is demonstrated by adding HCN and ammonia: when HCN and NH\u2083 were added to photoreduction products, lactaldehyde was \u201csmoothly converted\u201d via its cyanohydrin to the (allo-)threonine Strecker intermediate aminonitrile (aminonitrile 22 in the paper\u2019s numbering). Timescales reported for aminonitrile formation in these systems are days to weeks, indicating that geochemical \u201cholding times\u201d and compartmentalization could matter. [8]\nMechanistically, this route couples: (i) photoredox reduction of nitrile/cyanohydrin nodes to aldehydes (including lactaldehyde) and (ii) conventional Strecker-type conversion (aldehyde \u2192 imine \u2192 aminonitrile) once NH\u2083 and CN\u207b/HCN are available; hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the expected final step in Strecker frameworks, and the meteoritic Strecker discussion explicitly frames hydrolysis of aminonitriles as producing \u03b1-amino acids. [16]\nA systems-level restatement by Green, Xu, and Sutherland (2021, JACS) emphasizes that photoreduction of the relevant cyanohydrin node leads to lactaldehyde, and lactaldehyde then yields a threonine precursor aminonitrile by addition of HCN and NH\u2083, embedding this step inside a broader cyanosulfidic network. [10]\nSpark discharge / volcanic plume simulation \u2192 threonine in complex amino-acid mixtures\nIn Parker et al. (2011, PNAS), reanalysis of archived Miller-type residues from a 1958 discharge experiment (gas mixture including CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S, CO\u2082) identified 23 amino acids and 4 amines; the paper explicitly notes threonine among amino acids generated by this discharge chemistry and interprets racemic chiral amino acids (D/L \u2248 1 within stated uncertainty) as evidence against modern biological contamination. [17]\nQuantitatively, Parker et al. present product abundances as molar ratios relative to glycine (=1). In their Fig. 2, threonine appears at roughly the 10\u207b\u00b2 scale relative to glycine (order-of-magnitude read from the plotted point on a log molar-ratio axis). [18]\nIn an earlier and more expansive discharge study, Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) report that electric discharges in a methane\u2013nitrogen\u2013water system (with traces of ammonia) produced a wide set of amino acids, and explicitly confirm both threonine and allothreonine (alongside serine and others) by ion-exchange chromatography and GC\u2013MS. [1]\nThese discharge pathways are usually interpreted as producing amino acids via formation of reactive small C\u2013N intermediates (HCN, aldehydes/ketones) followed by aqueous-phase assembly (often Strecker-type), and Parker et al. explicitly connect volcanic lightning + reduced gases to generation of HCN and other intermediates that can wash out and accumulate in tidal settings. [15]\nHCN-oligomer (AMN) electrophile chemistry \u2192 threonine/allothreonine after hydrolysis\nThanassi (1975, J. Mol. Evol.) provides experimental evidence that aminomalononitrile-derived chemistry can yield threonine and allothreonine after hydrolysis when AMN is reacted with electrophiles (including aldehydes) under mild conditions. The study explicitly states that amino acids (including threonine/allothreonine) were identified and quantified from hydrolysates. [12]\nFrom a mechanism standpoint, AMN functions as a multifunctional C\u2013N synthon, offering an alternative to \u201csingle-carbonyl + HCN + NH\u2083\u201d assembly; its prebiotic plausibility hinges on whether AMN can accumulate at useful concentrations without being diverted into intractable HCN polymers\u2014an issue treated as part of the broader \u201cHCN chemistry\u201d challenge space in origin-of-life literature. [19]\nHydrothermal Strecker-type synthesis: relevance and limitations for threonine specifically\nHydrothermal Strecker synthesis under mineral-buffered redox conditions is experimentally documented for several amino acids, demonstrating that Strecker chemistry can proceed in plausible vent/flank conditions if aldehydes/ketones and cyanide are available. Andersson & Holm (2000, Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere) summarize hydrothermal experiments (Hennet et al., 1992) using HCN, CH\u2082O, and NH\u2084Cl at 150\u202f\u00b0C and 10 bar in the presence of a pyrite\u2013pyrrhotite\u2013magnetite buffer; reported products include mM-level glycine (\u22489\u201312 mM) and lower but measurable levels of other amino acids (e.g., alanine \u22480.5\u20131.3 mM; aspartate and glutamate at \u22480.28\u20130.36 mM and \u22480.064\u20130.100 mM, respectively). [20]\nHowever, threonine itself is not among the explicitly tabulated products in that summary table, highlighting a practical bottleneck: even if hydrothermal Strecker chemistry is viable in general, demonstrating threonine specifically requires (i) access to lactaldehyde (or a direct hydrothermal pathway to lactaldehyde/lactaldehyde equivalents) and (ii) managing the competing high-temperature degradation chemistry that can disproportionately affect hydroxy amino acids. [21]\nA further caution for purely vent-centric \u201cCO\u2082 \u2192 amino acids\u201d narratives is that some claimed FeS/H\u2082S-driven syntheses have not held up; Keefe et al. (1995, PNAS) report that their FeS/H\u2082S system did not produce amino acids from CO\u2082 (nor via proposed reductive amination/carboxylation), sharpening the distinction between (a) Strecker-type routes requiring carbonyls + CN\u207b and (b) hypothesized direct CO\u2082 fixation-to-amino-acid routes. [22]\nMineral catalysts and surfaces implicated in threonine-relevant steps\nCu(I) cyanide (CuCN) as a photoredox-active heterogeneous catalyst/surface.\nIn the Ritson\u2013Sutherland photoredox system, CuCN is added as a solid; mixing generates a fine dark precipitate that is irradiated, consistent with heterogeneous photoredox cycling and surface-mediated electron production. [8]\nGreen et al. (2021, JACS) discuss Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanocuprate photoredox cycling as a route to hydrated electrons and connect this catalysis to the production of amino-acid Strecker precursors, including the threonine aminonitrile precursor derived from lactaldehyde. [10]\nSulfide minerals as sources of H\u2082S (reductant) and CuCN-generating Cu\u2013S chemistry.\nRitson & Sutherland explicitly note a plausible geochemical source: dissolution of copper sulfide minerals in cyanide solution could generate CuCN catalysts, and dissolution of FeS could provide additional H\u2082S reductant\u2014an explicit mineralogical bridge between rock chemistry and the photoredox network. [8]\nFerrocyanide as a cyanide concentrator and potential \u201cfeedstock conditioner.\u201d\nRitson & Sutherland also emphasize that cyanide can be concentrated by complexation with Fe\u00b2\u207a to form ferrocyanide, and that thermal processing of mixed ferrocyanide salts can yield mixtures containing cyanide, ammonia, and cyanamide upon rehydration\u2014reagents directly relevant to Strecker chemistry and linked nucleotide-precursor reactions. [8]\nPyrite\u2013pyrrhotite\u2013magnetite and silicate buffers in hydrothermal simulations.\nAndersson & Holm\u2019s redox-buffered hydrothermal framework highlights the use of pyrite (FeS\u2082), pyrrhotite (FeS), and magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) to constrain oxygen fugacity (redox), and K\u2011feldspar\u2013muscovite\u2013quartz assemblages to influence pH via ion activity control\u2014key when extrapolating laboratory hydrothermal yields to natural settings. [20]\nEnvironmental context and the main open challenges for threonine\nMost relevant environments by route.\nFor spark-discharge threonine formation, the empirical basis is strongest for localized, reducing volcanic-plume or eruption-lightning environments, where mixtures of reduced gases (e.g., CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S) and oxidized components (e.g., CO\u2082) can coexist transiently; Parker et al. explicitly argue such localized plume chemistry could generate HCN and other intermediates that rain out and accumulate in tidal zones, supporting subsequent aqueous synthesis steps. [15]\nFor UV photoredox threonine-precursor formation, the most relevant setting is a sunlit surface environment that can sustain UV photochemistry (at least episodically) and maintain access to cyanide and sulfide redox pairs; Green et al. note that low H\u2082S solubility and low crustal copper abundance would restrict Cu/H\u2082S cyanosulfidic networks to specific terrains (e.g., copper-rich, alkaline pools), a critical geochemical constraint on global plausibility. [23]\nFor Strecker chemistry in aqueous-alteration contexts (meteorites or analogous wet-rock systems), the carbonaceous-chondrite analysis emphasizes that ammonia abundance and redox state influence whether aminonitriles (\u2192 amino acids) are favored over cyanohydrins (\u2192 hydroxy acids), and it frames threonine/allothreonine formation as dependent on lactaldehyde availability. [13]\nKey bottlenecks and debates.\nA central unresolved bottleneck is sourcing and sustaining lactaldehyde (and/or its direct nitrile/cyanohydrin precursors) at concentrations compatible with downstream Strecker chemistry. The meteoritic analysis proposes that lactaldehyde may be relatively less available than glycolaldehyde/hydroxyacetone because its formation depends on less abundant ethanol-derived radical chemistry in interstellar ices, which would suppress threonine relative to serine/\u03b1\u2011methylserine\u2014an argument that can be repurposed as a constraint on Earth scenarios if analogous precursor biases held in terrestrial inventories. [13]\nAnother challenge is selectivity and stereochemistry. Multiple experimental contexts support predominantly racemic production for chiral amino acids in abiotic syntheses (e.g., spark discharge products; racemic allo-threonine in some meteoritic extracts where it can be resolved cleanly), but threonine\u2019s second stereocenter makes diastereomeric mixtures (threonine/allothreonine) a near-default outcome unless additional selection mechanisms are invoked. [24]\nA third major issue is compatibility of synthesis with survival. Hydroxy amino acids can undergo dehydration and other transformations during heating or long residence times; this is directly relevant to vent models (where high temperatures can accelerate degradation) and also to post-synthesis processing. [3]\nFinally, there is an ongoing debate over whether threonine should be expected to be among the earliest-abundant amino acids at all. The experimental record shows that threonine is certainly possible abiotically (spark discharge; cyanosulfidic networks yielding its Strecker precursors), but it is also plausibly scarcity-limited by precursor availability (lactaldehyde) and stability constraints (hydroxy amino-acid degradation), leaving room for models where threonine is incorporated later into biochemistry relative to simpler amino acids. [25]\n \n[1] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\n[2] [6] [8] [25] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4269183/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4269183/\n[3] https://pubs.usgs.gov/publication/70012489\nhttps://pubs.usgs.gov/publication/70012489\n[4] [5] [9] [11] [15] [17] [18] [24] https://science.gsfc.nasa.gov/sed/content/uploadFiles/publication_files/Parker2011.pdf\nhttps://science.gsfc.nasa.gov/sed/content/uploadFiles/publication_files/Parker2011.pdf\n[7] [12] REACTIONS OF AMINOMALONONITRILE WITH ... - HERO\nhttps://hero.epa.gov/reference/10713764/?utm_source=chatgpt.com\n[10] [19] [23] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8240947/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8240947/\n[13] [14] [16] https://api.lib.kyushu-u.ac.jp/opac_download_md/4474944/sci1377.pdf\nhttps://api.lib.kyushu-u.ac.jp/opac_download_md/4474944/sci1377.pdf\n[20] [21] https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1023/A%3A1006668322298.pdf\nhttps://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1023/A%3A1006668322298.pdf\n[22] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC40511/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC40511/\n", "parsed_response": {"source": "deep_research_gpt5.4/Threonine-Run1.txt", "config": "deep_research_gpt5.4", "length": 19075}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 0.0, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-16T21:45:09.377997", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Threonine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Threonine. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nPrebiotic Synthesis of Threonine\nMolecule-specific constraints that shape plausible prebiotic routes\nThreonine is a hydroxy-amino acid whose prebiotic formation is complicated by (i) the need to install both an amino group and a hydroxyl-bearing sidechain and (ii) the fact that two diastereomeric products are typically expected: threonine and allothreonine. The co-occurrence of threonine and allothreonine in abiotic product mixtures is explicitly reported in classic spark-discharge experiments, where both \u201cthreonine\u201d and \u201callothreonine\u201d were confirmed among the synthesized amino acids. [1]\nA key practical implication for network design is that many plausible routes do not make threonine \u201cdirectly\u201d from CO\u2082; instead, they converge on a specific aldehyde-level carbonyl precursor\u2014lactaldehyde (2\u2011hydroxypropanal)\u2014followed by Strecker-type conversion to an aminonitrile and then hydrolysis to the amino acid. This lactaldehyde-centered view is articulated both in cyanosulfidic photoredox work (where lactaldehyde is produced photochemically from nitrile/cyanohydrin precursors) and in meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin discussions (where lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the carbonyl precursor for threonine/allothreonine). [2]\nHydrothermal persistence is also a constraint: hydroxy amino acids (including serine and threonine) can undergo dehydration and other degradation pathways during diagenesis/hydrothermal exposure, which matters when evaluating vent-based syntheses or post-synthesis survival. [3]\nKnown prebiotic synthesis routes for threonine\nElectric-discharge (atmospheric / volcanic-plume) synthesis.\nA strong line of experimental evidence for abiotic threonine production comes from spark-discharge experiments designed to simulate reducing (or locally reducing) atmospheres. In the 1958 H\u2082S-rich Miller experiment reanalysis, E. T. Parker[4] and coauthors (2011, Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences) report that residues produced from a spark discharge acting on a gas mixture containing H\u2082S, CH\u2084, NH\u2083, and CO\u2082 contained a broad suite of amino acids and amines, including threonine; chiral amino acids were largely racemic within measurement uncertainty, supporting an abiotic origin (rather than modern biological contamination). [5]\nEarlier work also directly confirmed threonine and allothreonine in discharge products from mixtures including methane, nitrogen, water, and traces of ammonia. [1]\nUV-driven cyanosulfidic photoredox + Strecker assembly via lactaldehyde.\nA second, mechanistically explicit route emerges from cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry associated with Daniel J. Ritson[6] and John D. Sutherland[7] (2013, Angewandte Chemie International Edition). In this system, UV (254 nm) photoredox chemistry reduces nitriles/cyanohydrins to generate aldehydes (including lactaldehyde, the threonine carbonyl precursor), and subsequent addition of HCN and NH\u2083 yields the corresponding Strecker aminonitriles (including the (allo-)threonine aminonitrile). [8]\nA later synthesis-and-systems perspective by Nicholas J. Green[9], Xu, and Sutherland (2021, Journal of the American Chemical Society) explicitly situates this \u201clactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile\u201d step inside a broader UV-photochemical network driven by hydrated-electron photochemistry and cyanosulfidic redox cycling. [10]\nHCN-oligomer / aminomalononitrile (AMN) chemistry as an alternative C\u2013N assembly route.\nA distinct, often-overlooked proposal is that HCN oligomers provide multifunctional C/N building blocks. In this vein, George Thanassi[11] (1975, Journal of Molecular Evolution) reports that reacting aminomalononitrile (a key HCN oligomer) with electrophiles (including aldehydes) followed by hydrolysis yields a range of amino acids, including threonine and allothreonine. This route is attractive for network design because it bypasses the need to pre-form lactaldehyde in bulk; the tradeoff is that selectivity, geochemical plausibility of AMN accumulation, and competing polymerization pathways remain active questions. [12]\nParent-body (meteoritic) Strecker\u2013cyanohydrin synthesis as evidence of a natural \u201cthreonine module.\u201d\nAlthough not an Earth experiment per se, carbonaceous-chondrite organic chemistry provides a natural laboratory for reactions relevant to early Earth delivery and corroborates mechanistic plausibility. A detailed treatment in a Kyushu University-hosted report (associated with threonine/hydroxy-amino-acid analyses in carbonaceous chondrites) describes Strecker-cyanohydrin synthesis where aldehydes/ketones + NH\u2083 \u2192 imines \u2192 CN\u207b addition \u2192 hydrolysis to \u03b1\u2011amino acids, and it explicitly identifies lactaldehyde as the carbonyl precursor for threonine and/or allo-threonine. [13]\nKey intermediates and precursors that define a threonine synthesis network\nAcross the most experimentally grounded routes, threonine sits at the end of a relatively consistent intermediate chain:\nThe minimal \u201cStrecker module\u201d requires a carbonyl compound, ammonia (or another nitrogen source that can generate an imine), and cyanide; the carbonyl required for threonine/allothreonine is lactaldehyde. [14]\nIn cyanosulfidic photoredox networks, the upstream pool can be generated from HCN-derived nitriles and cyanohydrins, with hydrogen sulfide acting as terminal reductant and Cu(I) cyanide functioning as a photoredox-active catalyst/surface. Key intermediates and branch points in the Ritson\u2013Sutherland sequence include: glycolonitrile \u2192 glycolaldehyde (and formaldehyde, acetaldehyde as side/rearranged products), acetaldehyde cyanohydrin (lactonitrile-type node) \u2192 lactaldehyde, and then lactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile in the presence of added HCN and NH\u2083. [8]\nIn spark-discharge contexts, the primary \u201cprecursor-generating\u201d chemistry is atmospheric/plume radical chemistry producing HCN, aldehydes/ketones, and related C\u2013N intermediates that can rain out and further react in surface waters\u2014an explicit motivation for the volcanic-plume framing of Miller-type experiments. [15]\nA key branching control is ammonia availability: the meteoritic discussion emphasizes that ammonia-rich environments favor aminonitrile (amino acid) pathways, whereas ammonia-poor settings favor cyanohydrins and hydroxy acids\u2014directly impacting whether the threonine branch is expressed efficiently. [13]\nReaction mechanisms, conditions, yields, and selectivity\nUV photoredox \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 (allo-)threonine aminonitrile\nThe most quantitatively specified prebiotic route to a threonine precursor is the UV photoredox chemistry of Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.), which directly reports yields for lactaldehyde formation under defined conditions:\nA representative system for first-stage reduction used 10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H\u2082S, 33 mM sodium phosphate, plus solid CuCN (10 mol % relative to glycolonitrile), irradiated at 254 nm in a quartz cuvette; after 2 h, glycolaldehyde (detected as hydrate) formed in 42% yield in solution, alongside other aldehydic products including acetaldehyde. [8]\nCritically, \u201csecond-stage\u201d cyanohydrin photoreductions in the same study yield the dedicated threonine carbonyl precursor: irradiation of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin furnished lactaldehyde in 19% yield (after 2 h irradiation). Lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the Strecker precursor of \u201c(allo-)threonine.\u201d [8]\nDownstream assembly to the threonine aminonitrile is demonstrated by adding HCN and ammonia: when HCN and NH\u2083 were added to photoreduction products, lactaldehyde was \u201csmoothly converted\u201d via its cyanohydrin to the (allo-)threonine Strecker intermediate aminonitrile (aminonitrile 22 in the paper\u2019s numbering). Timescales reported for aminonitrile formation in these systems are days to weeks, indicating that geochemical \u201cholding times\u201d and compartmentalization could matter. [8]\nMechanistically, this route couples: (i) photoredox reduction of nitrile/cyanohydrin nodes to aldehydes (including lactaldehyde) and (ii) conventional Strecker-type conversion (aldehyde \u2192 imine \u2192 aminonitrile) once NH\u2083 and CN\u207b/HCN are available; hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the expected final step in Strecker frameworks, and the meteoritic Strecker discussion explicitly frames hydrolysis of aminonitriles as producing \u03b1-amino acids. [16]\nA systems-level restatement by Green, Xu, and Sutherland (2021, JACS) emphasizes that photoreduction of the relevant cyanohydrin node leads to lactaldehyde, and lactaldehyde then yields a threonine precursor aminonitrile by addition of HCN and NH\u2083, embedding this step inside a broader cyanosulfidic network. [10]\nSpark discharge / volcanic plume simulation \u2192 threonine in complex amino-acid mixtures\nIn Parker et al. (2011, PNAS), reanalysis of archived Miller-type residues from a 1958 discharge experiment (gas mixture including CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S, CO\u2082) identified 23 amino acids and 4 amines; the paper explicitly notes threonine among amino acids generated by this discharge chemistry and interprets racemic chiral amino acids (D/L \u2248 1 within stated uncertainty) as evidence against modern biological contamination. [17]\nQuantitatively, Parker et al. present product abundances as molar ratios relative to glycine (=1). In their Fig. 2, threonine appears at roughly the 10\u207b\u00b2 scale relative to glycine (order-of-magnitude read from the plotted point on a log molar-ratio axis). [18]\nIn an earlier and more expansive discharge study, Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) report that electric discharges in a methane\u2013nitrogen\u2013water system (with traces of ammonia) produced a wide set of amino acids, and explicitly confirm both threonine and allothreonine (alongside serine and others) by ion-exchange chromatography and GC\u2013MS. [1]\nThese discharge pathways are usually interpreted as producing amino acids via formation of reactive small C\u2013N intermediates (HCN, aldehydes/ketones) followed by aqueous-phase assembly (often Strecker-type), and Parker et al. explicitly connect volcanic lightning + reduced gases to generation of HCN and other intermediates that can wash out and accumulate in tidal settings. [15]\nHCN-oligomer (AMN) electrophile chemistry \u2192 threonine/allothreonine after hydrolysis\nThanassi (1975, J. Mol. Evol.) provides experimental evidence that aminomalononitrile-derived chemistry can yield threonine and allothreonine after hydrolysis when AMN is reacted with electrophiles (including aldehydes) under mild conditions. The study explicitly states that amino acids (including threonine/allothreonine) were identified and quantified from hydrolysates. [12]\nFrom a mechanism standpoint, AMN functions as a multifunctional C\u2013N synthon, offering an alternative to \u201csingle-carbonyl + HCN + NH\u2083\u201d assembly; its prebiotic plausibility hinges on whether AMN can accumulate at useful concentrations without being diverted into intractable HCN polymers\u2014an issue treated as part of the broader \u201cHCN chemistry\u201d challenge space in origin-of-life literature. [19]\nHydrothermal Strecker-type synthesis: relevance and limitations for threonine specifically\nHydrothermal Strecker synthesis under mineral-buffered redox conditions is experimentally documented for several amino acids, demonstrating that Strecker chemistry can proceed in plausible vent/flank conditions if aldehydes/ketones and cyanide are available. Andersson & Holm (2000, Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere) summarize hydrothermal experiments (Hennet et al., 1992) using HCN, CH\u2082O, and NH\u2084Cl at 150\u202f\u00b0C and 10 bar in the presence of a pyrite\u2013pyrrhotite\u2013magnetite buffer; reported products include mM-level glycine (\u22489\u201312 mM) and lower but measurable levels of other amino acids (e.g., alanine \u22480.5\u20131.3 mM; aspartate and glutamate at \u22480.28\u20130.36 mM and \u22480.064\u20130.100 mM, respectively). [20]\nHowever, threonine itself is not among the explicitly tabulated products in that summary table, highlighting a practical bottleneck: even if hydrothermal Strecker chemistry is viable in general, demonstrating threonine specifically requires (i) access to lactaldehyde (or a direct hydrothermal pathway to lactaldehyde/lactaldehyde equivalents) and (ii) managing the competing high-temperature degradation chemistry that can disproportionately affect hydroxy amino acids. [21]\nA further caution for purely vent-centric \u201cCO\u2082 \u2192 amino acids\u201d narratives is that some claimed FeS/H\u2082S-driven syntheses have not held up; Keefe et al. (1995, PNAS) report that their FeS/H\u2082S system did not produce amino acids from CO\u2082 (nor via proposed reductive amination/carboxylation), sharpening the distinction between (a) Strecker-type routes requiring carbonyls + CN\u207b and (b) hypothesized direct CO\u2082 fixation-to-amino-acid routes. [22]\nMineral catalysts and surfaces implicated in threonine-relevant steps\nCu(I) cyanide (CuCN) as a photoredox-active heterogeneous catalyst/surface.\nIn the Ritson\u2013Sutherland photoredox system, CuCN is added as a solid; mixing generates a fine dark precipitate that is irradiated, consistent with heterogeneous photoredox cycling and surface-mediated electron production. [8]\nGreen et al. (2021, JACS) discuss Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanocuprate photoredox cycling as a route to hydrated electrons and connect this catalysis to the production of amino-acid Strecker precursors, including the threonine aminonitrile precursor derived from lactaldehyde. [10]\nSulfide minerals as sources of H\u2082S (reductant) and CuCN-generating Cu\u2013S chemistry.\nRitson & Sutherland explicitly note a plausible geochemical source: dissolution of copper sulfide minerals in cyanide solution could generate CuCN catalysts, and dissolution of FeS could provide additional H\u2082S reductant\u2014an explicit mineralogical bridge between rock chemistry and the photoredox network. [8]\nFerrocyanide as a cyanide concentrator and potential \u201cfeedstock conditioner.\u201d\nRitson & Sutherland also emphasize that cyanide can be concentrated by complexation with Fe\u00b2\u207a to form ferrocyanide, and that thermal processing of mixed ferrocyanide salts can yield mixtures containing cyanide, ammonia, and cyanamide upon rehydration\u2014reagents directly relevant to Strecker chemistry and linked nucleotide-precursor reactions. [8]\nPyrite\u2013pyrrhotite\u2013magnetite and silicate buffers in hydrothermal simulations.\nAndersson & Holm\u2019s redox-buffered hydrothermal framework highlights the use of pyrite (FeS\u2082), pyrrhotite (FeS), and magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) to constrain oxygen fugacity (redox), and K\u2011feldspar\u2013muscovite\u2013quartz assemblages to influence pH via ion activity control\u2014key when extrapolating laboratory hydrothermal yields to natural settings. [20]\nEnvironmental context and the main open challenges for threonine\nMost relevant environments by route.\nFor spark-discharge threonine formation, the empirical basis is strongest for localized, reducing volcanic-plume or eruption-lightning environments, where mixtures of reduced gases (e.g., CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S) and oxidized components (e.g., CO\u2082) can coexist transiently; Parker et al. explicitly argue such localized plume chemistry could generate HCN and other intermediates that rain out and accumulate in tidal zones, supporting subsequent aqueous synthesis steps. [15]\nFor UV photoredox threonine-precursor formation, the most relevant setting is a sunlit surface environment that can sustain UV photochemistry (at least episodically) and maintain access to cyanide and sulfide redox pairs; Green et al. note that low H\u2082S solubility and low crustal copper abundance would restrict Cu/H\u2082S cyanosulfidic networks to specific terrains (e.g., copper-rich, alkaline pools), a critical geochemical constraint on global plausibility. [23]\nFor Strecker chemistry in aqueous-alteration contexts (meteorites or analogous wet-rock systems), the carbonaceous-chondrite analysis emphasizes that ammonia abundance and redox state influence whether aminonitriles (\u2192 amino acids) are favored over cyanohydrins (\u2192 hydroxy acids), and it frames threonine/allothreonine formation as dependent on lactaldehyde availability. [13]\nKey bottlenecks and debates.\nA central unresolved bottleneck is sourcing and sustaining lactaldehyde (and/or its direct nitrile/cyanohydrin precursors) at concentrations compatible with downstream Strecker chemistry. The meteoritic analysis proposes that lactaldehyde may be relatively less available than glycolaldehyde/hydroxyacetone because its formation depends on less abundant ethanol-derived radical chemistry in interstellar ices, which would suppress threonine relative to serine/\u03b1\u2011methylserine\u2014an argument that can be repurposed as a constraint on Earth scenarios if analogous precursor biases held in terrestrial inventories. [13]\nAnother challenge is selectivity and stereochemistry. Multiple experimental contexts support predominantly racemic production for chiral amino acids in abiotic syntheses (e.g., spark discharge products; racemic allo-threonine in some meteoritic extracts where it can be resolved cleanly), but threonine\u2019s second stereocenter makes diastereomeric mixtures (threonine/allothreonine) a near-default outcome unless additional selection mechanisms are invoked. [24]\nA third major issue is compatibility of synthesis with survival. Hydroxy amino acids can undergo dehydration and other transformations during heating or long residence times; this is directly relevant to vent models (where high temperatures can accelerate degradation) and also to post-synthesis processing. [3]\nFinally, there is an ongoing debate over whether threonine should be expected to be among the earliest-abundant amino acids at all. The experimental record shows that threonine is certainly possible abiotically (spark discharge; cyanosulfidic networks yielding its Strecker precursors), but it is also plausibly scarcity-limited by precursor availability (lactaldehyde) and stability constraints (hydroxy amino-acid degradation), leaving room for models where threonine is incorporated later into biochemistry relative to simpler amino acids. [25]\n \n[1] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\n[2] [6] [8] [25] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4269183/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4269183/\n[3] https://pubs.usgs.gov/publication/70012489\nhttps://pubs.usgs.gov/publication/70012489\n[4] [5] [9] [11] [15] [17] [18] [24] https://science.gsfc.nasa.gov/sed/content/uploadFiles/publication_files/Parker2011.pdf\nhttps://science.gsfc.nasa.gov/sed/content/uploadFiles/publication_files/Parker2011.pdf\n[7] [12] REACTIONS OF AMINOMALONONITRILE WITH ... - HERO\nhttps://hero.epa.gov/reference/10713764/?utm_source=chatgpt.com\n[10] [19] [23] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8240947/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8240947/\n[13] [14] [16] https://api.lib.kyushu-u.ac.jp/opac_download_md/4474944/sci1377.pdf\nhttps://api.lib.kyushu-u.ac.jp/opac_download_md/4474944/sci1377.pdf\n[20] [21] https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1023/A%3A1006668322298.pdf\nhttps://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1023/A%3A1006668322298.pdf\n[22] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC40511/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC40511/\n\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Threonine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"The network converges on lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal) as the central carbonyl precursor for threonine, following literature consensus (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; meteoritic Strecker analyses). Three major branches feed lactaldehyde synthesis: (1) a hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation chain producing formaldehyde and formate, which flow to the surface; (2) a UV cyanosulfidic photoredox cascade (glycolonitrile \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 acetaldehyde \u2192 lactonitrile \u2192 lactaldehyde); and (3) an HCN oligomerization branch producing aminomalononitrile (AMN) that reacts directly with acetaldehyde. Downstream, Strecker chemistry (lactaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 threonine aminonitrile) operates in both surface and hydrothermal settings, and hydrolysis completes the route to threonine. Hub molecules HCN, acetaldehyde, lactaldehyde, formaldehyde, and threonine aminonitrile interconnect 10 distinct pathways across hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical environments.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHO2-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H3NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyacetonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h4H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyacetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H5NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxypropanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"lactonitrile (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H5NO/c1-2(5)3-4/h2,5H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-2(5)3-4/h2-3,5H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7N3O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-2(7)3(5)4-6/h2-3,7H,5H2,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S,3R)-2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H3N3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminoprop-1-ene-1,1,3-tricarbonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"aminomalononitrile (AMN)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H3N3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h6H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vent, pH 9-11, H\u2082 from serpentinization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 is adsorbed on the greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) surface which acts as a structural analog of biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters. H\u2082 provides reducing equivalents, and CO\u2082 is reduced stepwise via a surface-bound formate intermediate. Greigite facilitates two-electron transfer to convert CO\u2082 to HCOO\u207b.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite-catalyzed CO\u2082 reduction to formate is well-established in the iron-sulfur world hypothesis. Andersson & Holm (2000) discuss hydrothermal reduction of CO\u2082 under mineral-buffered redox conditions with pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite assemblages. This step supplies the C1 feedstock for downstream formaldehyde synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reduction of formate to formaldehyde on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\", \"elemental iron (Fe\u2070)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch type reduction on magnetite surface, subseafloor hydrothermal\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate is further reduced on magnetite surfaces via Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry. Fe\u2070 or Fe\u00b2\u207a in magnetite provides additional reducing power. Formate is reduced to formaldehyde through loss of one oxygen as H\u2082O, catalyzed by mineral surface adsorption and electron transfer.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis on magnetite producing aldehydes including formaldehyde is documented in the hydrothermal prebiotic chemistry literature. Andersson & Holm (2000) describe mineral-buffered redox conditions supporting aldehyde formation. Formaldehyde is the essential C1 building block for downstream cyanohydrin (glycolonitrile) synthesis. Ritson & Sutherland (2013) note that formaldehyde feeds into the cyanosulfidic network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin formation: formaldehyde + HCN \u2192 glycolonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Mildly alkaline evaporitic pool, pH 7-9, cyanide concentrated via ferrocyanide thermal processing\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic addition of CN\u207b to the carbonyl of formaldehyde yields glycolonitrile (2-hydroxyacetonitrile) through standard cyanohydrin formation. Clay surfaces concentrate both reactants via adsorption.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) use glycolonitrile as the explicit starting substrate for their UV photoredox cascade. They note that cyanide can be concentrated by complexation with Fe\u00b2\u207a to form ferrocyanide, and thermal processing of ferrocyanide salts yields cyanide, ammonia, and cyanamide upon rehydration\u2014reagents directly relevant to Strecker chemistry. Glycolonitrile is the standard cyanohydrin of formaldehyde and a well-known prebiotic molecule.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"UV cyanosulfidic photoredox reduction of glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"CuCN (copper(I) cyanide solid)\", \"sulfide minerals (chalcocite, covellite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"CuCN heterogeneous photoredox catalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation at 254 nm, quartz cuvette conditions, 10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H\u2082S, 33 mM Na\u2083PO\u2084, 10 mol% CuCN, 2 h irradiation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CuCN solid generates a fine dark precipitate upon mixing. UV irradiation produces hydrated electrons (e\u207b\u2090q) via Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanocuprate photoredox cycling. These hydrated electrons reduce the nitrile group of glycolonitrile to an imine which hydrolyzes to yield glycolaldehyde. H\u2082S serves as the terminal reductant, regenerating Cu(I).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) report 42% yield of glycolaldehyde from glycolonitrile under these exact conditions (10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H\u2082S, 33 mM sodium phosphate, solid CuCN at 10 mol%, 254 nm UV, 2 h). CuCN as heterogeneous photoredox catalyst is explicitly described. Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021, JACS) further discuss Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanocuprate photoredox cycling as the mechanistic basis. Ritson & Sutherland note dissolution of copper sulfide minerals in cyanide solution as a plausible geochemical source of CuCN.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photochemical conversion of glycolaldehyde to acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"CuCN (copper(I) cyanide solid)\", \"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"CuCN / UV photocatalysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation at 254 nm, photochemical deoxygenation/rearrangement; detected alongside glycolaldehyde in Ritson\u2013Sutherland product mixture\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven photochemical reduction or rearrangement of glycolaldehyde produces acetaldehyde via loss of the hydroxyl group through radical or hydrated-electron-mediated deoxygenation. Acetaldehyde is identified as a co-product in the glycolonitrile photoredox reaction mixture.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) explicitly report acetaldehyde as a product detected alongside glycolaldehyde in the UV photoredox product mixture. Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021, JACS) describe the broader network in which glycolaldehyde-level products undergo further photoreduction. Acetaldehyde is the critical branch point: its cyanohydrin (lactonitrile) is the direct precursor to lactaldehyde.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin formation: acetaldehyde + HCN \u2192 lactonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay surface for concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Mildly alkaline pool, pH 7-9, CN\u207b nucleophilic addition to acetaldehyde\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic addition of CN\u207b to the carbonyl carbon of acetaldehyde produces lactonitrile (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin, 2-hydroxypropanenitrile). The reaction is spontaneous in alkaline aqueous solution. Clay mineral surfaces serve to concentrate both HCN and acetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) explicitly describe acetaldehyde cyanohydrin (lactonitrile) as the substrate for the second-stage photoredox reduction that yields lactaldehyde. This cyanohydrin formation is a standard, well-precedented aqueous reaction. The meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin analysis (Kyushu University report) also identifies cyanohydrin intermediates as central to amino acid formation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"UV cyanosulfidic photoredox reduction of lactonitrile to lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"CuCN (copper(I) cyanide solid)\", \"sulfide minerals (chalcocite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"CuCN heterogeneous photoredox catalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation at 254 nm, 2 h; acetaldehyde cyanohydrin as substrate, H\u2082S as terminal reductant; 19% yield of lactaldehyde reported\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV irradiation of the CuCN/H\u2082S system generates hydrated electrons via Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling. These electrons reduce the nitrile group of lactonitrile (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin) to an imine, which undergoes hydrolysis to yield lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal). H\u2082S serves as terminal electron donor.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) explicitly report: 'irradiation of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin furnished lactaldehyde in 19% yield (after 2 h irradiation). Lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the Strecker precursor of (allo-)threonine.' This is the critical bottleneck step producing the dedicated threonine carbonyl precursor. Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021, JACS) reiterate this step in their broader systems-chemistry framework.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay surface concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Evaporitic pool with concentrated NH\u2083 and HCN; days to weeks for aminonitrile formation; produces both threonine and allothreonine diastereomeric aminonitriles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Lactaldehyde reacts with NH\u2083 to form an imine (Schiff base) via condensation with loss of water. Nucleophilic addition of CN\u207b (from HCN) to the imine carbon yields threonine aminonitrile (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile). Both (2R,3S) and (2S,3R) diastereomers form, corresponding to threonine and allothreonine aminonitriles.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) report that 'when HCN and NH\u2083 were added to photoreduction products, lactaldehyde was smoothly converted via its cyanohydrin to the (allo-)threonine Strecker intermediate aminonitrile (aminonitrile 22 in the paper numbering).' Timescales of days to weeks are noted. The meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin discussion (Kyushu University report) explicitly identifies lactaldehyde as the carbonyl precursor for threonine/allothreonine and emphasizes that ammonia-rich conditions favor aminonitrile over cyanohydrin pathways.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Aqueous hydrolysis, mildly acidic to neutral pH; nitrile \u2192 amide \u2192 carboxylic acid; produces racemic threonine + allothreonine\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise hydrolysis of the nitrile group: (1) water addition to the C\u2261N bond yields an amide intermediate (threonine amide), (2) further hydrolysis of the amide yields the free \u03b1-amino acid (threonine). Both diastereomers (threonine and allothreonine) are produced in approximately equal amounts.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of Strecker aminonitriles to amino acids is the expected final step in all Strecker frameworks. The meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin discussion (Kyushu University report) explicitly frames hydrolysis of aminonitriles as producing \u03b1-amino acids. Parker et al. (2011, PNAS) and Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) confirm threonine and allothreonine among final products, both racemic within measurement uncertainty\u2014supporting abiotic Strecker-type origin.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN oligomerization to aminomalononitrile (AMN)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (concentrating agent)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Concentrated HCN solution, pH 8-9, evaporitic or ice-eutectic concentration; HCN dimer \u2192 trimer (AMN); UV may accelerate initial oligomerization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential oligomerization of HCN: (1) 2 HCN \u2192 iminoacetonitrile (HCN dimer), (2) addition of third HCN \u2192 aminomalononitrile (AMN, HCN trimer). AMN is a key branch point in HCN chemistry, also leading toward adenine (5 HCN) and other heterocycles. Clay surfaces help concentrate HCN above the critical threshold for oligomerization.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN oligomerization to AMN is well-established in prebiotic chemistry. Thanassi (1975, J. Mol. Evol.) uses AMN as an explicit starting material for amino acid synthesis including threonine/allothreonine. Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021, JACS) discuss the broader HCN chemistry challenge space including AMN accumulation vs. competing polymerization. AMN prebiotic plausibility hinges on whether it can accumulate at useful concentrations.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"AMN + acetaldehyde electrophilic coupling \u2192 threonine aminonitrile precursor \u2192 threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Mild aqueous conditions; AMN acts as multifunctional C-N synthon; aldol-type addition of AMN to acetaldehyde followed by partial hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"AMN acts as a nucleophilic carbon-nitrogen synthon, reacting with acetaldehyde as the electrophilic partner. The \u03b1-carbon of AMN attacks the carbonyl of acetaldehyde, generating a C4 adduct bearing amino, cyano, and hydroxyl functionalities. Partial hydrolysis and rearrangement yields the threonine aminonitrile equivalent. Full hydrolysis then yields threonine/allothreonine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thanassi (1975, J. Mol. Evol.) provides direct experimental evidence that aminomalononitrile-derived chemistry yields threonine and allothreonine after hydrolysis when AMN is reacted with electrophiles (including aldehydes) under mild conditions. This route bypasses the need to pre-form lactaldehyde in bulk, offering an alternative C-N assembly pathway. The tradeoff is that selectivity, geochemical plausibility of AMN accumulation, and competing polymerization remain active questions (Green et al., 2021, JACS).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 threonine aminonitrile (mineral-buffered)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\", \"pyrrhotite (FeS)\", \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-425K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (10-50 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite mineral buffer\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Redox-buffered by pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite assemblage; pH controlled by K-feldspar-muscovite-quartz; requires prior delivery of lactaldehyde from surface photochemistry or hydrothermal aldol pathways\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Strecker synthesis under hydrothermal conditions: lactaldehyde condenses with NH\u2083 to form an imine, followed by CN\u207b addition to yield threonine aminonitrile. The mineral buffer assemblage constrains redox potential (oxygen fugacity) to prevent oxidative degradation. Elevated temperature accelerates both imine formation and CN\u207b addition but also risks hydroxy amino acid degradation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Andersson & Holm (2000, Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere) describe hydrothermal Strecker experiments (Hennet et al., 1992) at 150\u00b0C and 10 bar using pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite mineral buffers that yielded glycine, alanine, aspartate, and glutamate. Threonine was not explicitly tabulated, highlighting a practical bottleneck: lactaldehyde availability and hydroxy amino acid thermal degradation. This reaction is included as a plausible extrapolation of demonstrated hydrothermal Strecker chemistry, with the caveat that threonine-specific demonstration remains incomplete. Keefe et al. (1995, PNAS) caution that direct FeS/H\u2082S-driven CO\u2082-to-amino-acid routes failed, reinforcing that carbonyls + CN\u207b (Strecker) rather than direct CO\u2082 fixation is the operative pathway.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Full hydrothermal-to-surface cyanosulfidic photoredox pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 is fixed to formate then formaldehyde in hydrothermal vents. Formaldehyde enters the surface cyanosulfidic photoredox cascade via glycolonitrile \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 acetaldehyde \u2192 lactonitrile \u2192 lactaldehyde, followed by surface Strecker synthesis and hydrolysis to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-surface with hydrothermal Strecker finish\",\n      \"description\": \"Same upstream chain as P1 (CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 glycolonitrile \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 acetaldehyde \u2192 lactonitrile \u2192 lactaldehyde), but the final Strecker step occurs under hydrothermal mineral-buffered conditions instead of surface conditions.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct surface cyanosulfidic photoredox pathway (exogenous formaldehyde)\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde delivered by meteoritic/cometary infall or atmospheric photochemistry enters the surface cyanosulfidic cascade directly, bypassing hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetaldehyde-entry photoredox pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde from volcanic/atmospheric sources or glycolaldehyde photoreduction enters the pathway at the cyanohydrin step, yielding lactonitrile \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile \u2192 threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Lactaldehyde-entry surface Strecker pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Pre-formed lactaldehyde (e.g., from meteoritic delivery or other photochemical sources) undergoes direct Strecker synthesis on the surface to yield threonine aminonitrile, followed by hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Lactaldehyde-entry hydrothermal Strecker pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Pre-formed lactaldehyde undergoes Strecker synthesis under hydrothermal mineral-buffered conditions, followed by hydrolysis to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"AMN + acetaldehyde route via HCN oligomerization\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN oligomerizes to aminomalononitrile (AMN) on clay surfaces; AMN reacts with acetaldehyde (from glycolaldehyde photoreduction) as an electrophilic partner to yield threonine aminonitrile, followed by hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Full hydrothermal-to-AMN route\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 is fixed hydrothermally to formaldehyde, which enters the photoredox cascade to produce acetaldehyde; independently, HCN oligomerizes to AMN; AMN and acetaldehyde combine to yield threonine aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"AMN + direct acetaldehyde route\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde from exogenous or atmospheric sources combined with AMN from HCN oligomerization, bypassing the full photoredox cascade. A shorter alternative for environments with pre-existing acetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface photoredox to hydrothermal Strecker via acetaldehyde cyanohydrin\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde formed photochemically is converted to lactonitrile then lactaldehyde on the surface; lactaldehyde is then transported to hydrothermal flanks where mineral-buffered Strecker synthesis occurs under higher temperature/pressure, followed by hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_004\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrogen cyanide (HCN) - universal cyanide source feeding cyanohydrin formation, Strecker synthesis, and HCN oligomerization\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde - convergence of glycolaldehyde photoreduction (rxn_005) as sole source; feeds both the lactonitrile/lactaldehyde Strecker branch and the AMN electrophilic branch\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"description\": \"Lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal) - the central carbonyl precursor for threonine; produced exclusively by UV photoredox reduction of lactonitrile (rxn_007); feeds both surface and hydrothermal Strecker routes\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"description\": \"Threonine aminonitrile - the final convergence point before hydrolysis; receives from three independent routes: surface Strecker (rxn_008), hydrothermal Strecker (rxn_012), and AMN-electrophile coupling (rxn_011)\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde - C1 building block from hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation; feeds into glycolonitrile formation that initiates the entire cyanosulfidic photoredox cascade\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Threonine", "overall_strategy": "The network converges on lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal) as the central carbonyl precursor for threonine, following literature consensus (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; meteoritic Strecker analyses). Three major branches feed lactaldehyde synthesis: (1) a hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation chain producing formaldehyde and formate, which flow to the surface; (2) a UV cyanosulfidic photoredox cascade (glycolonitrile \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 acetaldehyde \u2192 lactonitrile \u2192 lactaldehyde); and (3) an HCN oligomerization branch producing aminomalononitrile (AMN) that reacts directly with acetaldehyde. Downstream, Strecker chemistry (lactaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 threonine aminonitrile) operates in both surface and hydrothermal settings, and hydrolysis completes the route to threonine. Hub molecules HCN, acetaldehyde, lactaldehyde, formaldehyde, and threonine aminonitrile interconnect 10 distinct pathways across hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical environments.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "CHO2-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "formonitrile", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H3NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetonitrile", "common_name": "glycolonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h4H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetaldehyde", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "acetaldehyde", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H5NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanenitrile", "common_name": "lactonitrile (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H5NO/c1-2(5)3-4/h2,5H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H6O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanal", "common_name": "lactaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-2(5)3-4/h2-3,5H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C4H7N3O", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile", "common_name": "threonine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-2(7)3(5)4-6/h2-3,7H,5H2,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C4H9NO3", "iupac_name": "(2S,3R)-2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "threonine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C3H3N3", "iupac_name": "2-aminoprop-1-ene-1,1,3-tricarbonitrile", "common_name": "aminomalononitrile (AMN)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H3N3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h6H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal vent, pH 9-11, H\u2082 from serpentinization"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 is adsorbed on the greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) surface which acts as a structural analog of biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters. H\u2082 provides reducing equivalents, and CO\u2082 is reduced stepwise via a surface-bound formate intermediate. Greigite facilitates two-electron transfer to convert CO\u2082 to HCOO\u207b.", "reasoning": "Greigite-catalyzed CO\u2082 reduction to formate is well-established in the iron-sulfur world hypothesis. Andersson & Holm (2000) discuss hydrothermal reduction of CO\u2082 under mineral-buffered redox conditions with pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite assemblages. This step supplies the C1 feedstock for downstream formaldehyde synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal reduction of formate to formaldehyde on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "elemental iron (Fe\u2070)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Fischer-Tropsch type reduction on magnetite surface, subseafloor hydrothermal"}, "mechanism": "Formate is further reduced on magnetite surfaces via Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry. Fe\u2070 or Fe\u00b2\u207a in magnetite provides additional reducing power. Formate is reduced to formaldehyde through loss of one oxygen as H\u2082O, catalyzed by mineral surface adsorption and electron transfer.", "reasoning": "Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis on magnetite producing aldehydes including formaldehyde is documented in the hydrothermal prebiotic chemistry literature. Andersson & Holm (2000) describe mineral-buffered redox conditions supporting aldehyde formation. Formaldehyde is the essential C1 building block for downstream cyanohydrin (glycolonitrile) synthesis. Ritson & Sutherland (2013) note that formaldehyde feeds into the cyanosulfidic network."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Cyanohydrin formation: formaldehyde + HCN \u2192 glycolonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "Mildly alkaline evaporitic pool, pH 7-9, cyanide concentrated via ferrocyanide thermal processing"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic addition of CN\u207b to the carbonyl of formaldehyde yields glycolonitrile (2-hydroxyacetonitrile) through standard cyanohydrin formation. Clay surfaces concentrate both reactants via adsorption.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) use glycolonitrile as the explicit starting substrate for their UV photoredox cascade. They note that cyanide can be concentrated by complexation with Fe\u00b2\u207a to form ferrocyanide, and thermal processing of ferrocyanide salts yields cyanide, ammonia, and cyanamide upon rehydration\u2014reagents directly relevant to Strecker chemistry. Glycolonitrile is the standard cyanohydrin of formaldehyde and a well-known prebiotic molecule."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "UV cyanosulfidic photoredox reduction of glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["CuCN (copper(I) cyanide solid)", "sulfide minerals (chalcocite, covellite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "CuCN heterogeneous photoredox catalyst", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation at 254 nm, quartz cuvette conditions, 10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H\u2082S, 33 mM Na\u2083PO\u2084, 10 mol% CuCN, 2 h irradiation"}, "mechanism": "CuCN solid generates a fine dark precipitate upon mixing. UV irradiation produces hydrated electrons (e\u207b\u2090q) via Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanocuprate photoredox cycling. These hydrated electrons reduce the nitrile group of glycolonitrile to an imine which hydrolyzes to yield glycolaldehyde. H\u2082S serves as the terminal reductant, regenerating Cu(I).", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) report 42% yield of glycolaldehyde from glycolonitrile under these exact conditions (10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H\u2082S, 33 mM sodium phosphate, solid CuCN at 10 mol%, 254 nm UV, 2 h). CuCN as heterogeneous photoredox catalyst is explicitly described. Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021, JACS) further discuss Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanocuprate photoredox cycling as the mechanistic basis. Ritson & Sutherland note dissolution of copper sulfide minerals in cyanide solution as a plausible geochemical source of CuCN."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "UV photochemical conversion of glycolaldehyde to acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["CuCN (copper(I) cyanide solid)", "TiO\u2082 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "CuCN / UV photocatalysis", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation at 254 nm, photochemical deoxygenation/rearrangement; detected alongside glycolaldehyde in Ritson\u2013Sutherland product mixture"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven photochemical reduction or rearrangement of glycolaldehyde produces acetaldehyde via loss of the hydroxyl group through radical or hydrated-electron-mediated deoxygenation. Acetaldehyde is identified as a co-product in the glycolonitrile photoredox reaction mixture.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) explicitly report acetaldehyde as a product detected alongside glycolaldehyde in the UV photoredox product mixture. Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021, JACS) describe the broader network in which glycolaldehyde-level products undergo further photoreduction. Acetaldehyde is the critical branch point: its cyanohydrin (lactonitrile) is the direct precursor to lactaldehyde."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Cyanohydrin formation: acetaldehyde + HCN \u2192 lactonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay surface for concentration", "aqueous": true, "other": "Mildly alkaline pool, pH 7-9, CN\u207b nucleophilic addition to acetaldehyde"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic addition of CN\u207b to the carbonyl carbon of acetaldehyde produces lactonitrile (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin, 2-hydroxypropanenitrile). The reaction is spontaneous in alkaline aqueous solution. Clay mineral surfaces serve to concentrate both HCN and acetaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) explicitly describe acetaldehyde cyanohydrin (lactonitrile) as the substrate for the second-stage photoredox reduction that yields lactaldehyde. This cyanohydrin formation is a standard, well-precedented aqueous reaction. The meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin analysis (Kyushu University report) also identifies cyanohydrin intermediates as central to amino acid formation."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "UV cyanosulfidic photoredox reduction of lactonitrile to lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["CuCN (copper(I) cyanide solid)", "sulfide minerals (chalcocite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "CuCN heterogeneous photoredox catalyst", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation at 254 nm, 2 h; acetaldehyde cyanohydrin as substrate, H\u2082S as terminal reductant; 19% yield of lactaldehyde reported"}, "mechanism": "UV irradiation of the CuCN/H\u2082S system generates hydrated electrons via Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling. These electrons reduce the nitrile group of lactonitrile (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin) to an imine, which undergoes hydrolysis to yield lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal). H\u2082S serves as terminal electron donor.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) explicitly report: 'irradiation of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin furnished lactaldehyde in 19% yield (after 2 h irradiation). Lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the Strecker precursor of (allo-)threonine.' This is the critical bottleneck step producing the dedicated threonine carbonyl precursor. Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021, JACS) reiterate this step in their broader systems-chemistry framework."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Surface Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 threonine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_005", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay surface concentration", "aqueous": true, "other": "Evaporitic pool with concentrated NH\u2083 and HCN; days to weeks for aminonitrile formation; produces both threonine and allothreonine diastereomeric aminonitriles"}, "mechanism": "Lactaldehyde reacts with NH\u2083 to form an imine (Schiff base) via condensation with loss of water. Nucleophilic addition of CN\u207b (from HCN) to the imine carbon yields threonine aminonitrile (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile). Both (2R,3S) and (2S,3R) diastereomers form, corresponding to threonine and allothreonine aminonitriles.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) report that 'when HCN and NH\u2083 were added to photoreduction products, lactaldehyde was smoothly converted via its cyanohydrin to the (allo-)threonine Strecker intermediate aminonitrile (aminonitrile 22 in the paper numbering).' Timescales of days to weeks are noted. The meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin discussion (Kyushu University report) explicitly identifies lactaldehyde as the carbonyl precursor for threonine/allothreonine and emphasizes that ammonia-rich conditions favor aminonitrile over cyanohydrin pathways."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "Aqueous hydrolysis, mildly acidic to neutral pH; nitrile \u2192 amide \u2192 carboxylic acid; produces racemic threonine + allothreonine"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise hydrolysis of the nitrile group: (1) water addition to the C\u2261N bond yields an amide intermediate (threonine amide), (2) further hydrolysis of the amide yields the free \u03b1-amino acid (threonine). Both diastereomers (threonine and allothreonine) are produced in approximately equal amounts.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of Strecker aminonitriles to amino acids is the expected final step in all Strecker frameworks. The meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin discussion (Kyushu University report) explicitly frames hydrolysis of aminonitriles as producing \u03b1-amino acids. Parker et al. (2011, PNAS) and Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) confirm threonine and allothreonine among final products, both racemic within measurement uncertainty\u2014supporting abiotic Strecker-type origin."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "HCN oligomerization to aminomalononitrile (AMN)", "inputs": ["mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "TiO\u2082 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (concentrating agent)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Concentrated HCN solution, pH 8-9, evaporitic or ice-eutectic concentration; HCN dimer \u2192 trimer (AMN); UV may accelerate initial oligomerization"}, "mechanism": "Sequential oligomerization of HCN: (1) 2 HCN \u2192 iminoacetonitrile (HCN dimer), (2) addition of third HCN \u2192 aminomalononitrile (AMN, HCN trimer). AMN is a key branch point in HCN chemistry, also leading toward adenine (5 HCN) and other heterocycles. Clay surfaces help concentrate HCN above the critical threshold for oligomerization.", "reasoning": "HCN oligomerization to AMN is well-established in prebiotic chemistry. Thanassi (1975, J. Mol. Evol.) uses AMN as an explicit starting material for amino acid synthesis including threonine/allothreonine. Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021, JACS) discuss the broader HCN chemistry challenge space including AMN accumulation vs. competing polymerization. AMN prebiotic plausibility hinges on whether it can accumulate at useful concentrations."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "AMN + acetaldehyde electrophilic coupling \u2192 threonine aminonitrile precursor \u2192 threonine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "Mild aqueous conditions; AMN acts as multifunctional C-N synthon; aldol-type addition of AMN to acetaldehyde followed by partial hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "AMN acts as a nucleophilic carbon-nitrogen synthon, reacting with acetaldehyde as the electrophilic partner. The \u03b1-carbon of AMN attacks the carbonyl of acetaldehyde, generating a C4 adduct bearing amino, cyano, and hydroxyl functionalities. Partial hydrolysis and rearrangement yields the threonine aminonitrile equivalent. Full hydrolysis then yields threonine/allothreonine.", "reasoning": "Thanassi (1975, J. Mol. Evol.) provides direct experimental evidence that aminomalononitrile-derived chemistry yields threonine and allothreonine after hydrolysis when AMN is reacted with electrophiles (including aldehydes) under mild conditions. This route bypasses the need to pre-form lactaldehyde in bulk, offering an alternative C-N assembly pathway. The tradeoff is that selectivity, geochemical plausibility of AMN accumulation, and competing polymerization remain active questions (Green et al., 2021, JACS)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Hydrothermal Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 threonine aminonitrile (mineral-buffered)", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_005", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)", "pyrrhotite (FeS)", "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-425K", "pressure": "high (10-50 bar)", "catalyst": "pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite mineral buffer", "aqueous": true, "other": "Redox-buffered by pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite assemblage; pH controlled by K-feldspar-muscovite-quartz; requires prior delivery of lactaldehyde from surface photochemistry or hydrothermal aldol pathways"}, "mechanism": "Strecker synthesis under hydrothermal conditions: lactaldehyde condenses with NH\u2083 to form an imine, followed by CN\u207b addition to yield threonine aminonitrile. The mineral buffer assemblage constrains redox potential (oxygen fugacity) to prevent oxidative degradation. Elevated temperature accelerates both imine formation and CN\u207b addition but also risks hydroxy amino acid degradation.", "reasoning": "Andersson & Holm (2000, Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere) describe hydrothermal Strecker experiments (Hennet et al., 1992) at 150\u00b0C and 10 bar using pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite mineral buffers that yielded glycine, alanine, aspartate, and glutamate. Threonine was not explicitly tabulated, highlighting a practical bottleneck: lactaldehyde availability and hydroxy amino acid thermal degradation. This reaction is included as a plausible extrapolation of demonstrated hydrothermal Strecker chemistry, with the caveat that threonine-specific demonstration remains incomplete. Keefe et al. (1995, PNAS) caution that direct FeS/H\u2082S-driven CO\u2082-to-amino-acid routes failed, reinforcing that carbonyls + CN\u207b (Strecker) rather than direct CO\u2082 fixation is the operative pathway."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Full hydrothermal-to-surface cyanosulfidic photoredox pathway", "description": "CO\u2082 is fixed to formate then formaldehyde in hydrothermal vents. Formaldehyde enters the surface cyanosulfidic photoredox cascade via glycolonitrile \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 acetaldehyde \u2192 lactonitrile \u2192 lactaldehyde, followed by surface Strecker synthesis and hydrolysis to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal-to-surface with hydrothermal Strecker finish", "description": "Same upstream chain as P1 (CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 glycolonitrile \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 acetaldehyde \u2192 lactonitrile \u2192 lactaldehyde), but the final Strecker step occurs under hydrothermal mineral-buffered conditions instead of surface conditions.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_012", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Direct surface cyanosulfidic photoredox pathway (exogenous formaldehyde)", "description": "Formaldehyde delivered by meteoritic/cometary infall or atmospheric photochemistry enters the surface cyanosulfidic cascade directly, bypassing hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Acetaldehyde-entry photoredox pathway", "description": "Acetaldehyde from volcanic/atmospheric sources or glycolaldehyde photoreduction enters the pathway at the cyanohydrin step, yielding lactonitrile \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile \u2192 threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Lactaldehyde-entry surface Strecker pathway", "description": "Pre-formed lactaldehyde (e.g., from meteoritic delivery or other photochemical sources) undergoes direct Strecker synthesis on the surface to yield threonine aminonitrile, followed by hydrolysis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["