r as hub intermediates without production reactions\u2014the network should show their genesis (e.g., volcanic HCN, thermal decomposition of ferrocyanide); (2) rxn_005 (glycolaldehyde \u2192 acetaldehyde) lacks a clean mechanistic pathway and is a bottleneck in 6 of 10 pathways; (3) the AMN + acetaldehyde coupling mechanism (rxn_011) needs elaboration. Formaldehyde's designation as a hub is marginal (degree 2). Overall, the network is chemically credible, well-connected, and achieves the target through multiple validated routes.", "approved": true, "hub_quality": 0.82, "convergence_quality": 0.88}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 281057.44194984436, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-16T21:56:17.032486", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Threonine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Threonine. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nPrebiotic Synthesis of Threonine\nMolecule-specific constraints that shape plausible prebiotic routes\nThreonine is a hydroxy-amino acid whose prebiotic formation is complicated by (i) the need to install both an amino group and a hydroxyl-bearing sidechain and (ii) the fact that two diastereomeric products are typically expected: threonine and allothreonine. The co-occurrence of threonine and allothreonine in abiotic product mixtures is explicitly reported in classic spark-discharge experiments, where both \u201cthreonine\u201d and \u201callothreonine\u201d were confirmed among the synthesized amino acids. [1]\nA key practical implication for network design is that many plausible routes do not make threonine \u201cdirectly\u201d from CO\u2082; instead, they converge on a specific aldehyde-level carbonyl precursor\u2014lactaldehyde (2\u2011hydroxypropanal)\u2014followed by Strecker-type conversion to an aminonitrile and then hydrolysis to the amino acid. This lactaldehyde-centered view is articulated both in cyanosulfidic photoredox work (where lactaldehyde is produced photochemically from nitrile/cyanohydrin precursors) and in meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin discussions (where lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the carbonyl precursor for threonine/allothreonine). [2]\nHydrothermal persistence is also a constraint: hydroxy amino acids (including serine and threonine) can undergo dehydration and other degradation pathways during diagenesis/hydrothermal exposure, which matters when evaluating vent-based syntheses or post-synthesis survival. [3]\nKnown prebiotic synthesis routes for threonine\nElectric-discharge (atmospheric / volcanic-plume) synthesis.\nA strong line of experimental evidence for abiotic threonine production comes from spark-discharge experiments designed to simulate reducing (or locally reducing) atmospheres. In the 1958 H\u2082S-rich Miller experiment reanalysis, E. T. Parker[4] and coauthors (2011, Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences) report that residues produced from a spark discharge acting on a gas mixture containing H\u2082S, CH\u2084, NH\u2083, and CO\u2082 contained a broad suite of amino acids and amines, including threonine; chiral amino acids were largely racemic within measurement uncertainty, supporting an abiotic origin (rather than modern biological contamination). [5]\nEarlier work also directly confirmed threonine and allothreonine in discharge products from mixtures including methane, nitrogen, water, and traces of ammonia. [1]\nUV-driven cyanosulfidic photoredox + Strecker assembly via lactaldehyde.\nA second, mechanistically explicit route emerges from cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry associated with Daniel J. Ritson[6] and John D. Sutherland[7] (2013, Angewandte Chemie International Edition). In this system, UV (254 nm) photoredox chemistry reduces nitriles/cyanohydrins to generate aldehydes (including lactaldehyde, the threonine carbonyl precursor), and subsequent addition of HCN and NH\u2083 yields the corresponding Strecker aminonitriles (including the (allo-)threonine aminonitrile). [8]\nA later synthesis-and-systems perspective by Nicholas J. Green[9], Xu, and Sutherland (2021, Journal of the American Chemical Society) explicitly situates this \u201clactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile\u201d step inside a broader UV-photochemical network driven by hydrated-electron photochemistry and cyanosulfidic redox cycling. [10]\nHCN-oligomer / aminomalononitrile (AMN) chemistry as an alternative C\u2013N assembly route.\nA distinct, often-overlooked proposal is that HCN oligomers provide multifunctional C/N building blocks. In this vein, George Thanassi[11] (1975, Journal of Molecular Evolution) reports that reacting aminomalononitrile (a key HCN oligomer) with electrophiles (including aldehydes) followed by hydrolysis yields a range of amino acids, including threonine and allothreonine. This route is attractive for network design because it bypasses the need to pre-form lactaldehyde in bulk; the tradeoff is that selectivity, geochemical plausibility of AMN accumulation, and competing polymerization pathways remain active questions. [12]\nParent-body (meteoritic) Strecker\u2013cyanohydrin synthesis as evidence of a natural \u201cthreonine module.\u201d\nAlthough not an Earth experiment per se, carbonaceous-chondrite organic chemistry provides a natural laboratory for reactions relevant to early Earth delivery and corroborates mechanistic plausibility. A detailed treatment in a Kyushu University-hosted report (associated with threonine/hydroxy-amino-acid analyses in carbonaceous chondrites) describes Strecker-cyanohydrin synthesis where aldehydes/ketones + NH\u2083 \u2192 imines \u2192 CN\u207b addition \u2192 hydrolysis to \u03b1\u2011amino acids, and it explicitly identifies lactaldehyde as the carbonyl precursor for threonine and/or allo-threonine. [13]\nKey intermediates and precursors that define a threonine synthesis network\nAcross the most experimentally grounded routes, threonine sits at the end of a relatively consistent intermediate chain:\nThe minimal \u201cStrecker module\u201d requires a carbonyl compound, ammonia (or another nitrogen source that can generate an imine), and cyanide; the carbonyl required for threonine/allothreonine is lactaldehyde. [14]\nIn cyanosulfidic photoredox networks, the upstream pool can be generated from HCN-derived nitriles and cyanohydrins, with hydrogen sulfide acting as terminal reductant and Cu(I) cyanide functioning as a photoredox-active catalyst/surface. Key intermediates and branch points in the Ritson\u2013Sutherland sequence include: glycolonitrile \u2192 glycolaldehyde (and formaldehyde, acetaldehyde as side/rearranged products), acetaldehyde cyanohydrin (lactonitrile-type node) \u2192 lactaldehyde, and then lactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile in the presence of added HCN and NH\u2083. [8]\nIn spark-discharge contexts, the primary \u201cprecursor-generating\u201d chemistry is atmospheric/plume radical chemistry producing HCN, aldehydes/ketones, and related C\u2013N intermediates that can rain out and further react in surface waters\u2014an explicit motivation for the volcanic-plume framing of Miller-type experiments. [15]\nA key branching control is ammonia availability: the meteoritic discussion emphasizes that ammonia-rich environments favor aminonitrile (amino acid) pathways, whereas ammonia-poor settings favor cyanohydrins and hydroxy acids\u2014directly impacting whether the threonine branch is expressed efficiently. [13]\nReaction mechanisms, conditions, yields, and selectivity\nUV photoredox \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 (allo-)threonine aminonitrile\nThe most quantitatively specified prebiotic route to a threonine precursor is the UV photoredox chemistry of Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.), which directly reports yields for lactaldehyde formation under defined conditions:\nA representative system for first-stage reduction used 10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H\u2082S, 33 mM sodium phosphate, plus solid CuCN (10 mol % relative to glycolonitrile), irradiated at 254 nm in a quartz cuvette; after 2 h, glycolaldehyde (detected as hydrate) formed in 42% yield in solution, alongside other aldehydic products including acetaldehyde. [8]\nCritically, \u201csecond-stage\u201d cyanohydrin photoreductions in the same study yield the dedicated threonine carbonyl precursor: irradiation of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin furnished lactaldehyde in 19% yield (after 2 h irradiation). Lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the Strecker precursor of \u201c(allo-)threonine.\u201d [8]\nDownstream assembly to the threonine aminonitrile is demonstrated by adding HCN and ammonia: when HCN and NH\u2083 were added to photoreduction products, lactaldehyde was \u201csmoothly converted\u201d via its cyanohydrin to the (allo-)threonine Strecker intermediate aminonitrile (aminonitrile 22 in the paper\u2019s numbering). Timescales reported for aminonitrile formation in these systems are days to weeks, indicating that geochemical \u201cholding times\u201d and compartmentalization could matter. [8]\nMechanistically, this route couples: (i) photoredox reduction of nitrile/cyanohydrin nodes to aldehydes (including lactaldehyde) and (ii) conventional Strecker-type conversion (aldehyde \u2192 imine \u2192 aminonitrile) once NH\u2083 and CN\u207b/HCN are available; hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the expected final step in Strecker frameworks, and the meteoritic Strecker discussion explicitly frames hydrolysis of aminonitriles as producing \u03b1-amino acids. [16]\nA systems-level restatement by Green, Xu, and Sutherland (2021, JACS) emphasizes that photoreduction of the relevant cyanohydrin node leads to lactaldehyde, and lactaldehyde then yields a threonine precursor aminonitrile by addition of HCN and NH\u2083, embedding this step inside a broader cyanosulfidic network. [10]\nSpark discharge / volcanic plume simulation \u2192 threonine in complex amino-acid mixtures\nIn Parker et al. (2011, PNAS), reanalysis of archived Miller-type residues from a 1958 discharge experiment (gas mixture including CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S, CO\u2082) identified 23 amino acids and 4 amines; the paper explicitly notes threonine among amino acids generated by this discharge chemistry and interprets racemic chiral amino acids (D/L \u2248 1 within stated uncertainty) as evidence against modern biological contamination. [17]\nQuantitatively, Parker et al. present product abundances as molar ratios relative to glycine (=1). In their Fig. 2, threonine appears at roughly the 10\u207b\u00b2 scale relative to glycine (order-of-magnitude read from the plotted point on a log molar-ratio axis). [18]\nIn an earlier and more expansive discharge study, Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) report that electric discharges in a methane\u2013nitrogen\u2013water system (with traces of ammonia) produced a wide set of amino acids, and explicitly confirm both threonine and allothreonine (alongside serine and others) by ion-exchange chromatography and GC\u2013MS. [1]\nThese discharge pathways are usually interpreted as producing amino acids via formation of reactive small C\u2013N intermediates (HCN, aldehydes/ketones) followed by aqueous-phase assembly (often Strecker-type), and Parker et al. explicitly connect volcanic lightning + reduced gases to generation of HCN and other intermediates that can wash out and accumulate in tidal settings. [15]\nHCN-oligomer (AMN) electrophile chemistry \u2192 threonine/allothreonine after hydrolysis\nThanassi (1975, J. Mol. Evol.) provides experimental evidence that aminomalononitrile-derived chemistry can yield threonine and allothreonine after hydrolysis when AMN is reacted with electrophiles (including aldehydes) under mild conditions. The study explicitly states that amino acids (including threonine/allothreonine) were identified and quantified from hydrolysates. [12]\nFrom a mechanism standpoint, AMN functions as a multifunctional C\u2013N synthon, offering an alternative to \u201csingle-carbonyl + HCN + NH\u2083\u201d assembly; its prebiotic plausibility hinges on whether AMN can accumulate at useful concentrations without being diverted into intractable HCN polymers\u2014an issue treated as part of the broader \u201cHCN chemistry\u201d challenge space in origin-of-life literature. [19]\nHydrothermal Strecker-type synthesis: relevance and limitations for threonine specifically\nHydrothermal Strecker synthesis under mineral-buffered redox conditions is experimentally documented for several amino acids, demonstrating that Strecker chemistry can proceed in plausible vent/flank conditions if aldehydes/ketones and cyanide are available. Andersson & Holm (2000, Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere) summarize hydrothermal experiments (Hennet et al., 1992) using HCN, CH\u2082O, and NH\u2084Cl at 150\u202f\u00b0C and 10 bar in the presence of a pyrite\u2013pyrrhotite\u2013magnetite buffer; reported products include mM-level glycine (\u22489\u201312 mM) and lower but measurable levels of other amino acids (e.g., alanine \u22480.5\u20131.3 mM; aspartate and glutamate at \u22480.28\u20130.36 mM and \u22480.064\u20130.100 mM, respectively). [20]\nHowever, threonine itself is not among the explicitly tabulated products in that summary table, highlighting a practical bottleneck: even if hydrothermal Strecker chemistry is viable in general, demonstrating threonine specifically requires (i) access to lactaldehyde (or a direct hydrothermal pathway to lactaldehyde/lactaldehyde equivalents) and (ii) managing the competing high-temperature degradation chemistry that can disproportionately affect hydroxy amino acids. [21]\nA further caution for purely vent-centric \u201cCO\u2082 \u2192 amino acids\u201d narratives is that some claimed FeS/H\u2082S-driven syntheses have not held up; Keefe et al. (1995, PNAS) report that their FeS/H\u2082S system did not produce amino acids from CO\u2082 (nor via proposed reductive amination/carboxylation), sharpening the distinction between (a) Strecker-type routes requiring carbonyls + CN\u207b and (b) hypothesized direct CO\u2082 fixation-to-amino-acid routes. [22]\nMineral catalysts and surfaces implicated in threonine-relevant steps\nCu(I) cyanide (CuCN) as a photoredox-active heterogeneous catalyst/surface.\nIn the Ritson\u2013Sutherland photoredox system, CuCN is added as a solid; mixing generates a fine dark precipitate that is irradiated, consistent with heterogeneous photoredox cycling and surface-mediated electron production. [8]\nGreen et al. (2021, JACS) discuss Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanocuprate photoredox cycling as a route to hydrated electrons and connect this catalysis to the production of amino-acid Strecker precursors, including the threonine aminonitrile precursor derived from lactaldehyde. [10]\nSulfide minerals as sources of H\u2082S (reductant) and CuCN-generating Cu\u2013S chemistry.\nRitson & Sutherland explicitly note a plausible geochemical source: dissolution of copper sulfide minerals in cyanide solution could generate CuCN catalysts, and dissolution of FeS could provide additional H\u2082S reductant\u2014an explicit mineralogical bridge between rock chemistry and the photoredox network. [8]\nFerrocyanide as a cyanide concentrator and potential \u201cfeedstock conditioner.\u201d\nRitson & Sutherland also emphasize that cyanide can be concentrated by complexation with Fe\u00b2\u207a to form ferrocyanide, and that thermal processing of mixed ferrocyanide salts can yield mixtures containing cyanide, ammonia, and cyanamide upon rehydration\u2014reagents directly relevant to Strecker chemistry and linked nucleotide-precursor reactions. [8]\nPyrite\u2013pyrrhotite\u2013magnetite and silicate buffers in hydrothermal simulations.\nAndersson & Holm\u2019s redox-buffered hydrothermal framework highlights the use of pyrite (FeS\u2082), pyrrhotite (FeS), and magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) to constrain oxygen fugacity (redox), and K\u2011feldspar\u2013muscovite\u2013quartz assemblages to influence pH via ion activity control\u2014key when extrapolating laboratory hydrothermal yields to natural settings. [20]\nEnvironmental context and the main open challenges for threonine\nMost relevant environments by route.\nFor spark-discharge threonine formation, the empirical basis is strongest for localized, reducing volcanic-plume or eruption-lightning environments, where mixtures of reduced gases (e.g., CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S) and oxidized components (e.g., CO\u2082) can coexist transiently; Parker et al. explicitly argue such localized plume chemistry could generate HCN and other intermediates that rain out and accumulate in tidal zones, supporting subsequent aqueous synthesis steps. [15]\nFor UV photoredox threonine-precursor formation, the most relevant setting is a sunlit surface environment that can sustain UV photochemistry (at least episodically) and maintain access to cyanide and sulfide redox pairs; Green et al. note that low H\u2082S solubility and low crustal copper abundance would restrict Cu/H\u2082S cyanosulfidic networks to specific terrains (e.g., copper-rich, alkaline pools), a critical geochemical constraint on global plausibility. [23]\nFor Strecker chemistry in aqueous-alteration contexts (meteorites or analogous wet-rock systems), the carbonaceous-chondrite analysis emphasizes that ammonia abundance and redox state influence whether aminonitriles (\u2192 amino acids) are favored over cyanohydrins (\u2192 hydroxy acids), and it frames threonine/allothreonine formation as dependent on lactaldehyde availability. [13]\nKey bottlenecks and debates.\nA central unresolved bottleneck is sourcing and sustaining lactaldehyde (and/or its direct nitrile/cyanohydrin precursors) at concentrations compatible with downstream Strecker chemistry. The meteoritic analysis proposes that lactaldehyde may be relatively less available than glycolaldehyde/hydroxyacetone because its formation depends on less abundant ethanol-derived radical chemistry in interstellar ices, which would suppress threonine relative to serine/\u03b1\u2011methylserine\u2014an argument that can be repurposed as a constraint on Earth scenarios if analogous precursor biases held in terrestrial inventories. [13]\nAnother challenge is selectivity and stereochemistry. Multiple experimental contexts support predominantly racemic production for chiral amino acids in abiotic syntheses (e.g., spark discharge products; racemic allo-threonine in some meteoritic extracts where it can be resolved cleanly), but threonine\u2019s second stereocenter makes diastereomeric mixtures (threonine/allothreonine) a near-default outcome unless additional selection mechanisms are invoked. [24]\nA third major issue is compatibility of synthesis with survival. Hydroxy amino acids can undergo dehydration and other transformations during heating or long residence times; this is directly relevant to vent models (where high temperatures can accelerate degradation) and also to post-synthesis processing. [3]\nFinally, there is an ongoing debate over whether threonine should be expected to be among the earliest-abundant amino acids at all. The experimental record shows that threonine is certainly possible abiotically (spark discharge; cyanosulfidic networks yielding its Strecker precursors), but it is also plausibly scarcity-limited by precursor availability (lactaldehyde) and stability constraints (hydroxy amino-acid degradation), leaving room for models where threonine is incorporated later into biochemistry relative to simpler amino acids. [25]\n \n[1] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\n[2] [6] [8] [25] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4269183/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4269183/\n[3] https://pubs.usgs.gov/publication/70012489\nhttps://pubs.usgs.gov/publication/70012489\n[4] [5] [9] [11] [15] [17] [18] [24] https://science.gsfc.nasa.gov/sed/content/uploadFiles/publication_files/Parker2011.pdf\nhttps://science.gsfc.nasa.gov/sed/content/uploadFiles/publication_files/Parker2011.pdf\n[7] [12] REACTIONS OF AMINOMALONONITRILE WITH ... - HERO\nhttps://hero.epa.gov/reference/10713764/?utm_source=chatgpt.com\n[10] [19] [23] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8240947/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8240947/\n[13] [14] [16] https://api.lib.kyushu-u.ac.jp/opac_download_md/4474944/sci1377.pdf\nhttps://api.lib.kyushu-u.ac.jp/opac_download_md/4474944/sci1377.pdf\n[20] [21] https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1023/A%3A1006668322298.pdf\nhttps://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1023/A%3A1006668322298.pdf\n[22] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC40511/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC40511/\n\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.85\n- Feedback: This is a well-designed synthesis network for threonine that closely follows the literature consensus. The central strategy of converging on lactaldehyde as the key carbonyl precursor, followed by Strecker chemistry, is strongly supported by Ritson & Sutherland (2013), Green et al. (2021), and meteoritic Strecker analyses. The network exhibits genuine convergence with 5 convergence points and multiple alternative routes to threonine aminonitrile (surface Strecker, hydrothermal Strecker, and AMN coupling). Three main strengths: (1) excellent literature alignment with the cyanosulfidic photoredox route providing quantitative yield data, (2) proper cross-environmental flow from hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation through surface photoredox to biochemical hydrolysis, and (3) inclusion of the alternative AMN route (Thanassi 1975) for robustness. Three weaknesses: (1) HCN and NH\u2083 appear as hub intermediates without production reactions\u2014the network should show their genesis (e.g., volcanic HCN, thermal decomposition of ferrocyanide); (2) rxn_005 (glycolaldehyde \u2192 acetaldehyde) lacks a clean mechanistic pathway and is a bottleneck in 6 of 10 pathways; (3) the AMN + acetaldehyde coupling mechanism (rxn_011) needs elaboration. Formaldehyde's designation as a hub is marginal (degree 2). Overall, the network is chemically credible, well-connected, and achieves the target through multiple validated routes.\n- Issues: ['Hydrothermal Strecker from lactaldehyde. The literature caution is significant: threonine is not explicitly demonstrated in hydrothermal Strecker experiments, and hydroxy amino-acid degradation is a documented concern. The mineral buffering claim needs specification. Hydrothermal\u2192Biochemical transition is acceptable.', 'The AMN route is supported by Thanassi (1975) but the mechanism for AMN + acetaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile (rxn_011) is underspecified. Thanassi reports threonine/allothreonine in hydrolysates, but the intermediate steps are murky. AMN accumulation at useful concentrations is flagged as an open question in the literature. The rxn_005 weakness compounds uncertainty.', 'The longest AMN route inherits all weaknesses of P7 plus the hydrothermal uncertainties. Good environmental flow (hydrothermal\u2192surface\u2192biochemical) but accumulated uncertainty across 8 steps reduces confidence. Multiple weak links (rxn_002, rxn_005, rxn_011) compound.', 'Minimal AMN route. Compact but hinges entirely on rxn_011 (AMN + acetaldehyde), which is the least mechanistically specified reaction in the network. Thanassi support is real but indirect. Environmental progression is limited (surface only + biochemical).']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Threonine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"The network converges on lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal) as the key carbonyl precursor for threonine, following the literature consensus (Ritson & Sutherland 2013; meteoritic Strecker analyses). Three main branches feed into threonine aminonitrile: (1) cyanosulfidic UV photoredox chain reducing glycolonitrile \u2192 glycolaldehyde/acetaldehyde \u2192 lactonitrile \u2192 lactaldehyde, followed by Strecker assembly; (2) volcanic spark-discharge generation of HCN, NH\u2083, HCHO, and acetaldehyde as direct precursors; (3) HCN oligomerization to aminomalononitrile (AMN) followed by condensation with acetaldehyde (Thanassi 1975). Hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation on greigite/magnetite provides formate, formaldehyde, and FTT-derived acetaldehyde, creating cross-environmental flow. HCN, acetaldehyde, lactaldehyde, and threonine aminonitrile serve as hub molecules where multiple pathways converge. Final hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine occurs under mild aqueous (Biochemical) conditions.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"water\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"methane\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"dinitrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"nitrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/N2/c1-2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H3NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyacetonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h4H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyacetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H5NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxypropanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"lactonitrile (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H5NO/c1-2(5)3-4/h2,5H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-2(5)3-4/h2-3,5H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-2(7)3(5)4-6/h2-3,7H,5H2,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S,3R)-2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H3N3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanedinitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"aminomalononitrile (AMN)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H3N3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h3H,6H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHO2-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Volcanic spark discharge synthesis of reactive C-N intermediates\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"basalticite (volcanic rock surfaces)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-1500K (plume gradient)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"electrical discharge (volcanic lightning)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"Reducing gas mixture including CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S, CO\u2082; products rain out into tidal/surface waters; H\u2082S-rich variant per Parker et al. 2011\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"High-energy electrical discharge in a reducing volcanic plume dissociates CH\u2084, N\u2082, and H\u2082O into radicals (CH\u2083\u00b7, NH\u00b7, OH\u00b7, CN\u00b7). Radical recombination produces HCN, NH\u2083, and small carbonyl species including formaldehyde and acetaldehyde. Products condense and accumulate in surface waters. Both HCN and aldehydes are necessary Strecker precursors.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Parker et al. (2011, PNAS) reanalyzed Miller's 1958 H\u2082S-rich spark discharge residues and identified 23 amino acids including threonine, with racemic D/L ratios supporting abiotic origin. Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) confirmed threonine and allothreonine in CH\u2084/N\u2082/H\u2082O discharge products. Parker et al. explicitly argue volcanic lightning in reducing plumes generates HCN and aldehydes that rain out into tidal settings for subsequent aqueous-phase Strecker assembly.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (deep-sea)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vent, H\u2082-rich serpentinization fluid, pH 9-11\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 is adsorbed onto the greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) surface, which is structurally analogous to biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters. H\u2082 from serpentinization provides reducing equivalents. Two-electron reduction of CO\u2082 yields formate (HCOO\u207b) as the initial C\u2081 fixation product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"CO\u2082 reduction to formate on greigite and mackinawite surfaces is well-documented in alkaline hydrothermal vent chemistry. This provides the initial C\u2081 building block from which further reduction to formaldehyde is possible. The formate produced here enters the surface environment where it feeds into the cyanosulfidic network as a C\u2081 source, bridging hydrothermal and surface chemistries.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reduction of formate to formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\", \"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Subseafloor hydrothermal fluid, moderate pH, continued H\u2082 supply from serpentinization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate adsorbed on magnetite surface undergoes further two-electron reduction by H\u2082 to yield formaldehyde (HCHO). The magnetite surface stabilizes the transition state and provides a template for ordered reduction. HCHO is a critical C\u2081 building block for cyanohydrin and formose chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis on magnetite surfaces produces a range of oxygenated C\u2081-C\u2083 compounds from CO\u2082/CO + H\u2082. Formaldehyde is a key early intermediate in this progression. Andersson & Holm (2000, Orig. Life Evol. Biosph.) discuss pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite mineral buffers as controlling redox conditions for hydrothermal organic synthesis. The HCHO produced can be transported to surface environments via vent fluids.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\", \"elemental iron (Fe\u2070)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-300 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Black smoker or subseafloor hydrothermal system; CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 CO intermediate \u2192 C\u2082 oxygenates\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 is first reduced to CO on mineral surfaces, then CO undergoes Fischer-Tropsch chain growth: CO insertion and hydrogenation steps on the magnetite/iron surface yield C\u2082 oxygenates including acetaldehyde (CH\u2083CHO). Fe\u2070 provides strong reducing power. This is a well-documented FTT product spectrum.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite produces alcohols, aldehydes, and hydrocarbons from CO/CO\u2082 + H\u2082 at 400-500K. Acetaldehyde is a key C\u2082 carbonyl product. This provides an independent hydrothermal source of acetaldehyde, complementing volcanic discharge (rxn_001) and cyanosulfidic photoredox (rxn_006) routes. Establishing multiple routes to this hub molecule is critical for network robustness.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin formation: HCN + formaldehyde \u2192 glycolonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate buffer (sodium phosphate / apatite dissolution)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Mildly alkaline aqueous pool; CN\u207b nucleophilic addition to HCHO carbonyl; near-quantitative at modest concentrations\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanide ion (CN\u207b, from HCN at alkaline pH) attacks the electrophilic carbon of formaldehyde in a nucleophilic addition to form the cyanohydrin glycolonitrile (HOCH\u2082CN). This is a rapid, thermodynamically favorable reaction at ambient temperature. Phosphate buffers maintain pH in the 7-9 range needed for sufficient CN\u207b concentration.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) use glycolonitrile as the starting substrate for their cyanosulfidic photoredox network, and note that it forms readily from HCN + HCHO. They explicitly use sodium phosphate buffer (33 mM) in their experimental system. Glycolonitrile serves as the entry point into the photoredox reduction cascade that ultimately yields lactaldehyde. HCN can be concentrated via ferrocyanide complexation with Fe\u00b2\u207a as noted by Ritson & Sutherland.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"UV cyanosulfidic photoredox of glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"CuCN (copper(I) cyanide)\", \"sulfide minerals (chalcocite/covellite as CuCN source)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"CuCN heterogeneous photoredox catalyst (10 mol%)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation at 254 nm, 2 h; 10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H\u2082S, 33 mM sodium phosphate, quartz cuvette; glycolaldehyde 42% yield; acetaldehyde as co-product via rearrangement\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV irradiation of CuCN generates hydrated electrons (e\u2090q\u207b) via Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanocuprate photoredox cycling. H\u2082S serves as terminal reductant, regenerating Cu(I). Hydrated electrons reduce the nitrile group of glycolonitrile through a radical anion intermediate, leading to C-N bond cleavage and formation of glycolaldehyde (as hydrate). Acetaldehyde arises as a rearrangement/degradation co-product. CuCN forms a fine dark precipitate consistent with heterogeneous surface-mediated photocatalysis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) report that UV irradiation (254 nm) of glycolonitrile with H\u2082S and CuCN yields glycolaldehyde in 42% yield after 2 h, alongside acetaldehyde and formaldehyde as side products. Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021, JACS) elaborate the mechanism as Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanocuprate photoredox cycling generating hydrated electrons. Ritson & Sutherland note that CuCN could be sourced geochemically from dissolution of copper sulfide minerals in cyanide solution.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin formation: acetaldehyde + HCN \u2192 lactonitrile (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate buffer\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Mildly alkaline aqueous pool; CN\u207b addition to acetaldehyde carbonyl; produces racemic lactonitrile (2-hydroxypropanenitrile)\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanide ion (CN\u207b) attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of acetaldehyde in nucleophilic addition, forming the cyanohydrin lactonitrile (CH\u2083CH(OH)CN). This is an equilibrium reaction favored at moderate cyanide concentrations and mildly alkaline pH. The product retains a hydroxyl group at C2, which is essential for the threonine sidechain.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) explicitly identify acetaldehyde cyanohydrin (lactonitrile) as a key intermediate in their 'second-stage' photoredox reductions. It is the direct substrate for the photoredox step that yields lactaldehyde\u2014the dedicated threonine Strecker precursor. Cyanohydrin formation from aldehydes + HCN is a well-established, thermodynamically favorable reaction under mild aqueous conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"UV cyanosulfidic photoredox of lactonitrile to lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"CuCN (copper(I) cyanide)\", \"sulfide minerals (chalcocite/covellite as CuCN source)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"CuCN heterogeneous photoredox catalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation at 254 nm, 2 h; lactaldehyde yield 19%; quartz vessel; H\u2082S as terminal reductant\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-generated hydrated electrons from Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling reduce the nitrile group of lactonitrile (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin) through a radical anion intermediate, cleaving the C\u2261N bond and producing lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal, CH\u2083CH(OH)CHO). H\u2082S regenerates the Cu(I) state. This is the rate-limiting and yield-limiting step for threonine precursor formation in the cyanosulfidic network.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) explicitly report: 'irradiation of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin furnished lactaldehyde in 19% yield (after 2 h irradiation).' They identify lactaldehyde as 'the Strecker precursor of (allo-)threonine.' This 19% yield represents the key bottleneck in the photoredox route. Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021, JACS) situate this step within the broader cyanosulfidic network and note constraints on CuCN availability (low crustal copper abundance restricts this to copper-rich terrains).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate buffer\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Mildly alkaline pool; ammonia-rich conditions favor aminonitrile over cyanohydrin pathway; timescale days to weeks; produces racemic mixture of threonine and allothreonine aminonitriles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Lactaldehyde reacts with NH\u2083 to form an imine (Schiff base, CH\u2083CH(OH)CH=NH). Nucleophilic addition of CN\u207b (from HCN) to the imine carbon yields the \u03b1-aminonitrile 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile\u2014the threonine Strecker intermediate. The two stereocenters (C2, C3) yield diastereomeric products: threonine aminonitrile and allothreonine aminonitrile. Ammonia-rich conditions are essential; ammonia-poor conditions divert to cyanohydrin (\u2192 hydroxy acid) pathway.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) report that when HCN and NH\u2083 were added to photoreduction products, lactaldehyde was 'smoothly converted' via its cyanohydrin to the (allo-)threonine Strecker intermediate aminonitrile (compound 22 in their numbering). Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021, JACS) embed this step in their systems-level network. The meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin analysis (Kyushu University report) emphasizes that ammonia availability controls whether amino acid vs. hydroxy acid products dominate, and explicitly identifies lactaldehyde as the carbonyl precursor for threonine/allothreonine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\", \"pyrrhotite (FeS)\", \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (10 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite mineral buffer\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Redox buffered by FeS\u2082/FeS/Fe\u2083O\u2084 assemblage; pH buffered by K-feldspar-muscovite-quartz; caution: hydroxy amino acids susceptible to thermal degradation at high T; threonine specifically not yet confirmed in hydrothermal Strecker experiments\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Same Strecker mechanism as rxn_009 (imine formation + CN\u207b addition) but operating at elevated temperature and pressure in a mineral-buffered hydrothermal setting. The pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite assemblage controls oxygen fugacity (redox), while silicate buffers control pH. Higher temperature accelerates reaction kinetics but also promotes competing degradation (dehydration) of the hydroxy amino acid product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Andersson & Holm (2000, Orig. Life Evol. Biosph.) summarize hydrothermal Strecker experiments by Hennet et al. (1992) using HCN, CH\u2082O, and NH\u2084Cl at 150\u00b0C and 10 bar with pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite buffer, producing glycine (~9-12 mM) and alanine (~0.5-1.3 mM). However, threonine is NOT explicitly tabulated among products in those experiments\u2014this route is therefore speculative for threonine specifically. The literature cautions that hydroxy amino acids undergo dehydration and degradation during hydrothermal exposure (USGS report on diagenetic amino acid reactions). This reaction requires lactaldehyde transport from surface to vent-flank environments.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN trimerization to aminomalononitrile (AMN)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay surfaces (concentrate HCN)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Requires moderate HCN concentration (>0.01 M); clay surfaces adsorb and concentrate HCN; competes with HCN polymerization to intractable tholins; ferrocyanide pathway can pre-concentrate cyanide via Fe\u00b2\u207a complexation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Three molecules of HCN undergo stepwise oligomerization: HCN dimerizes to iminoacetonitrile (or its tautomer), which then reacts with a third HCN to form aminomalononitrile (H\u2082N-CH(CN)\u2082). AMN is a key branch point in HCN chemistry: it can further react with a fourth HCN to yield diaminomaleonitrile (DAMN, adenine precursor), or it can serve as a multifunctional C-N nucleophile for condensation with electrophilic aldehydes.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thanassi (1975, J. Mol. Evol.) uses aminomalononitrile as a starting material for amino acid synthesis including threonine/allothreonine, establishing AMN as a legitimate prebiotic C-N building block. Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021, JACS) discuss the broader HCN oligomerization landscape, noting that AMN accumulation at useful concentrations remains an open question due to competing polymerization to intractable HCN polymers. Ritson & Sutherland (2013) note cyanide can be concentrated via ferrocyanide complexation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"AMN condensation with acetaldehyde \u2192 threonine/allothreonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (clay surface catalysis and concentration)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Mild aqueous conditions; AMN acts as carbanion-equivalent nucleophile; product is \u03b1-aminonitrile bearing hydroxyl sidechain; subsequent hydrolysis yields threonine/allothreonine\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aminomalononitrile (H\u2082N-CH(CN)\u2082) acts as a stabilized carbanion equivalent: one nitrile group is displaced or hydrolyzed during condensation with acetaldehyde (CH\u2083CHO). The AMN nitrogen provides the amino group while acetaldehyde provides the C2-C3 fragment with the hydroxyl-bearing sidechain. The product is an \u03b1-aminonitrile equivalent (threonine aminonitrile) or a closely related intermediate that converges on the same hydrolysis product. The dinitrile character of AMN facilitates initial C-C bond formation via stabilized enolization. Both threonine and allothreonine diastereomers are produced.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thanassi (1975, J. Mol. Evol.) reports that reacting aminomalononitrile with electrophiles (including aldehydes) followed by hydrolysis yields a range of amino acids, explicitly identifying threonine and allothreonine in hydrolysates. This provides an alternative to the classical Strecker route that bypasses the need for preformed lactaldehyde. The mechanistic details are less specified than the Ritson-Sutherland route, and AMN accumulation remains an open question (Green et al. 2021, JACS). Clay surfaces may help concentrate AMN and aldehyde reactants.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Aminonitrile hydrolysis: threonine aminonitrile \u2192 threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null (acid or base catalyzed hydrolysis)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Mild aqueous conditions; stepwise hydrolysis: aminonitrile \u2192 amide (via amidonitrile) \u2192 amino acid; can proceed slowly at neutral pH or more rapidly at mildly acidic/basic pH; produces racemic DL-threonine + DL-allothreonine mixture\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile group (-C\u2261N) of threonine aminonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: first to an amide (-CONH\u2082) by addition of H\u2082O across the C\u2261N triple bond, then further hydrolysis of the amide to a carboxylic acid (-COOH) with loss of NH\u2083. The amino group at C2 and hydroxyl at C3 are retained. Product is racemic (allo-)threonine. This is the universal final step in all Strecker amino acid syntheses.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aminonitrile hydrolysis to amino acids is the well-established final step of the Strecker synthesis. The Kyushu University meteoritic analysis explicitly frames hydrolysis of aminonitriles as producing \u03b1-amino acids, and identifies this as the terminal step for threonine formation from lactaldehyde-derived Strecker intermediates. Ritson & Sutherland (2013) and Green et al. (2021, JACS) assume this hydrolysis as the completion of their cyanosulfidic route to amino acids. The hydrolysis is spontaneous in aqueous solution over geochemical timescales.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Full cyanosulfidic photoredox from hydrothermal CO\u2082\",\n      \"description\": \"Complete pathway from hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation through surface cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry to threonine. CO\u2082 is reduced to formate then formaldehyde in hydrothermal vents, transported to surface pools where it combines with volcanic HCN to form glycolonitrile, which undergoes UV photoredox to glycolaldehyde/acetaldehyde, then cyanohydrin formation to lactonitrile, photoredox reduction to lactaldehyde, Strecker assembly to threonine aminonitrile, and hydrolysis to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Volcanic discharge HCN/HCHO \u2192 cyanosulfidic photoredox \u2192 Strecker threonine\",\n      \"description\": \"Volcanic spark discharge provides HCN and formaldehyde, which combine to form glycolonitrile. UV cyanosulfidic photoredox reduces glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde. Acetaldehyde is converted to lactonitrile (cyanohydrin), then photoredox-reduced to lactaldehyde, and Strecker chemistry yields threonine aminonitrile \u2192 threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Volcanic discharge direct acetaldehyde \u2192 photoredox lactaldehyde \u2192 Strecker threonine\",\n      \"description\": \"Shortest photoredox pathway: volcanic discharge directly provides acetaldehyde and HCN. Acetaldehyde forms lactonitrile cyanohydrin with HCN, photoredox reduction yields lactaldehyde, Strecker assembly with HCN and NH\u2083 (both from discharge) gives threonine aminonitrile \u2192 threonine. Only 5 reaction steps.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal FTT acetaldehyde + volcanic HCN \u2192 photoredox \u2192 surface Strecker\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde from hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis (rxn_004) meets volcanic discharge-derived HCN (rxn_001) in surface pools. Cyanohydrin formation yields lactonitrile, UV photoredox produces lactaldehyde, and surface Strecker chemistry assembles threonine aminonitrile. Cross-environmental: Hydrothermal + Surface \u2192 Biochemical.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal FTT acetaldehyde \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 hydrothermal Strecker\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal acetaldehyde (FTT) and volcanic HCN combine in surface pools to form lactonitrile, photoredox reduction yields lactaldehyde, and lactaldehyde undergoes Strecker chemistry in a hydrothermal vent-flank setting with mineral buffering. CAUTION: threonine not explicitly confirmed in hydrothermal Strecker experiments; hydroxy amino acid degradation at high T is a concern.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"AMN route with volcanic discharge acetaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Volcanic discharge produces HCN, NH\u2083, and acetaldehyde. HCN trimerizes to aminomalononitrile (AMN) on clay surfaces. AMN condenses with discharge-derived acetaldehyde to form threonine aminonitrile directly, bypassing the need for lactaldehyde. Hydrolysis yields threonine. Most compact AMN route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"AMN route with hydrothermal FTT acetaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN from volcanic discharge trimerizes to AMN (surface), while acetaldehyde is independently sourced from hydrothermal FTT synthesis. AMN and FTT-acetaldehyde condense to form threonine aminonitrile. Cross-environmental: Hydrothermal acetaldehyde + Surface AMN \u2192 Biochemical hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"AMN route with cyanosulfidic photoredox-derived acetaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Longest AMN pathway: hydrothermal CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 glycolonitrile (with volcanic HCN) \u2192 photoredox yields acetaldehyde as co-product. Separately, HCN trimerizes to AMN. AMN condenses with photoredox-derived acetaldehyde to form threonine aminonitrile \u2192 threonine. Spans all three environments.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Volcanic discharge \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 hydrothermal Strecker threonine\",\n      \"description\": \"Volcanic discharge provides HCN, NH\u2083, and acetaldehyde. Surface cyanohydrin + photoredox chemistry produces lactaldehyde. Lactaldehyde and HCN/NH\u2083 then undergo Strecker synthesis in a hydrothermal vent-flank mineral-buffered setting. This tests the boundary between surface and hydrothermal Strecker chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Full hydrothermal origin \u2192 cyanosulfidic chain \u2192 hydrothermal Strecker \u2192 threonine\",\n      \"description\": \"Maximum cross-environmental pathway: CO\u2082 reduced to formate then formaldehyde in hydrothermal vents, FTT also produces acetaldehyde. Formaldehyde + volcanic HCN \u2192 glycolonitrile in surface pools. Photoredox yields more acetaldehyde. Cyanohydrin + photoredox yields lactaldehyde. Lactaldehyde returns to hydrothermal environment for mineral-buffered Strecker synthesis. Threonine aminonitrile hydrolysis in mild pool. Traverses Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal \u2192 Biochemical.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrogen cyanide - central C\u2081/N building block produced by volcanic discharge, required for cyanohydrin formation, Strecker imine-cyanation, and AMN trimerization\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_001\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde - C\u2082 carbonyl hub produced by three independent routes (volcanic discharge, hydrothermal FTT, cyanosulfidic photoredox co-product); feeds into both the cyanohydrin/lactaldehyde pathway and the AMN condensation route\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"description\": \"Lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal) - the dedicated carbonyl Strecker precursor for threonine/allothreonine; bottleneck intermediate produced only by cyanosulfidic photoredox of lactonitrile at 19% yield\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"description\": \"Threonine aminonitrile - the key convergence point where all pathways meet before final hydrolysis; produced by three independent routes: surface Strecker from lactaldehyde, hydrothermal Strecker from lactaldehyde, and AMN condensation with acetaldehyde\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Threonine", "overall_strategy": "The network converges on lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal) as the key carbonyl precursor for threonine, following the literature consensus (Ritson & Sutherland 2013; meteoritic Strecker analyses). Three main branches feed into threonine aminonitrile: (1) cyanosulfidic UV photoredox chain reducing glycolonitrile \u2192 glycolaldehyde/acetaldehyde \u2192 lactonitrile \u2192 lactaldehyde, followed by Strecker assembly; (2) volcanic spark-discharge generation of HCN, NH\u2083, HCHO, and acetaldehyde as direct precursors; (3) HCN oligomerization to aminomalononitrile (AMN) followed by condensation with acetaldehyde (Thanassi 1975). Hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation on greigite/magnetite provides formate, formaldehyde, and FTT-derived acetaldehyde, creating cross-environmental flow. HCN, acetaldehyde, lactaldehyde, and threonine aminonitrile serve as hub molecules where multiple pathways converge. Final hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine occurs under mild aqueous (Biochemical) conditions.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "CH4", "iupac_name": "methane", "common_name": "methane", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "N2", "iupac_name": "dinitrogen", "common_name": "nitrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/N2/c1-2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "formonitrile", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H3NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetonitrile", "common_name": "glycolonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h4H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetaldehyde", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "acetaldehyde", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C3H5NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanenitrile", "common_name": "lactonitrile (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H5NO/c1-2(5)3-4/h2,5H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C3H6O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanal", "common_name": "lactaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-2(5)3-4/h2-3,5H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C4H8N2O", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile", "common_name": "threonine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-2(7)3(5)4-6/h2-3,7H,5H2,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C4H9NO3", "iupac_name": "(2S,3R)-2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "threonine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C3H3N3", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanedinitrile", "common_name": "aminomalononitrile (AMN)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H3N3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h3H,6H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "CHO2-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Volcanic spark discharge synthesis of reactive C-N intermediates", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["basalticite (volcanic rock surfaces)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-1500K (plume gradient)", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "electrical discharge (volcanic lightning)", "aqueous": "false", "other": "Reducing gas mixture including CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S, CO\u2082; products rain out into tidal/surface waters; H\u2082S-rich variant per Parker et al. 2011"}, "mechanism": "High-energy electrical discharge in a reducing volcanic plume dissociates CH\u2084, N\u2082, and H\u2082O into radicals (CH\u2083\u00b7, NH\u00b7, OH\u00b7, CN\u00b7). Radical recombination produces HCN, NH\u2083, and small carbonyl species including formaldehyde and acetaldehyde. Products condense and accumulate in surface waters. Both HCN and aldehydes are necessary Strecker precursors.", "reasoning": "Parker et al. (2011, PNAS) reanalyzed Miller's 1958 H\u2082S-rich spark discharge residues and identified 23 amino acids including threonine, with racemic D/L ratios supporting abiotic origin. Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) confirmed threonine and allothreonine in CH\u2084/N\u2082/H\u2082O discharge products. Parker et al. explicitly argue volcanic lightning in reducing plumes generates HCN and aldehydes that rain out into tidal settings for subsequent aqueous-phase Strecker assembly."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (deep-sea)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal vent, H\u2082-rich serpentinization fluid, pH 9-11"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 is adsorbed onto the greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) surface, which is structurally analogous to biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters. H\u2082 from serpentinization provides reducing equivalents. Two-electron reduction of CO\u2082 yields formate (HCOO\u207b) as the initial C\u2081 fixation product.", "reasoning": "CO\u2082 reduction to formate on greigite and mackinawite surfaces is well-documented in alkaline hydrothermal vent chemistry. This provides the initial C\u2081 building block from which further reduction to formaldehyde is possible. The formate produced here enters the surface environment where it feeds into the cyanosulfidic network as a C\u2081 source, bridging hydrothermal and surface chemistries."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal reduction of formate to formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_018", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Subseafloor hydrothermal fluid, moderate pH, continued H\u2082 supply from serpentinization"}, "mechanism": "Formate adsorbed on magnetite surface undergoes further two-electron reduction by H\u2082 to yield formaldehyde (HCHO). The magnetite surface stabilizes the transition state and provides a template for ordered reduction. HCHO is a critical C\u2081 building block for cyanohydrin and formose chemistry.", "reasoning": "Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis on magnetite surfaces produces a range of oxygenated C\u2081-C\u2083 compounds from CO\u2082/CO + H\u2082. Formaldehyde is a key early intermediate in this progression. Andersson & Holm (2000, Orig. Life Evol. Biosph.) discuss pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite mineral buffers as controlling redox conditions for hydrothermal organic synthesis. The HCHO produced can be transported to surface environments via vent fluids."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "elemental iron (Fe\u2070)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (100-300 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Black smoker or subseafloor hydrothermal system; CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 CO intermediate \u2192 C\u2082 oxygenates"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 is first reduced to CO on mineral surfaces, then CO undergoes Fischer-Tropsch chain growth: CO insertion and hydrogenation steps on the magnetite/iron surface yield C\u2082 oxygenates including acetaldehyde (CH\u2083CHO). Fe\u2070 provides strong reducing power. This is a well-documented FTT product spectrum.", "reasoning": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite produces alcohols, aldehydes, and hydrocarbons from CO/CO\u2082 + H\u2082 at 400-500K. Acetaldehyde is a key C\u2082 carbonyl product. This provides an independent hydrothermal source of acetaldehyde, complementing volcanic discharge (rxn_001) and cyanosulfidic photoredox (rxn_006) routes. Establishing multiple routes to this hub molecule is critical for network robustness."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Cyanohydrin formation: HCN + formaldehyde \u2192 glycolonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate buffer (sodium phosphate / apatite dissolution)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Mildly alkaline aqueous pool; CN\u207b nucleophilic addition to HCHO carbonyl; near-quantitative at modest concentrations"}, "mechanism": "Cyanide ion (CN\u207b, from HCN at alkaline pH) attacks the electrophilic carbon of formaldehyde in a nucleophilic addition to form the cyanohydrin glycolonitrile (HOCH\u2082CN). This is a rapid, thermodynamically favorable reaction at ambient temperature. Phosphate buffers maintain pH in the 7-9 range needed for sufficient CN\u207b concentration.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) use glycolonitrile as the starting substrate for their cyanosulfidic photoredox network, and note that it forms readily from HCN + HCHO. They explicitly use sodium phosphate buffer (33 mM) in their experimental system. Glycolonitrile serves as the entry point into the photoredox reduction cascade that ultimately yields lactaldehyde. HCN can be concentrated via ferrocyanide complexation with Fe\u00b2\u207a as noted by Ritson & Sutherland."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "UV cyanosulfidic photoredox of glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_011", "mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["CuCN (copper(I) cyanide)", "sulfide minerals (chalcocite/covellite as CuCN source)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "CuCN heterogeneous photoredox catalyst (10 mol%)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation at 254 nm, 2 h; 10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H\u2082S, 33 mM sodium phosphate, quartz cuvette; glycolaldehyde 42% yield; acetaldehyde as co-product via rearrangement"}, "mechanism": "UV irradiation of CuCN generates hydrated electrons (e\u2090q\u207b) via Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanocuprate photoredox cycling. H\u2082S serves as terminal reductant, regenerating Cu(I). Hydrated electrons reduce the nitrile group of glycolonitrile through a radical anion intermediate, leading to C-N bond cleavage and formation of glycolaldehyde (as hydrate). Acetaldehyde arises as a rearrangement/degradation co-product. CuCN forms a fine dark precipitate consistent with heterogeneous surface-mediated photocatalysis.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) report that UV irradiation (254 nm) of glycolonitrile with H\u2082S and CuCN yields glycolaldehyde in 42% yield after 2 h, alongside acetaldehyde and formaldehyde as side products. Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021, JACS) elaborate the mechanism as Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanocuprate photoredox cycling generating hydrated electrons. Ritson & Sutherland note that CuCN could be sourced geochemically from dissolution of copper sulfide minerals in cyanide solution."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Cyanohydrin formation: acetaldehyde + HCN \u2192 lactonitrile (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin)", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate buffer", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Mildly alkaline aqueous pool; CN\u207b addition to acetaldehyde carbonyl; produces racemic lactonitrile (2-hydroxypropanenitrile)"}, "mechanism": "Cyanide ion (CN\u207b) attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of acetaldehyde in nucleophilic addition, forming the cyanohydrin lactonitrile (CH\u2083CH(OH)CN). This is an equilibrium reaction favored at moderate cyanide concentrations and mildly alkaline pH. The product retains a hydroxyl group at C2, which is essential for the threonine sidechain.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) explicitly identify acetaldehyde cyanohydrin (lactonitrile) as a key intermediate in their 'second-stage' photoredox reductions. It is the direct substrate for the photoredox step that yields lactaldehyde\u2014the dedicated threonine Strecker precursor. Cyanohydrin formation from aldehydes + HCN is a well-established, thermodynamically favorable reaction under mild aqueous conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "UV cyanosulfidic photoredox of lactonitrile to lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["CuCN (copper(I) cyanide)", "sulfide minerals (chalcocite/covellite as CuCN source)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "CuCN heterogeneous photoredox catalyst", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation at 254 nm, 2 h; lactaldehyde yield 19%; quartz vessel; H\u2082S as terminal reductant"}, "mechanism": "UV-generated hydrated electrons from Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling reduce the nitrile group of lactonitrile (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin) through a radical anion intermediate, cleaving the C\u2261N bond and producing lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal, CH\u2083CH(OH)CHO). H\u2082S regenerates the Cu(I) state. This is the rate-limiting and yield-limiting step for threonine precursor formation in the cyanosulfidic network.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) explicitly report: 'irradiation of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin furnished lactaldehyde in 19% yield (after 2 h irradiation).' They identify lactaldehyde as 'the Strecker precursor of (allo-)threonine.' This 19% yield represents the key bottleneck in the photoredox route. Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021, JACS) situate this step within the broader cyanosulfidic network and note constraints on CuCN availability (low crustal copper abundance restricts this to copper-rich terrains)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Surface Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 threonine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_007", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate buffer", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Mildly alkaline pool; ammonia-rich conditions favor aminonitrile over cyanohydrin pathway; timescale days to weeks; produces racemic mixture of threonine and allothreonine aminonitriles"}, "mechanism": "Lactaldehyde reacts with NH\u2083 to form an imine (Schiff base, CH\u2083CH(OH)CH=NH). Nucleophilic addition of CN\u207b (from HCN) to the imine carbon yields the \u03b1-aminonitrile 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile\u2014the threonine Strecker intermediate. The two stereocenters (C2, C3) yield diastereomeric products: threonine aminonitrile and allothreonine aminonitrile. Ammonia-rich conditions are essential; ammonia-poor conditions divert to cyanohydrin (\u2192 hydroxy acid) pathway.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) report that when HCN and NH\u2083 were added to photoreduction products, lactaldehyde was 'smoothly converted' via its cyanohydrin to the (allo-)threonine Strecker intermediate aminonitrile (compound 22 in their numbering). Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021, JACS) embed this step in their systems-level network. The meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin analysis (Kyushu University report) emphasizes that ammonia availability controls whether amino acid vs. hydroxy acid products dominate, and explicitly identifies lactaldehyde as the carbonyl precursor for threonine/allothreonine."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Hydrothermal Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 threonine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_007", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)", "pyrrhotite (FeS)", "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "high (10 bar)", "catalyst": "pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite mineral buffer", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Redox buffered by FeS\u2082/FeS/Fe\u2083O\u2084 assemblage; pH buffered by K-feldspar-muscovite-quartz; caution: hydroxy amino acids susceptible to thermal degradation at high T; threonine specifically not yet confirmed in hydrothermal Strecker experiments"}, "mechanism": "Same Strecker mechanism as rxn_009 (imine formation + CN\u207b addition) but operating at elevated temperature and pressure in a mineral-buffered hydrothermal setting. The pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite assemblage controls oxygen fugacity (redox), while silicate buffers control pH. Higher temperature accelerates reaction kinetics but also promotes competing degradation (dehydration) of the hydroxy amino acid product.", "reasoning": "Andersson & Holm (2000, Orig. Life Evol. Biosph.) summarize hydrothermal Strecker experiments by Hennet et al. (1992) using HCN, CH\u2082O, and NH\u2084Cl at 150\u00b0C and 10 bar with pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite buffer, producing glycine (~9-12 mM) and alanine (~0.5-1.3 mM). However, threonine is NOT explicitly tabulated among products in those experiments\u2014this route is therefore speculative for threonine specifically. The literature cautions that hydroxy amino acids undergo dehydration and degradation during hydrothermal exposure (USGS report on diagenetic amino acid reactions). This reaction requires lactaldehyde transport from surface to vent-flank environments."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "HCN trimerization to aminomalononitrile (AMN)", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay surfaces (concentrate HCN)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Requires moderate HCN concentration (>0.01 M); clay surfaces adsorb and concentrate HCN; competes with HCN polymerization to intractable tholins; ferrocyanide pathway can pre-concentrate cyanide via Fe\u00b2\u207a complexation"}, "mechanism": "Three molecules of HCN undergo stepwise oligomerization: HCN dimerizes to iminoacetonitrile (or its tautomer), which then reacts with a third HCN to form aminomalononitrile (H\u2082N-CH(CN)\u2082). AMN is a key branch point in HCN chemistry: it can further react with a fourth HCN to yield diaminomaleonitrile (DAMN, adenine precursor), or it can serve as a multifunctional C-N nucleophile for condensation with electrophilic aldehydes.", "reasoning": "Thanassi (1975, J. Mol. Evol.) uses aminomalononitrile as a starting material for amino acid synthesis including threonine/allothreonine, establishing AMN as a legitimate prebiotic C-N building block. Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021, JACS) discuss the broader HCN oligomerization landscape, noting that AMN accumulation at useful concentrations remains an open question due to competing polymerization to intractable HCN polymers. Ritson & Sutherland (2013) note cyanide can be concentrated via ferrocyanide complexation."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "AMN condensation with acetaldehyde \u2192 threonine/allothreonine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (clay surface catalysis and concentration)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Mild aqueous conditions; AMN acts as carbanion-equivalent nucleophile; product is \u03b1-aminonitrile bearing hydroxyl sidechain; subsequent hydrolysis yields threonine/allothreonine"}, "mechanism": "Aminomalononitrile (H\u2082N-CH(CN)\u2082) acts as a stabilized carbanion equivalent: one nitrile group is displaced or hydrolyzed during condensation with acetaldehyde (CH\u2083CHO). The AMN nitrogen provides the amino group while acetaldehyde provides the C2-C3 fragment with the hydroxyl-bearing sidechain. The product is an \u03b1-aminonitrile equivalent (threonine aminonitrile) or a closely related intermediate that converges on the same hydrolysis product. The dinitrile character of AMN facilitates initial C-C bond formation via stabilized enolization. Both threonine and allothreonine diastereomers are produced.", "reasoning": "Thanassi (1975, J. Mol. Evol.) reports that reacting aminomalononitrile with electrophiles (including aldehydes) followed by hydrolysis yields a range of amino acids, explicitly identifying threonine and allothreonine in hydrolysates. This provides an alternative to the classical Strecker route that bypasses the need for preformed lactaldehyde. The mechanistic details are less specified than the Ritson-Sutherland route, and AMN accumulation remains an open question (Green et al. 2021, JACS). Clay surfaces may help concentrate AMN and aldehyde reactants."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Aminonitrile hydrolysis: threonine aminonitrile \u2192 threonine", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null (acid or base catalyzed hydrolysis)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Mild aqueous conditions; stepwise hydrolysis: aminonitrile \u2192 amide (via amidonitrile) \u2192 amino acid; can proceed slowly at neutral pH or more rapidly at mildly acidic/basic pH; produces racemic DL-threonine + DL-allothreonine mixture"}, "mechanism": "The nitrile group (-C\u2261N) of threonine aminonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: first to an amide (-CONH\u2082) by addition of H\u2082O across the C\u2261N triple bond, then further hydrolysis of the amide to a carboxylic acid (-COOH) with loss of NH\u2083. The amino group at C2 and hydroxyl at C3 are retained. Product is racemic (allo-)threonine. This is the universal final step in all Strecker amino acid syntheses.", "reasoning": "Aminonitrile hydrolysis to amino acids is the well-established final step of the Strecker synthesis. The Kyushu University meteoritic analysis explicitly frames hydrolysis of aminonitriles as producing \u03b1-amino acids, and identifies this as the terminal step for threonine formation from lactaldehyde-derived Strecker intermediates. Ritson & Sutherland (2013) and Green et al. (2021, JACS) assume this hydrolysis as the completion of their cyanosulfidic route to amino acids. The hydrolysis is spontaneous in aqueous solution over geochemical timescales."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Full cyanosulfidic photoredox from hydrothermal CO\u2082", "description": "Complete pathway from hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation through surface cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry to threonine. CO\u2082 is reduced to formate then formaldehyde in hydrothermal vents, transported to surface pools where it combines with volcanic HCN to form glycolonitrile, which undergoes UV photoredox to glycolaldehyde/acetaldehyde, then cyanohydrin formation to lactonitrile, photoredox reduction to lactaldehyde, Strecker assembly to threonine aminonitrile, and hydrolysis to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_001", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_018", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Volcanic discharge HCN/HCHO \u2192 cyanosulfidic photoredox \u2192 Strecker threonine", "description": "Volcanic spark discharge provides HCN and formaldehyde, which combine to form glycolonitrile. UV cyanosulfidic photoredox reduces glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde. Acetaldehyde is converted to lactonitrile (cyanohydrin), then photoredox-reduced to lactaldehyde, and Strecker chemistry yields threonine aminonitrile \u2192 threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Volcanic discharge direct acetaldehyde \u2192 photoredox lactaldehyde \u2192 Strecker threonine", "description": "Shortest photoredox pathway: volcanic discharge directly provides acetaldehyde and HCN. Acetaldehyde forms lactonitrile cyanohydrin with HCN, photoredox reduction yields lactaldehyde, Strecker assembly with HCN and NH\u2083 (both from discharge) gives threonine aminonitrile \u2192 threonine. Only 5 reaction steps.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Hydrothermal FTT acetaldehyde + volcanic HCN \u2192 photoredox \u2192 surface Strecker", "description": "Acetaldehyde from hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis (rxn_004) meets volcanic discharge-derived HCN (rxn_001) in surface pools. Cyanohydrin formation yields lactonitrile, UV photoredox produces lactaldehyde, and surface Strecker chemistry assembles threonine aminonitrile. Cross-environmental: Hydrothermal + Surface \u2192 Biochemical.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_001", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Hydrothermal FTT acetaldehyde \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 hydrothermal Strecker", "description": "Hydrothermal acetaldehyde (FTT) and volcanic HCN combine in surface pools to form lactonitrile, photoredox reduction yields lactaldehyde, and lactaldehyde undergoes Strecker chemistry in a hydrothermal vent-flank setting with mineral buffering. CAUTION: threonine not explicitly confirmed in hydrothermal Strecker experiments; hydroxy amino acid degradation at high T is a concern.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_001", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_007", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "AMN route with volcanic discharge acetaldehyde", "description": "Volcanic discharge produces HCN, NH\u2083, and acetaldehyde. HCN trimerizes to aminomalononitrile (AMN) on clay surfaces. AMN condenses with discharge-derived acetaldehyde to form threonine aminonitrile directly, bypassing the need for lactaldehyde. Hydrolysis yields threonine. Most compact AMN route.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_017", "mol_012", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "AMN route with hydrothermal FTT acetaldehyde", "description": "HCN from volcanic discharge trimerizes to AMN (surface), while acetaldehyde is independently sourced from hydrothermal FTT synthesis. AMN and FTT-acetaldehyde condense to form threonine aminonitrile. Cross-environmental: Hydrothermal acetaldehyde + Surface AMN \u2192 Biochemical hydrolysis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_011", "rxn_004", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_017", "mol_012", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "AMN route with cyanosulfidic photoredox-derived acetaldehyde", "description": "Longest AMN pathway: hydrothermal CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 glycolonitrile (with volcanic HCN) \u2192 photoredox yields acetaldehyde as co-product. Separately, HCN trimerizes to AMN. AMN condenses with photoredox-derived acetaldehyde to form threonine aminonitrile \u2192 threonine. Spans all three environments.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_001", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_018", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_017", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Volcanic discharge \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 hydrothermal Strecker threonine", "description": "Volcanic discharge provides HCN, NH\u2083, and acetaldehyde. Surface cyanohydrin + photoredox chemistry produces lactaldehyde. Lactaldehyde and HCN/NH\u2083 then undergo Strecker synthesis in a hydrothermal vent-flank mineral-buffered setting. This tests the boundary between surface and hydrothermal Strecker chemistry.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Full hydrothermal origin \u2192 cyanosulfidic chain \u2192 hydrothermal Strecker \u2192 threonine", "description": "Maximum cross-environmental pathway: CO\u2082 reduced to formate then formaldehyde in hydrothermal vents, FTT also produces acetaldehyde. Formaldehyde + volcanic HCN \u2192 glycolonitrile in surface pools. Photoredox yields more acetaldehyde. Cyanohydrin + photoredox yields lactaldehyde. Lactaldehyde returns to hydrothermal environment for mineral-buffered Strecker synthesis. Threonine aminonitrile hydrolysis in mild pool. Traverses Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal \u2192 Biochemical.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_001", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_018", "mol_009", "mol_007", "mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_007", "mol_012", "mol_014", "mol_015"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_007", "description": "Hydrogen cyanide - central C\u2081/N building block produced by volcanic discharge, required for cyanohydrin formation, Strecker imine-cyanation, and AMN trimerization", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_001"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_012", "description": "Acetaldehyde - C\u2082 carbonyl hub produced by three independent routes (volcanic discharge, hydrothermal FTT, cyanosulfidic photoredox co-product); feeds into both the cyanohydrin/lactaldehyde pathway and the AMN condensation route", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_001", "rxn_004", "rxn_006"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_007", "rxn_012"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_014", "description": "Lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal) - the dedicated carbonyl Strecker precursor for threonine/allothreonine; bottleneck intermediate produced only by cyanosulfidic photoredox of lactonitrile at 19% yield", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_008"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_009", "rxn_010"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_015", "description": "Threonine aminonitrile - the key convergence point where all pathways meet before final hydrolysis; produced by three independent routes: surface Strecker from lactaldehyde, hydrothermal Strecker from lactaldehyde, and AMN condensation with acetaldehyde", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_012"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_013"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 461312.0467662811, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-16T22:03:58.351432", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.8\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Threonine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: The network converges on lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal) as the key carbonyl precursor for threonine, following the literature consensus (Ritson & Sutherland 2013; meteoritic Strecker analyses). Three main branches feed into threonine aminonitrile: (1) cyanosulfidic UV photoredox chain reducing glycolonitrile \u2192 glycolaldehyde/acetaldehyde \u2192 lactonitrile \u2192 lactaldehyde, followed by Strecker assembly; (2) volcanic spark-discharge generation of HCN, NH\u2083, HCHO, and acetaldehyde as direct precursors; (3) HCN oligomerization to aminomalononitrile (AMN) followed by condensation with acetaldehyde (Thanassi 1975). Hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation on greigite/magnetite provides formate, formaldehyde, and FTT-derived acetaldehyde, creating cross-environmental flow. HCN, acetaldehyde, lactaldehyde, and threonine aminonitrile serve as hub molecules where multiple pathways converge. Final hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine occurs under mild aqueous (Biochemical) conditions.\n\nMOLECULES (18 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2O (water) [starting]\n  - mol_003: H2 (hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_004: CH4 (methane) [starting]\n  - mol_005: N2 (nitrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_006: H2S (hydrogen sulfide) [starting]\n  - mol_007: HCN (hydrogen cyanide) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_008: NH3 (ammonia) [intermediate]\n  - mol_009: CH2O (formaldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C2H3NO (glycolonitrile) [intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C2H4O2 (glycolaldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C2H4O (acetaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C3H5NO (lactonitrile (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin)) [intermediate]\n  - mol_014: C3H6O2 (lactaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_015: C4H8N2O (threonine aminonitrile) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_016: C4H9NO3 (threonine) [target]\n  - mol_017: C3H3N3 (aminomalononitrile (AMN)) [intermediate]\n  - mol_018: CHO2- (formate) [intermediate]\n\nREACTIONS (13 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_004, mol_005, mol_002 -> mol_007, mol_008, mol_009, mol_012 (Volcanic spark discharge synthesis of reactive C-N intermediates) [Surface]\n  - rxn_002: mol_001, mol_003 -> mol_018 (Hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction to formate on greigite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_003: mol_018, mol_003 -> mol_009 (Hydrothermal reduction of formate to formaldehyde) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_004: mol_001, mol_003 -> mol_012 (Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_005: mol_007, mol_009 -> mol_010 (Cyanohydrin formation: HCN + formaldehyde \u2192 glycolonitrile) [Surface]\n  - rxn_006: mol_010, mol_006 -> mol_011, mol_012 (UV cyanosulfidic photoredox of glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_007: mol_012, mol_007 -> mol_013 (Cyanohydrin formation: acetaldehyde + HCN \u2192 lactonitrile (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin)) [Surface]\n  - rxn_008: mol_013, mol_006 -> mol_014 (UV cyanosulfidic photoredox of lactonitrile to lactaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_009: mol_014, mol_007, mol_008 -> mol_015 (Surface Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 threonine aminonitrile) [Surface]\n  - rxn_010: mol_014, mol_007, mol_008 -> mol_015 (Hydrothermal Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 threonine aminonitrile) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_011: mol_007 -> mol_017 (HCN trimerization to aminomalononitrile (AMN)) [Surface]\n  - rxn_012: mol_017, mol_012 -> mol_015 (AMN condensation with acetaldehyde \u2192 threonine/allothreonine aminonitrile) [Surface]\n  - rxn_013: mol_015, mol_002 -> mol_016 (Aminonitrile hydrolysis: threonine aminonitrile \u2192 threonine) [Biochemical]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Full cyanosulfidic photoredox from hydrothermal CO\u2082 (9 steps)\n  - P2: Volcanic discharge HCN/HCHO \u2192 cyanosulfidic photoredox \u2192 Strecker threonine (7 steps)\n  - P3: Volcanic discharge direct acetaldehyde \u2192 photoredox lactaldehyde \u2192 Strecker threonine (5 steps)\n  - P4: Hydrothermal FTT acetaldehyde + volcanic HCN \u2192 photoredox \u2192 surface Strecker (6 steps)\n  - P5: Hydrothermal FTT acetaldehyde \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 hydrothermal Strecker (6 steps)\n  - P6: AMN route with volcanic discharge acetaldehyde (4 steps)\n  - P7: AMN route with hydrothermal FTT acetaldehyde (5 steps)\n  - P8: AMN route with cyanosulfidic photoredox-derived acetaldehyde (8 steps)\n  - P9: Volcanic discharge \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 hydrothermal Strecker threonine (5 steps)\n  - P10: Full hydrothermal origin \u2192 cyanosulfidic chain \u2192 hydrothermal Strecker \u2192 threonine (9 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_007, mol_012, mol_014, mol_015\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 4\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH ON TARGET MOLECULE ===\nThe following research was conducted on the target molecule before network generation. Use it to assess whether the network aligns with known prebiotic chemistry literature.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nPrebiotic Synthesis of Threonine\nMolecule-specific constraints that shape plausible prebiotic routes\nThreonine is a hydroxy-amino acid whose prebiotic formation is complicated by (i) the need to install both an amino group and a hydroxyl-bearing sidechain and (ii) the fact that two diastereomeric products are typically expected: threonine and allothreonine. The co-occurrence of threonine and allothreonine in abiotic product mixtures is explicitly reported in classic spark-discharge experiments, where both \u201cthreonine\u201d and \u201callothreonine\u201d were confirmed among the synthesized amino acids. [1]\nA key practical implication for network design is that many plausible routes do not make threonine \u201cdirectly\u201d from CO\u2082; instead, they converge on a specific aldehyde-level carbonyl precursor\u2014lactaldehyde (2\u2011hydroxypropanal)\u2014followed by Strecker-type conversion to an aminonitrile and then hydrolysis to the amino acid. This lactaldehyde-centered view is articulated both in cyanosulfidic photoredox work (where lactaldehyde is produced photochemically from nitrile/cyanohydrin precursors) and in meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin discussions (where lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the carbonyl precursor for threonine/allothreonine). [2]\nHydrothermal persistence is also a constraint: hydroxy amino acids (including serine and threonine) can undergo dehydration and other degradation pathways during diagenesis/hydrothermal exposure, which matters when evaluating vent-based syntheses or post-synthesis survival. [3]\nKnown prebiotic synthesis routes for threonine\nElectric-discharge (atmospheric / volcanic-plume) synthesis.\nA strong line of experimental evidence for abiotic threonine production comes from spark-discharge experiments designed to simulate reducing (or locally reducing) atmospheres. In the 1958 H\u2082S-rich Miller experiment reanalysis, E. T. Parker[4] and coauthors (2011, Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences) report that residues produced from a spark discharge acting on a gas mixture containing H\u2082S, CH\u2084, NH\u2083, and CO\u2082 contained a broad suite of amino acids and amines, including threonine; chiral amino acids were largely racemic within measurement uncertainty, supporting an abiotic origin (rather than modern biological contamination). [5]\nEarlier work also directly confirmed threonine and allothreonine in discharge products from mixtures including methane, nitrogen, water, and traces of ammonia. [1]\nUV-driven cyanosulfidic photoredox + Strecker assembly via lactaldehyde.\nA second, mechanistically explicit route emerges from cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry associated with Daniel J. Ritson[6] and John D. Sutherland[7] (2013, Angewandte Chemie International Edition). In this system, UV (254 nm) photoredox chemistry reduces nitriles/cyanohydrins to generate aldehydes (including lactaldehyde, the threonine carbonyl precursor), and subsequent addition of HCN and NH\u2083 yields the corresponding Strecker aminonitriles (including the (allo-)threonine aminonitrile). [8]\nA later synthesis-and-systems perspective by Nicholas J. Green[9], Xu, and Sutherland (2021, Journal of the American Chemical Society) explicitly situates this \u201clactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile\u201d step inside a broader UV-photochemical network driven by hydrated-electron photochemistry and cyanosulfidic redox cycling. [10]\nHCN-oligomer / aminomalononitrile (AMN) chemistry as an alternative C\u2013N assembly route.\nA distinct, often-overlooked proposal is that HCN oligomers provide multifunctional C/N building blocks. In this vein, George Thanassi[11] (1975, Journal of Molecular Evolution) reports that reacting aminomalononitrile (a key HCN oligomer) with electrophiles (including aldehydes) followed by hydrolysis yields a range of amino acids, including threonine and allothreonine. This route is attractive for network design because it bypasses the need to pre-form lactaldehyde in bulk; the tradeoff is that selectivity, geochemical plausibility of AMN accumulation, and competing polymerization pathways remain active questions. [12]\nParent-body (meteoritic) Strecker\u2013cyanohydrin synthesis as evidence of a natural \u201cthreonine module.\u201d\nAlthough not an Earth experiment per se, carbonaceous-chondrite organic chemistry provides a natural laboratory for reactions relevant to early Earth delivery and corroborates mechanistic plausibility. A detailed treatment in a Kyushu University-hosted report (associated with threonine/hydroxy-amino-acid analyses in carbonaceous chondrites) describes Strecker-cyanohydrin synthesis where aldehydes/ketones + NH\u2083 \u2192 imines \u2192 CN\u207b addition \u2192 hydrolysis to \u03b1\u2011amino acids, and it explicitly identifies lactaldehyde as the carbonyl precursor for threonine and/or allo-threonine. [13]\nKey intermediates and precursors that define a threonine synthesis network\nAcross the most experimentally grounded routes, threonine sits at the end of a relatively consistent intermediate chain:\nThe minimal \u201cStrecker module\u201d requires a carbonyl compound, ammonia (or another nitrogen source that can generate an imine), and cyanide; the carbonyl required for threonine/allothreonine is lactaldehyde. [14]\nIn cyanosulfidic photoredox networks, the upstream pool can be generated from HCN-derived nitriles and cyanohydrins, with hydrogen sulfide acting as terminal reductant and Cu(I) cyanide functioning as a photoredox-active catalyst/surface. Key intermediates and branch points in the Ritson\u2013Sutherland sequence include: glycolonitrile \u2192 glycolaldehyde (and formaldehyde, acetaldehyde as side/rearranged products), acetaldehyde cyanohydrin (lactonitrile-type node) \u2192 lactaldehyde, and then lactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile in the presence of added HCN and NH\u2083. [8]\nIn spark-discharge contexts, the primary \u201cprecursor-generating\u201d chemistry is atmospheric/plume radical chemistry producing HCN, aldehydes/ketones, and related C\u2013N intermediates that can rain out and further react in surface waters\u2014an explicit motivation for the volcanic-plume framing of Miller-type experiments. [15]\nA key branching control is ammonia availability: the meteoritic discussion emphasizes that ammonia-rich environments favor aminonitrile (amino acid) pathways, whereas ammonia-poor settings favor cyanohydrins and hydroxy acids\u2014directly impacting whether the threonine branch is expressed efficiently. [13]\nReaction mechanisms, conditions, yields, and selectivity\nUV photoredox \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 (allo-)threonine aminonitrile\nThe most quantitatively specified prebiotic route to a threonine precursor is the UV photoredox chemistry of Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.), which directly reports yields for lactaldehyde formation under defined conditions:\nA representative system for first-stage reduction used 10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H\u2082S, 33 mM sodium phosphate, plus solid CuCN (10 mol % relative to glycolonitrile), irradiated at 254 nm in a quartz cuvette; after 2 h, glycolaldehyde (detected as hydrate) formed in 42% yield in solution, alongside other aldehydic products including acetaldehyde. [8]\nCritically, \u201csecond-stage\u201d cyanohydrin photoreductions in the same study yield the dedicated threonine carbonyl precursor: irradiation of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin furnished lactaldehyde in 19% yield (after 2 h irradiation). Lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the Strecker precursor of \u201c(allo-)threonine.\u201d [8]\nDownstream assembly to the threonine aminonitrile is demonstrated by adding HCN and ammonia: when HCN and NH\u2083 were added to photoreduction products, lactaldehyde was \u201csmoothly converted\u201d via its cyanohydrin to the (allo-)threonine Strecker intermediate aminonitrile (aminonitrile 22 in the paper\u2019s numbering). Timescales reported for aminonitrile formation in these systems are days to weeks, indicating that geochemical \u201cholding times\u201d and compartmentalization could matter. [8]\nMechanistically, this route couples: (i) photoredox reduction of nitrile/cyanohydrin nodes to aldehydes (including lactaldehyde) and (ii) conventional Strecker-type conversion (aldehyde \u2192 imine \u2192 aminonitrile) once NH\u2083 and CN\u207b/HCN are available; hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the expected final step in Strecker frameworks, and the meteoritic Strecker discussion explicitly frames hydrolysis of aminonitriles as producing \u03b1-amino acids. [16]\nA systems-level restatement by Green, Xu, and Sutherland (2021, JACS) emphasizes that photoreduction of the relevant cyanohydrin node leads to lactaldehyde, and lactaldehyde then yields a threonine precursor aminonitrile by addition of HCN and NH\u2083, embedding this step inside a broader cyanosulfidic network. [10]\nSpark discharge / volcanic plume simulation \u2192 threonine in complex amino-acid mixtures\nIn Parker et al. (2011, PNAS), reanalysis of archived Miller-type residues from a 1958 discharge experiment (gas mixture including CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S, CO\u2082) identified 23 amino acids and 4 amines; the paper explicitly notes threonine among amino acids generated by this discharge chemistry and interprets racemic chiral amino acids (D/L \u2248 1 within stated uncertainty) as evidence against modern biological contamination. [17]\nQuantitatively, Parker et al. present product abundances as molar ratios relative to glycine (=1). In their Fig. 2, threonine appears at roughly the 10\u207b\u00b2 scale relative to glycine (order-of-magnitude read from the plotted point on a log molar-ratio axis). [18]\nIn an earlier and more expansive discharge study, Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) report that electric discharges in a methane\u2013nitrogen\u2013water system (with traces of ammonia) produced a wide set of amino acids, and explicitly confirm both threonine and allothreonine (alongside serine and others) by ion-exchange chromatography and GC\u2013MS. [1]\nThese discharge pathways are usually interpreted as producing amino acids via formation of reactive small C\u2013N intermediates (HCN, aldehydes/ketones) followed by aqueous-phase assembly (often Strecker-type), and Parker et al. explicitly connect volcanic lightning + reduced gases to generation of HCN and other intermediates that can wash out and accumulate in tidal settings. [15]\nHCN-oligomer (AMN) electrophile chemistry \u2192 threonine/allothreonine after hydrolysis\nThanassi (1975, J. Mol. Evol.) provides experimental evidence that aminomalononitrile-derived chemistry can yield threonine and allothreonine after hydrolysis when AMN is reacted with electrophiles (including aldehydes) under mild conditions. The study explicitly states that amino acids (including threonine/allothreonine) were identified and quantified from hydrolysates. [12]\nFrom a mechanism standpoint, AMN functions as a multifunctional C\u2013N synthon, offering an alternative to \u201csingle-carbonyl + HCN + NH\u2083\u201d assembly; its prebiotic plausibility hinges on whether AMN can accumulate at useful concentrations without being diverted into intractable HCN polymers\u2014an issue treated as part of the broader \u201cHCN chemistry\u201d challenge space in origin-of-life literature. [19]\nHydrothermal Strecker-type synthesis: relevance and limitations for threonine specifically\nHydrothermal Strecker synthesis under mineral-buffered redox conditions is experimentally documented for several amino acids, demonstrating that Strecker chemistry can proceed in plausible vent/flank conditions if aldehydes/ketones and cyanide are available. Andersson & Holm (2000, Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere) summarize hydrothermal experiments (Hennet et al., 1992) using HCN, CH\u2082O, and NH\u2084Cl at 150\u202f\u00b0C and 10 bar in the presence of a pyrite\u2013pyrrhotite\u2013magnetite buffer; reported products include mM-level glycine (\u22489\u201312 mM) and lower but measurable levels of other amino acids (e.g., alanine \u22480.5\u20131.3 mM; aspartate and glutamate at \u22480.28\u20130.36 mM and \u22480.064\u20130.100 mM, respectively). [20]\nHowever, threonine itself is not among the explicitly tabulated products in that summary table, highlighting a practical bottleneck: even if hydrothermal Strecker chemistry is viable in general, demonstrating threonine specifically requires (i) access to lactaldehyde (or a direct hydrothermal pathway to lactaldehyde/lactaldehyde equivalents) and (ii) managing the competing high-temperature degradation chemistry that can disproportionately affect hydroxy amino acids. [21]\nA further caution for purely vent-centric \u201cCO\u2082 \u2192 amino acids\u201d narratives is that some claimed FeS/H\u2082S-driven syntheses have not held up; Keefe et al. (1995, PNAS) report that their FeS/H\u2082S system did not produce amino acids from CO\u2082 (nor via proposed reductive amination/carboxylation), sharpening the distinction between (a) Strecker-type routes requiring carbonyls + CN\u207b and (b) hypothesized direct CO\u2082 fixation-to-amino-acid routes. [22]\nMineral catalysts and surfaces implicated in threonine-relevant steps\nCu(I) cyanide (CuCN) as a photoredox-active heterogeneous catalyst/surface.\nIn the Ritson\u2013Sutherland photoredox system, CuCN is added as a solid; mixing generates a fine dark precipitate that is irradiated, consistent with heterogeneous photoredox cycling and surface-mediated electron production. [8]\nGreen et al. (2021, JACS) discuss Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanocuprate photoredox cycling as a route to hydrated electrons and connect this catalysis to the production of amino-acid Strecker precursors, including the threonine aminonitrile precursor derived from lactaldehyde. [10]\nSulfide minerals as sources of H\u2082S (reductant) and CuCN-generating Cu\u2013S chemistry.\nRitson & Sutherland explicitly note a plausible geochemical source: dissolution of copper sulfide minerals in cyanide solution could generate CuCN catalysts, and dissolution of FeS could provide additional H\u2082S reductant\u2014an explicit mineralogical bridge between rock chemistry and the photoredox network. [8]\nFerrocyanide as a cyanide concentrator and potential \u201cfeedstock conditioner.\u201d\nRitson & Sutherland also emphasize that cyanide can be concentrated by complexation with Fe\u00b2\u207a to form ferrocyanide, and that thermal processing of mixed ferrocyanide salts can yield mixtures containing cyanide, ammonia, and cyanamide upon rehydration\u2014reagents directly relevant to Strecker chemistry and linked nucleotide-precursor reactions. [8]\nPyrite\u2013pyrrhotite\u2013magnetite and silicate buffers in hydrothermal simulations.\nAndersson & Holm\u2019s redox-buffered hydrothermal framework highlights the use of pyrite (FeS\u2082), pyrrhotite (FeS), and magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) to constrain oxygen fugacity (redox), and K\u2011feldspar\u2013muscovite\u2013quartz assemblages to influence pH via ion activity control\u2014key when extrapolating laboratory hydrothermal yields to natural settings. [20]\nEnvironmental context and the main open challenges for threonine\nMost relevant environments by route.\nFor spark-discharge threonine formation, the empirical basis is strongest for localized, reducing volcanic-plume or eruption-lightning environments, where mixtures of reduced gases (e.g., CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S) and oxidized components (e.g., CO\u2082) can coexist transiently; Parker et al. explicitly argue such localized plume chemistry could generate HCN and other intermediates that rain out and accumulate in tidal zones, supporting subsequent aqueous synthesis steps. [15]\nFor UV photoredox threonine-precursor formation, the most relevant setting is a sunlit surface environment that can sustain UV photochemistry (at least episodically) and maintain access to cyanide and sulfide redox pairs; Green et al. note that low H\u2082S solubility and low crustal copper abundance would restrict Cu/H\u2082S cyanosulfidic networks to specific terrains (e.g., copper-rich, alkaline pools), a critical geochemical constraint on global plausibility. [23]\nFor Strecker chemistry in aqueous-alteration contexts (meteorites or analogous wet-rock systems), the carbonaceous-chondrite analysis emphasizes that ammonia abundance and redox state influence whether aminonitriles (\u2192 amino acids) are favored over cyanohydrins (\u2192 hydroxy acids), and it frames threonine/allothreonine formation as dependent on lactaldehyde availability. [13]\nKey bottlenecks and debates.\nA central unresolved bottleneck is sourcing and sustaining lactaldehyde (and/or its direct nitrile/cyanohydrin precursors) at concentrations compatible with downstream Strecker chemistry. The meteoritic analysis proposes that lactaldehyde may be relatively less available than glycolaldehyde/hydroxyacetone because its formation depends on less abundant ethanol-derived radical chemistry in interstellar ices, which would suppress threonine relative to serine/\u03b1\u2011methylserine\u2014an argument that can be repurposed as a constraint on Earth scenarios if analogous precursor biases held in terrestrial inventories. [13]\nAnother challenge is selectivity and stereochemistry. Multiple experimental contexts support predominantly racemic production for chiral amino acids in abiotic syntheses (e.g., spark discharge products; racemic allo-threonine in some meteoritic extracts where it can be resolved cleanly), but threonine\u2019s second stereocenter makes diastereomeric mixtures (threonine/allothreonine) a near-default outcome unless additional selection mechanisms are invoked. [24]\nA third major issue is compatibility of synthesis with survival. Hydroxy amino acids can undergo dehydration and other transformations during heating or long residence times; this is directly relevant to vent models (where high temperatures can accelerate degradation) and also to post-synthesis processing. [3]\nFinally, there is an ongoing debate over whether threonine should be expected to be among the earliest-abundant amino acids at all. The experimental record shows that threonine is certainly possible abiotically (spark discharge; cyanosulfidic networks yielding its Strecker precursors), but it is also plausibly scarcity-limited by precursor availability (lactaldehyde) and stability constraints (hydroxy amino-acid degradation), leaving room for models where threonine is incorporated later into biochemistry relative to simpler amino acids. [25]\n \n[1] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\n[2] [6] [8] [25] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4269183/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4269183/\n[3] h