 \"rxn_013\": 0.90\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.84,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.88,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.82,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.90,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.85,\n            \"feedback\": \"This is the core Ritson\u2013Sutherland cyanosulfidic photoredox pathway, well-supported by literature. Spark discharge provides HCN and formaldehyde, cyanohydrin formation leads to glycolonitrile, UV cyanosulfidic photoreduction yields glycolaldehyde/acetaldehyde, second-stage photoreduction gives lactaldehyde, and Strecker assembly completes to threonine. The 42% yield for glycolaldehyde and 19% for lactaldehyde are experimentally documented. Minor concern: rxn_006 producing acetaldehyde as a co-product from glycolonitrile photoreduction should specify more precisely how the C\u2013O bond is lost. Missing explicit CuCN catalyst specification for rxn_006 and rxn_008.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\n                \"Specify CuCN as mineral photoredox catalyst in rxn_006 and rxn_008\",\n                \"Consider whether acetaldehyde coproduction in rxn_006 is a separate mechanistic event or comes from glycolaldehyde rearrangement\"\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_001\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_007\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_008\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_009\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_013\": 0.90\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.87,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.88,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.80,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.90,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.86,\n            \"feedback\": \"Elegant short pathway using acetaldehyde produced directly by spark discharge, followed by cyanohydrin formation (lactonitrile), UV photoreduction to lactaldehyde, Strecker assembly, and hydrolysis. All individual steps are well-precedented. The discharge production of acetaldehyde alongside HCN and NH\u2083 is experimentally confirmed (Parker et al. 2011, Ring et al. 1972). This is one of the most plausible and concise routes in the network.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n            \"suggestions\": [\n                \"Specify CuCN catalyst and H\u2082S reductant more explicitly in rxn_008\"\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_004\": 0.60,\n                \"rxn_001\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_007\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_008\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_009\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_013\": 0.90\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.78,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.82,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.85,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.81,\n            \"feedback\": \"Cross-environmental pathway combining hydrothermal FTT acetaldehyde with volcanic HCN. The FTT synthesis of acetaldehyde (rxn_004) is the weakest link\u2014while FTT synthesis of hydrocarbons and simple oxygenates is documented on Fe/Ni minerals, specific yields of acetaldehyde are poorly quantified. The remainder of the pathway (cyanohydrin \u2192 photoreduction \u2192 Strecker) is solid.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\n                \"Provide more specific mineral catalyst for FTT (e.g., magnetite, awaruite)\",\n                \"Consider whether acetaldehyde survives transport from hydrothermal to surface environment\"\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_004\": 0.60,\n                \"rxn_007\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_008\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_010\": 0.60,\n                \"rxn_013\": 0.90\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.68,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.72,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.70,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.70,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.69,\n            \"feedback\": \"This pathway relies heavily on hydrothermal conditions for both acetaldehyde production (FTT) and Strecker assembly. Literature explicitly notes that threonine is NOT among the amino acids reported from hydrothermal Strecker experiments (Andersson & Holm 2000), and hydroxy amino acids undergo dehydration at elevated temperatures. The hydrothermal Strecker step (rxn_010) is the major vulnerability. Additionally, there is an environmental coherence issue: rxn_008 (UV photoreduction to lactaldehyde) is a Surface reaction sandwiched between hydrothermal steps.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_010\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\n                \"Consider replacing hydrothermal Strecker (rxn_010) with surface Strecker (rxn_009) given hydroxy amino acid instability at high T\",\n                \"Address the environmental transition: lactaldehyde made by UV photoreduction at surface would need to be transported back to hydrothermal zone for rxn_010\"\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_001\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_011\": 0.78,\n                \"rxn_012\": 0.75,\n                \"rxn_013\": 0.90\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.80,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.83,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.75,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.82,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.80,\n            \"feedback\": \"Short AMN-based route grounded in Thanassi (1975). Spark discharge provides both HCN and acetaldehyde; HCN trimerizes to AMN; AMN condenses with acetaldehyde to give threonine aminonitrile; hydrolysis yields threonine. Chemically plausible and experimentally supported, though AMN accumulation at useful concentrations (avoiding runaway HCN polymerization) remains a recognized challenge in the literature. The pathway elegantly bypasses the lactaldehyde bottleneck.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\n                \"Address AMN concentration/accumulation challenge explicitly\",\n                \"Specify conditions (pH, temperature) under which HCN trimerization favors AMN over higher polymers\"\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_004\": 0.60,\n                \"rxn_001\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_011\": 0.78,\n                \"rxn_012\": 0.75,\n                \"rxn_013\": 0.90\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.74,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.78,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.80,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.78,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.77,\n            \"feedback\": \"AMN route using hydrothermal FTT acetaldehyde. Combines hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation with surface AMN chemistry. Good environmental flow but limited by the speculative FTT acetaldehyde step. Otherwise follows the same Thanassi mechanism as P6.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\n                \"Strengthen the FTT acetaldehyde evidence or provide alternative hydrothermal acetaldehyde source\"\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_001\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_005\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_006\": 0.70,\n                \"rxn_011\": 0.78,\n                \"rxn_012\": 0.75,\n                \"rxn_013\": 0.90\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.76,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.72,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.75,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.78,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.74,\n            \"feedback\": \"Long route combining cyanosulfidic acetaldehyde generation with AMN condensation. Somewhat redundant: if you have the cyanosulfidic apparatus running, the direct lactaldehyde \u2192 Strecker route (P2/P3) is more efficient. The AMN branch adds complexity without clear benefit when acetaldehyde is already being routed through the cyanosulfidic channel. Chemical feasibility is adequate but pathway coherence suffers from unnecessary length.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\n                \"This pathway could be simplified; it represents a hybrid that is less efficient than either the pure cyanosulfidic or pure AMN route\"\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_001\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_007\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_008\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_010\": 0.60,\n                \"rxn_013\": 0.90\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.75,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.76,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.68,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.75,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.73,\n            \"feedback\": \"Similar to P5 but starts from volcanic discharge. The hydrothermal Strecker step (rxn_010) remains problematic given the lack of experimental evidence for threonine from hydrothermal Strecker and the known instability of hydroxy amino acids at elevated temperatures. The environmental retrograde (surface UV photoreduction \u2192 hydrothermal Strecker) is also geologically awkward.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\n                \"Use surface Strecker (rxn_009) instead of hydrothermal (rxn_010) to avoid thermal degradation of threonine\"\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_002\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_003\": 0.60,\n                \"rxn_005\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_006\": 0.70,\n                \"rxn_007\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_008\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_010\": 0.60,\n                \"rxn_013\": 0.90\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.70,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.72,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.75,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.72,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.71,\n            \"feedback\": \"Longest pathway combining the weakest hydrothermal steps (formate\u2192formaldehyde, FTT acetaldehyde) with the problematic hydrothermal Strecker. While it demonstrates maximal cross-environmental connectivity, each weak link compounds. The formate-to-formaldehyde reduction and hydrothermal Strecker for a hydroxy amino acid are both poorly supported.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_010\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\n                \"Replace rxn_003 with a better-supported formaldehyde source\",\n                \"Replace rxn_010 with surface Strecker (rxn_009)\"\n            ]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": 0.84,\n    \"network_feedback\": \"This is a well-designed synthesis network for threonine that closely mirrors the literature landscape. The network correctly identifies lactaldehyde as the key carbonyl hub for threonine biosynthesis and implements three experimentally grounded routes: (1) the Ritson\u2013Sutherland cyanosulfidic photoredox chain, (2) spark-discharge precursor generation, and (3) the Thanassi AMN condensation. Hub molecules (HCN, acetaldehyde, lactaldehyde, threonine aminonitrile) are well-chosen and provide genuine convergence. Literature alignment is excellent\u2014the network references all major experimental studies and reflects known yields and conditions. Key strengths: (i) multiple convergent routes to the target, (ii) realistic environmental transitions with hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation feeding into surface UV chemistry, (iii) correct identification of the lactaldehyde bottleneck. Key weaknesses: (i) the formate-to-formaldehyde hydrothermal reduction (rxn_003) is thermodynamically uphill and poorly documented; (ii) FTT synthesis of acetaldehyde specifically (rxn_004) is speculative; (iii) hydrothermal Strecker synthesis for threonine (rxn_010) lacks direct experimental support and conflicts with known hydroxy amino acid thermal instability; (iv) surface photoredox reactions (rxn_006, rxn_008) should explicitly specify CuCN as the mineral photoredox catalyst per Ritson & Sutherland; (v) rxn_006 producing acetaldehyde as a co-product of glycolonitrile photoreduction needs mechanistic clarification. Despite these issues, four pathways (P2, P3, P4, P6) achieve approval-level confidence, and the overall network architecture is sound and well-grounded in the experimental prebiotic chemistry literature.\",\n    \"approved\": true,\n    \"hub_quality\": 0.90,\n    \"convergence_quality\": 0.88\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_002": 0.85, "rxn_003": 0.6, "rxn_005": 0.9, "rxn_006": 0.7, "rxn_007": 0.9, "rxn_008": 0.85, "rxn_009": 0.9, "rxn_013": 0.9}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.72, "pathway_coherence": 0.75, "environmental_progression": 0.82, "target_achievement": 0.8, "overall_confidence": 0.76, "feedback": "Longest pathway; formate-to-formaldehyde reduction (rxn_003) i