: 0.72, "environmental_progression": 0.7, "target_achievement": 0.7, "overall_confidence": 0.69, "feedback": "This pathway relies heavily on hydrothermal conditions for both acetaldehyde production (FTT) and Strecker assembly. Literature explicitly notes that threonine is NOT among the amino acids reported from hydrothermal Strecker experiments (Andersson & Holm 2000), and hydroxy amino acids undergo dehydration at elevated temperatures. The hydrothermal Strecker step (rxn_010) is the major vulnerability. Additionally, there is an environmental coherence issue: rxn_008 (UV photoreduction to lactaldehyde) is a Surface reaction sandwiched between hydrothermal steps.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_004", "rxn_010"], "suggestions": ["Consider replacing hydrothermal Strecker (rxn_010) with surface Strecker (rxn_009) given hydroxy amino acid instability at high T", "Address the environmental transition: lactaldehyde made by UV photoreduction at surface would need to be transported back to hydrothermal zone for rxn_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.85, "rxn_011": 0.78, "rxn_012": 0.75, "rxn_013": 0.9}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.8, "pathway_coherence": 0.83, "environmental_progression": 0.75, "target_achievement": 0.82, "overall_confidence": 0.8, "feedback": "Short AMN-based route grounded in Thanassi (1975). Spark discharge provides both HCN and acetaldehyde; HCN trimerizes to AMN; AMN condenses with acetaldehyde to give threonine aminonitrile; hydrolysis yields threonine. Chemically plausible and experimentally supported, though AMN accumulation at useful concentrations (avoiding runaway HCN polymerization) remains a recognized challenge in the literature. The pathway elegantly bypasses the lactaldehyde bottleneck.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_011"], "suggestions": ["Address AMN concentration/accumulation challenge explicitly", "Specify conditions (pH, temperature) under which HCN trimerization favors A