provide genuine convergence. Literature alignment is excellent\u2014the network references all major experimental studies and reflects known yields and conditions. Key strengths: (i) multiple convergent routes to the target, (ii) realistic environmental transitions with hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation feeding into surface UV chemistry, (iii) correct identification of the lactaldehyde bottleneck. Key weaknesses: (i) the formate-to-formaldehyde hydrothermal reduction (rxn_003) is thermodynamically uphill and poorly documented; (ii) FTT synthesis of acetaldehyde specifically (rxn_004) is speculative; (iii) hydrothermal Strecker synthesis for threonine (rxn_010) lacks direct experimental support and conflicts with known hydroxy amino acid thermal instability; (iv) surface photoredox reactions (rxn_006, rxn_008) should explicitly specify CuCN as the mineral photoredox catalyst per Ritson & Sutherland; (v) rxn_006 producing acetaldehyde as a co-product of glycolonitrile photoreduction needs mechanistic clarification. Despite these issues, four pathways (P2, P3, P4, P6) achieve approval-level confidence, and the overall network architecture is sound and well-grounded in the experimental prebiotic chemistry literature.", "approved": true, "hub_quality": 0.9, "convergence_quality": 0.88}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 286014.94121551514, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-16T22:08:44.375951", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Threonine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Threonine. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nPrebiotic Synthesis of Threonine\nMolecule-specific constraints that shape plausible prebiotic routes\nThreonine is a hydroxy-amino acid whose prebiotic formation is complicated by (i) the need to install both an amino group and a hydroxyl-bearing sidechain and (ii) the fact that two diastereomeric products are typically expected: threonine and allothreonine. The co-occurrence of threonine and allothreonine in abiotic product mixtures is explicitly reported in classic spark-discharge experiments, where both \u201cthreonine\u201d and \u201callothreonine\u201d were confirmed among the synthesized amino acids. [1]\nA key practical implication for network design is that many plausible routes do not make threonine \u201cdirectly\u201d from CO\u2082; instead, they converge on a specific aldehyde-level carbonyl precursor\u2014lactaldehyde (2\u2011hydroxypropanal)\u2014followed by Strecker-type conversion to an aminonitrile and then hydrolysis to the amino acid. This lactaldehyde-centered view is articulated both in cyanosulfidic photoredox work (where lactaldehyde is produced photochemically from nitrile/cyanohydrin precursors) and in meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin discussions (where lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the carbonyl precursor for threonine/allothreonine). [2]\nHydrothermal persistence is also a constraint: hydroxy amino acids (including serine and threonine) can undergo dehydration and other degradation pathways during diagenesis/hydrothermal exposure, which matters when evaluating vent-based syntheses or post-synthesis survival. [3]\nKnown prebiotic synthesis routes for threonine\nElectric-discharge (atmospheric / volcanic-plume) synthesis.\nA strong line of experimental evidence for abiotic threonine production comes from spark-discharge experiments designed to simulate reducing (or locally reducing) atmospheres. In the 1958 H\u2082S-rich Miller experiment reanalysis, E. T. Parker[4] and coauthors (2011, Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences) report that residues produced from a spark discharge acting on a gas mixture containing H\u2082S, CH\u2084, NH\u2083, and CO\u2082 contained a broad suite of amino acids and amines, including threonine; chiral amino acids were largely racemic within measurement uncertainty, supporting an abiotic origin (rather than modern biological contamination). [5]\nEarlier work also directly confirmed threonine and allothreonine in discharge products from mixtures including methane, nitrogen, water, and traces of ammonia. [1]\nUV-driven cyanosulfidic photoredox + Strecker assembly via lactaldehyde.\nA second, mechanistically explicit route emerges from cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry associated with Daniel J. Ritson[6] and John D. Sutherland[7] (2013, Angewandte Chemie International Edition). In this system, UV (254 nm) photoredox chemistry reduces nitriles/cyanohydrins to generate aldehydes (including lactaldehyde, the threonine carbonyl precursor), and subsequent addition of HCN and NH\u2083 yields the corresponding Strecker aminonitriles (including the (allo-)threonine aminonitrile). [8]\nA later synthesis-and-systems perspective by Nicholas J. Green[9], Xu, and Sutherland (2021, Journal of the American Chemical Society) explicitly situates this \u201clactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile\u201d step inside a broader UV-photochemical network driven by hydrated-electron photochemistry and cyanosulfidic redox cycling. [10]\nHCN-oligomer / aminomalononitrile (AMN) chemistry as an alternative C\u2013N assembly route.\nA distinct, often-overlooked proposal is that HCN oligomers provide multifunctional C/N building blocks. In this vein, George Thanassi[11] (1975, Journal of Molecular Evolution) reports that reacting aminomalononitrile (a key HCN oligomer) with electrophiles (including aldehydes) followed by hydrolysis yields a range of amino acids, including threonine and allothreonine. This route is attractive for network design because it bypasses the need to pre-form lactaldehyde in bulk; the tradeoff is that selectivity, geochemical plausibility of AMN accumulation, and competing polymerization pathways remain active questions. [12]\nParent-body (meteoritic) Strecker\u2013cyanohydrin synthesis as evidence of a natural \u201cthreonine module.\u201d\nAlthough not an Earth experiment per se, carbonaceous-chondrite organic chemistry provides a natural laboratory for reactions relevant to early Earth delivery and corroborates mechanistic plausibility. A detailed treatment in a Kyushu University-hosted report (associated with threonine/hydroxy-amino-acid analyses in carbonaceous chondrites) describes Strecker-cyanohydrin synthesis where aldehydes/ketones + NH\u2083 \u2192 imines \u2192 CN\u207b addition \u2192 hydrolysis to \u03b1\u2011amino acids, and it explicitly identifies lactaldehyde as the carbonyl precursor for threonine and/or allo-threonine. [13]\nKey intermediates and precursors that define a threonine synthesis network\nAcross the most experimentally grounded routes, threonine sits at the end of a relatively consistent intermediate chain:\nThe minimal \u201cStrecker module\u201d requires a carbonyl compound, ammonia (or another nitrogen source that can generate an imine), and cyanide; the carbonyl required for threonine/allothreonine is lactaldehyde. [14]\nIn cyanosulfidic photoredox networks, the upstream pool can be generated from HCN-derived nitriles and cyanohydrins, with hydrogen sulfide acting as terminal reductant and Cu(I) cyanide functioning as a photoredox-active catalyst/surface. Key intermediates and branch points in the Ritson\u2013Sutherland sequence include: glycolonitrile \u2192 glycolaldehyde (and formaldehyde, acetaldehyde as side/rearranged products), acetaldehyde cyanohydrin (lactonitrile-type node) \u2192 lactaldehyde, and then lactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile in the presence of added HCN and NH\u2083. [8]\nIn spark-discharge contexts, the primary \u201cprecursor-generating\u201d chemistry is atmospheric/plume radical chemistry producing HCN, aldehydes/ketones, and related C\u2013N intermediates that can rain out and further react in surface waters\u2014an explicit motivation for the volcanic-plume framing of Miller-type experiments. [15]\nA key branching control is ammonia availability: the meteoritic discussion emphasizes that ammonia-rich environments favor aminonitrile (amino acid) pathways, whereas ammonia-poor settings favor cyanohydrins and hydroxy acids\u2014directly impacting whether the threonine branch is expressed efficiently. [13]\nReaction mechanisms, conditions, yields, and selectivity\nUV photoredox \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 (allo-)threonine aminonitrile\nThe most quantitatively specified prebiotic route to a threonine precursor is the UV photoredox chemistry of Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.), which directly reports yields for lactaldehyde formation under defined conditions:\nA representative system for first-stage reduction used 10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H\u2082S, 33 mM sodium phosphate, plus solid CuCN (10 mol % relative to glycolonitrile), irradiated at 254 nm in a quartz cuvette; after 2 h, glycolaldehyde (detected as hydrate) formed in 42% yield in solution, alongside other aldehydic products including acetaldehyde. [8]\nCritically, \u201csecond-stage\u201d cyanohydrin photoreductions in the same study yield the dedicated threonine carbonyl precursor: irradiation of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin furnished lactaldehyde in 19% yield (after 2 h irradiation). Lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the Strecker precursor of \u201c(allo-)threonine.\u201d [8]\nDownstream assembly to the threonine aminonitrile is demonstrated by adding HCN and ammonia: when HCN and NH\u2083 were added to photoreduction products, lactaldehyde was \u201csmoothly converted\u201d via its cyanohydrin to the (allo-)threonine Strecker intermediate aminonitrile (aminonitrile 22 in the paper\u2019s numbering). Timescales reported for aminonitrile formation in these systems are days to weeks, indicating that geochemical \u201cholding times\u201d and compartmentalization could matter. [8]\nMechanistically, this route couples: (i) photoredox reduction of nitrile/cyanohydrin nodes to aldehydes (including lactaldehyde) and (ii) conventional Strecker-type conversion (aldehyde \u2192 imine \u2192 aminonitrile) once NH\u2083 and CN\u207b/HCN are available; hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the expected final step in Strecker frameworks, and the meteoritic Strecker discussion explicitly frames hydrolysis of aminonitriles as producing \u03b1-amino acids. [16]\nA systems-level restatement by Green, Xu, and Sutherland (2021, JACS) emphasizes that photoreduction of the relevant cyanohydrin node leads to lactaldehyde, and lactaldehyde then yields a threonine precursor aminonitrile by addition of HCN and NH\u2083, embedding this step inside a broader cyanosulfidic network. [10]\nSpark discharge / volcanic plume simulation \u2192 threonine in complex amino-acid mixtures\nIn Parker et al. (2011, PNAS), reanalysis of archived Miller-type residues from a 1958 discharge experiment (gas mixture including CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S, CO\u2082) identified 23 amino acids and 4 amines; the paper explicitly notes threonine among amino acids generated by this discharge chemistry and interprets racemic chiral amino acids (D/L \u2248 1 within stated uncertainty) as evidence against modern biological contamination. [17]\nQuantitatively, Parker et al. present product abundances as molar ratios relative to glycine (=1). In their Fig. 2, threonine appears at roughly the 10\u207b\u00b2 scale relative to glycine (order-of-magnitude read from the plotted point on a log molar-ratio axis). [18]\nIn an earlier and more expansive discharge study, Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) report that electric discharges in a methane\u2013nitrogen\u2013water system (with traces of ammonia) produced a wide set of amino acids, and explicitly confirm both threonine and allothreonine (alongside serine and others) by ion-exchange chromatography and GC\u2013MS. [1]\nThese discharge pathways are usually interpreted as producing amino acids via formation of reactive small C\u2013N intermediates (HCN, aldehydes/ketones) followed by aqueous-phase assembly (often Strecker-type), and Parker et al. explicitly connect volcanic lightning + reduced gases to generation of HCN and other intermediates that can wash out and accumulate in tidal settings. [15]\nHCN-oligomer (AMN) electrophile chemistry \u2192 threonine/allothreonine after hydrolysis\nThanassi (1975, J. Mol. Evol.) provides experimental evidence that aminomalononitrile-derived chemistry can yield threonine and allothreonine after hydrolysis when AMN is reacted with electrophiles (including aldehydes) under mild conditions. The study explicitly states that amino acids (including threonine/allothreonine) were identified and quantified from hydrolysates. [12]\nFrom a mechanism standpoint, AMN functions as a multifunctional C\u2013N synthon, offering an alternative to \u201csingle-carbonyl + HCN + NH\u2083\u201d assembly; its prebiotic plausibility hinges on whether AMN can accumulate at useful concentrations without being diverted into intractable HCN polymers\u2014an issue treated as part of the broader \u201cHCN chemistry\u201d challenge space in origin-of-life literature. [19]\nHydrothermal Strecker-type synthesis: relevance and limitations for threonine specifically\nHydrothermal Strecker synthesis under mineral-buffered redox conditions is experimentally documented for several amino acids, demonstrating that Strecker chemistry can proceed in plausible vent/flank conditions if aldehydes/ketones and cyanide are available. Andersson & Holm (2000, Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere) summarize hydrothermal experiments (Hennet et al., 1992) using HCN, CH\u2082O, and NH\u2084Cl at 150\u202f\u00b0C and 10 bar in the presence of a pyrite\u2013pyrrhotite\u2013magnetite buffer; reported products include mM-level glycine (\u22489\u201312 mM) and lower but measurable levels of other amino acids (e.g., alanine \u22480.5\u20131.3 mM; aspartate and glutamate at \u22480.28\u20130.36 mM and \u22480.064\u20130.100 mM, respectively). [20]\nHowever, threonine itself is not among the explicitly tabulated products in that summary table, highlighting a practical bottleneck: even if hydrothermal Strecker chemistry is viable in general, demonstrating threonine specifically requires (i) access to lactaldehyde (or a direct hydrothermal pathway to lactaldehyde/lactaldehyde equivalents) and (ii) managing the competing high-temperature degradation chemistry that can disproportionately affect hydroxy amino acids. [21]\nA further caution for purely vent-centric \u201cCO\u2082 \u2192 amino acids\u201d narratives is that some claimed FeS/H\u2082S-driven syntheses have not held up; Keefe et al. (1995, PNAS) report that their FeS/H\u2082S system did not produce amino acids from CO\u2082 (nor via proposed reductive amination/carboxylation), sharpening the distinction between (a) Strecker-type routes requiring carbonyls + CN\u207b and (b) hypothesized direct CO\u2082 fixation-to-amino-acid routes. [22]\nMineral catalysts and surfaces implicated in threonine-relevant steps\nCu(I) cyanide (CuCN) as a photoredox-active heterogeneous catalyst/surface.\nIn the Ritson\u2013Sutherland photoredox system, CuCN is added as a solid; mixing generates a fine dark precipitate that is irradiated, consistent with heterogeneous photoredox cycling and surface-mediated electron production. [8]\nGreen et al. (2021, JACS) discuss Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanocuprate photoredox cycling as a route to hydrated electrons and connect this catalysis to the production of amino-acid Strecker precursors, including the threonine aminonitrile precursor derived from lactaldehyde. [10]\nSulfide minerals as sources of H\u2082S (reductant) and CuCN-generating Cu\u2013S chemistry.\nRitson & Sutherland explicitly note a plausible geochemical source: dissolution of copper sulfide minerals in cyanide solution could generate CuCN catalysts, and dissolution of FeS could provide additional H\u2082S reductant\u2014an explicit mineralogical bridge between rock chemistry and the photoredox network. [8]\nFerrocyanide as a cyanide concentrator and potential \u201cfeedstock conditioner.\u201d\nRitson & Sutherland also emphasize that cyanide can be concentrated by complexation with Fe\u00b2\u207a to form ferrocyanide, and that thermal processing of mixed ferrocyanide salts can yield mixtures containing cyanide, ammonia, and cyanamide upon rehydration\u2014reagents directly relevant to Strecker chemistry and linked nucleotide-precursor reactions. [8]\nPyrite\u2013pyrrhotite\u2013magnetite and silicate buffers in hydrothermal simulations.\nAndersson & Holm\u2019s redox-buffered hydrothermal framework highlights the use of pyrite (FeS\u2082), pyrrhotite (FeS), and magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) to constrain oxygen fugacity (redox), and K\u2011feldspar\u2013muscovite\u2013quartz assemblages to influence pH via ion activity control\u2014key when extrapolating laboratory hydrothermal yields to natural settings. [20]\nEnvironmental context and the main open challenges for threonine\nMost relevant environments by route.\nFor spark-discharge threonine formation, the empirical basis is strongest for localized, reducing volcanic-plume or eruption-lightning environments, where mixtures of reduced gases (e.g., CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S) and oxidized components (e.g., CO\u2082) can coexist transiently; Parker et al. explicitly argue such localized plume chemistry could generate HCN and other intermediates that rain out and accumulate in tidal zones, supporting subsequent aqueous synthesis steps. [15]\nFor UV photoredox threonine-precursor formation, the most relevant setting is a sunlit surface environment that can sustain UV photochemistry (at least episodically) and maintain access to cyanide and sulfide redox pairs; Green et al. note that low H\u2082S solubility and low crustal copper abundance would restrict Cu/H\u2082S cyanosulfidic networks to specific terrains (e.g., copper-rich, alkaline pools), a critical geochemical constraint on global plausibility. [23]\nFor Strecker chemistry in aqueous-alteration contexts (meteorites or analogous wet-rock systems), the carbonaceous-chondrite analysis emphasizes that ammonia abundance and redox state influence whether aminonitriles (\u2192 amino acids) are favored over cyanohydrins (\u2192 hydroxy acids), and it frames threonine/allothreonine formation as dependent on lactaldehyde availability. [13]\nKey bottlenecks and debates.\nA central unresolved bottleneck is sourcing and sustaining lactaldehyde (and/or its direct nitrile/cyanohydrin precursors) at concentrations compatible with downstream Strecker chemistry. The meteoritic analysis proposes that lactaldehyde may be relatively less available than glycolaldehyde/hydroxyacetone because its formation depends on less abundant ethanol-derived radical chemistry in interstellar ices, which would suppress threonine relative to serine/\u03b1\u2011methylserine\u2014an argument that can be repurposed as a constraint on Earth scenarios if analogous precursor biases held in terrestrial inventories. [13]\nAnother challenge is selectivity and stereochemistry. Multiple experimental contexts support predominantly racemic production for chiral amino acids in abiotic syntheses (e.g., spark discharge products; racemic allo-threonine in some meteoritic extracts where it can be resolved cleanly), but threonine\u2019s second stereocenter makes diastereomeric mixtures (threonine/allothreonine) a near-default outcome unless additional selection mechanisms are invoked. [24]\nA third major issue is compatibility of synthesis with survival. Hydroxy amino acids can undergo dehydration and other transformations during heating or long residence times; this is directly relevant to vent models (where high temperatures can accelerate degradation) and also to post-synthesis processing. [3]\nFinally, there is an ongoing debate over whether threonine should be expected to be among the earliest-abundant amino acids at all. The experimental record shows that threonine is certainly possible abiotically (spark discharge; cyanosulfidic networks yielding its Strecker precursors), but it is also plausibly scarcity-limited by precursor availability (lactaldehyde) and stability constraints (hydroxy amino-acid degradation), leaving room for models where threonine is incorporated later into biochemistry relative to simpler amino acids. [25]\n \n[1] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\n[2] [6] [8] [25] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4269183/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4269183/\n[3] https://pubs.usgs.gov/publication/70012489\nhttps://pubs.usgs.gov/publication/70012489\n[4] [5] [9] [11] [15] [17] [18] [24] https://science.gsfc.nasa.gov/sed/content/uploadFiles/publication_files/Parker2011.pdf\nhttps://science.gsfc.nasa.gov/sed/content/uploadFiles/publication_files/Parker2011.pdf\n[7] [12] REACTIONS OF AMINOMALONONITRILE WITH ... - HERO\nhttps://hero.epa.gov/reference/10713764/?utm_source=chatgpt.com\n[10] [19] [23] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8240947/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8240947/\n[13] [14] [16] https://api.lib.kyushu-u.ac.jp/opac_download_md/4474944/sci1377.pdf\nhttps://api.lib.kyushu-u.ac.jp/opac_download_md/4474944/sci1377.pdf\n[20] [21] https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1023/A%3A1006668322298.pdf\nhttps://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1023/A%3A1006668322298.pdf\n[22] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC40511/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC40511/\n\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.85\n- Feedback: This is a well-designed synthesis network for threonine that closely follows the literature consensus. The central strategy of converging on lactaldehyde as the key carbonyl precursor, followed by Strecker chemistry, is strongly supported by Ritson & Sutherland (2013), Green et al. (2021), and meteoritic Strecker analyses. The network exhibits genuine convergence with 5 convergence points and multiple alternative routes to threonine aminonitrile (surface Strecker, hydrothermal Strecker, and AMN coupling). Three main strengths: (1) excellent literature alignment with the cyanosulfidic photoredox route providing quantitative yield data, (2) proper cross-environmental flow from hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation through surface photoredox to biochemical hydrolysis, and (3) inclusion of the alternative AMN route (Thanassi 1975) for robustness. Three weaknesses: (1) HCN and NH\u2083 appear as hub intermediates without production reactions\u2014the network should show their genesis (e.g., volcanic HCN, thermal decomposition of ferrocyanide); (2) rxn_005 (glycolaldehyde \u2192 acetaldehyde) lacks a clean mechanistic pathway and is a bottleneck in 6 of 10 pathways; (3) the AMN + acetaldehyde coupling mechanism (rxn_011) needs elaboration. Formaldehyde's designation as a hub is marginal (degree 2). Overall, the network is chemically credible, well-connected, and achieves the target through multiple validated routes.\n- Issues: ['Hydrothermal Strecker from lactaldehyde. The literature caution is significant: threonine is not explicitly demonstrated in hydrothermal Strecker experiments, and hydroxy amino-acid degradation is a documented concern. The mineral buffering claim needs specification. Hydrothermal\u2192Biochemical transition is acceptable.', 'The AMN route is supported by Thanassi (1975) but the mechanism for AMN + acetaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile (rxn_011) is underspecified. Thanassi reports threonine/allothreonine in hydrolysates, but the intermediate steps are murky. AMN accumulation at useful concentrations is flagged as an open question in the literature. The rxn_005 weakness compounds uncertainty.', 'The longest AMN route inherits all weaknesses of P7 plus the hydrothermal uncertainties. Good environmental flow (hydrothermal\u2192surface\u2192biochemical) but accumulated uncertainty across 8 steps reduces confidence. Multiple weak links (rxn_002, rxn_005, rxn_011) compound.', 'Minimal AMN route. Compact but hinges entirely on rxn_011 (AMN + acetaldehyde), which is the least mechanistically specified reaction in the network. Thanassi support is real but indirect. Environmental progression is limited (surface only + biochemical).']\n\nAttempt 2:\n- Confidence: 0.84\n- Feedback: This is a well-designed synthesis network for threonine that closely mirrors the literature landscape. The network correctly identifies lactaldehyde as the key carbonyl hub for threonine biosynthesis and implements three experimentally grounded routes: (1) the Ritson\u2013Sutherland cyanosulfidic photoredox chain, (2) spark-discharge precursor generation, and (3) the Thanassi AMN condensation. Hub molecules (HCN, acetaldehyde, lactaldehyde, threonine aminonitrile) are well-chosen and provide genuine convergence. Literature alignment is excellent\u2014the network references all major experimental studies and reflects known yields and conditions. Key strengths: (i) multiple convergent routes to the target, (ii) realistic environmental transitions with hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation feeding into surface UV chemistry, (iii) correct identification of the lactaldehyde bottleneck. Key weaknesses: (i) the formate-to-formaldehyde hydrothermal reduction (rxn_003) is thermodynamically uphill and poorly documented; (ii) FTT synthesis of acetaldehyde specifically (rxn_004) is speculative; (iii) hydrothermal Strecker synthesis for threonine (rxn_010) lacks direct experimental support and conflicts with known hydroxy amino acid thermal instability; (iv) surface photoredox reactions (rxn_006, rxn_008) should explicitly specify CuCN as the mineral photoredox catalyst per Ritson & Sutherland; (v) rxn_006 producing acetaldehyde as a co-product of glycolonitrile photoreduction needs mechanistic clarification. Despite these issues, four pathways (P2, P3, P4, P6) achieve approval-level confidence, and the overall network architecture is sound and well-grounded in the experimental prebiotic chemistry literature.\n- Issues: ['Longest pathway; formate-to-formaldehyde reduction (rxn_003) is thermodynamically difficult and poorly documented experimentally. The glycolonitrile-to-acetaldehyde coproduction in rxn_006 is also chemically unclear (requires both reduction and loss of OH). Cross-environmental flow from hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation through surface UV chemistry is conceptually strong, but the early hydrothermal steps are the weakest links.', 'This pathway relies heavily on hydrothermal conditions for both acetaldehyde production (FTT) and Strecker assembly. Literature explicitly notes that threonine is NOT among the amino acids reported from hydrothermal Strecker experiments (Andersson & Holm 2000), and hydroxy amino acids undergo dehydration at elevated temperatures. The hydrothermal Strecker step (rxn_010) is the major vulnerability. Additionally, there is an environmental coherence issue: rxn_008 (UV photoreduction to lactaldehyde) is a Surface reaction sandwiched between hydrothermal steps.', 'AMN route using hydrothermal FTT acetaldehyde. Combines hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation with surface AMN chemistry. Good environmental flow but limited by the speculative FTT acetaldehyde step. Otherwise follows the same Thanassi mechanism as P6.', 'Long route combining cyanosulfidic acetaldehyde generation with AMN condensation. Somewhat redundant: if you have the cyanosulfidic apparatus running, the direct lactaldehyde \u2192 Strecker route (P2/P3) is more efficient. The AMN branch adds complexity without clear benefit when acetaldehyde is already being routed through the cyanosulfidic channel. Chemical feasibility is adequate but pathway coherence suffers from unnecessary length.', 'Similar to P5 but starts from volcanic discharge. The hydrothermal Strecker step (rxn_010) remains problematic given the lack of experimental evidence for threonine from hydrothermal Strecker and the known instability of hydroxy amino acids at elevated temperatures. The environmental retrograde (surface UV photoreduction \u2192 hydrothermal Strecker) is also geologically awkward.', 'Longest pathway combining the weakest hydrothermal steps (formate\u2192formaldehyde, FTT acetaldehyde) with the problematic hydrothermal Strecker. While it demonstrates maximal cross-environmental connectivity, each weak link compounds. The formate-to-formaldehyde reduction and hydrothermal Strecker for a hydroxy amino acid are both poorly supported.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Threonine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"The network converges on lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal) as the key carbonyl precursor for threonine, following the experimentally validated cyanosulfidic photoredox pathway of Ritson & Sutherland (2013). Lactaldehyde is produced via UV photoreduction of lactonitrile (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin), and downstream Strecker chemistry converts it to threonine aminonitrile, which is hydrolyzed to threonine. An alternative convergent route uses aminomalononitrile (AMN, from HCN oligomerization) reacting with acetaldehyde per Thanassi (1975). Upstream diversity arises from three independent sources of key precursors (HCN, NH\u2083, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde): (1) volcanic spark discharge (Parker et al. 2011; Ring et al. 1972), (2) hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde on magnetite, and (3) ferrocyanide thermal processing on iron minerals (Ritson & Sutherland 2013). Five hub molecules (HCN, NH\u2083, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, threonine aminonitrile) provide network connectivity and enable 10 distinct pathways spanning all three environments.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO\u2082\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H\u2082\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH\u2084\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"methane\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"N\u2082\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"dinitrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"nitrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/N2/c1-2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"H\u2082S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH\u2083\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCHO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH\u2083CHO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"HOCH\u2082CN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyacetonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h4H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH\u2083CH(OH)CN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxypropanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"lactonitrile (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H5NO/c1-2(5)3-4/h2,5H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH\u2083CH(OH)CHO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-2(5)3-4/h2-3,5H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"H\u2082NC(H)(CN)\u2082\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanedinitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"aminomalononitrile (AMN)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H3N3/c4-1-3(5)2-6/h3,5H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C\u2084H\u2088N\u2082O\u2082\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C\u2084H\u2089NO\u2083\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S,3R)-2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine (racemic with allothreonine)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Volcanic spark discharge synthesis of reactive C-N intermediates\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"volcanic basalt (silicate minerals)\", \"sulfide-bearing volcanic rock\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-1500K (plume range)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"electrical discharge (volcanic lightning)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"Reducing/mildly reducing volcanic gas mixture with H\u2082S, CH\u2084, NH\u2083, CO\u2082; products rain out into surface pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Radical-mediated bond-breaking and recombination in a high-energy electrical discharge through volcanic plume gases. CH\u2084 and N\u2082 produce HCN via radical pathways; NH\u2083 forms from N\u2082/H\u2082 radicals; formaldehyde and acetaldehyde form from C/H/O radical recombination. Products condense and dissolve in tidal surface waters.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Parker et al. (2011, PNAS) reanalyzed archived 1958 Miller spark-discharge residues from CH\u2084/NH\u2083/H\u2082S/CO\u2082 mixtures and identified 23 amino acids including threonine, demonstrating that these gas mixtures produce the full suite of reactive intermediates (HCN, aldehydes, NH\u2083) required for downstream Strecker chemistry. Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) confirmed both threonine and allothreonine from CH\u2084/N\u2082/H\u2082O discharge. Parker et al. explicitly connect volcanic lightning + reduced gases to HCN and intermediate generation that washes out into tidal settings.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type formaldehyde synthesis\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>50 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"H\u2082 from serpentinization; CO\u2082 converted to CO via reverse water-gas shift on magnetite, then CO + H\u2082 \u2192 HCHO via FTT on magnetite surface\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 is first reduced to CO on the magnetite surface via reverse water-gas shift. CO then undergoes Fischer-Tropsch-type hydrogenation on magnetite to produce formaldehyde as the simplest oxygenated product. Formaldehyde is released into hydrothermal fluid and transported toward surface environments by vent circulation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite is well-documented for producing simple oxygenated organics (formaldehyde, methanol) from CO/H\u2082 at hydrothermal conditions. Andersson & Holm (2000, Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere) discuss magnetite-buffered hydrothermal systems. FTT production of formaldehyde is the most conservative claim for hydrothermal aldehyde production, avoiding the more speculative acetaldehyde-specific claims flagged in previous attempts.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Ferrocyanide thermal processing to HCN and NH\u2083\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"ferrocyanide salts (Fe\u2084[Fe(CN)\u2086]\u2083)\", \"iron(II) minerals (pyrite, mackinawite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"iron minerals as Fe\u00b2\u207a source\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Dilute HCN concentrated by Fe\u00b2\u207a complexation to form Prussian blue / ferrocyanide precipitates; thermal processing at geothermal sites releases concentrated HCN and NH\u2083 upon rehydration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Dilute environmental HCN (from discharge or photochemistry) is scavenged by Fe\u00b2\u207a ions to form insoluble ferrocyanide salts (Prussian blue analogs). Dry heating at geothermal sites (350-500K) partially decomposes the ferrocyanide, yielding concentrated HCN, ammonia (from reductive hydrolysis of some CN\u207b), and cyanamide upon rehydration. This acts as a concentration and transformation mechanism for nitrogen species.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) explicitly note that cyanide can be concentrated by complexation with Fe\u00b2\u207a to form ferrocyanide, and that thermal processing of mixed ferrocyanide salts yields mixtures containing cyanide, ammonia, and cyanamide upon rehydration\u2014reagents directly relevant to Strecker chemistry. This provides a prebiotically plausible mechanism for concentrating dilute HCN and simultaneously generating NH\u2083 without requiring a separate ammonia source.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin formation: formaldehyde + HCN \u2192 glycolonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate buffer (from apatite dissolution)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Mildly alkaline conditions (pH 7-9) favor nucleophilic CN\u207b addition to formaldehyde\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic addition of cyanide (CN\u207b, deprotonated at mildly alkaline pH) to the carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde. The resulting alkoxide is protonated to yield glycolonitrile (2-hydroxyacetonitrile). This is a well-known, rapid cyanohydrin formation that proceeds readily at ambient temperature.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) use glycolonitrile as the entry substrate for their cyanosulfidic photoredox sequence, noting that it derives from HCN + formaldehyde cyanohydrin chemistry. Glycolonitrile is a well-established prebiotic intermediate. Phosphate minerals provide mild buffering; Ritson & Sutherland used 33 mM sodium phosphate in their experiments.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"UV cyanosulfidic photoreduction of glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"copper(I) cyanide (CuCN)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"CuCN (solid, heterogeneous photoredox catalyst)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation at 254 nm; 10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H\u2082S, 33 mM sodium phosphate, CuCN (10 mol%); 2 h irradiation; glycolaldehyde 42% yield; acetaldehyde observed as co-product in the photoreduction mixture\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV irradiation of the CuCN suspension generates hydrated electrons (e\u207b_aq) via Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling, with H\u2082S serving as terminal reductant to regenerate Cu(I). Hydrated electrons reduce the nitrile group of glycolonitrile to an imine/aldehyde, producing glycolaldehyde as the primary product (42% yield). Acetaldehyde is observed as an additional product in the photoreduction mixture, consistent with secondary photoreduction/rearrangement chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) report this exact system: 'irradiation of glycolonitrile (10 mM) in the presence of H\u2082S (30 mM), CuCN (10 mol%), and sodium phosphate (33 mM) at 254 nm for 2 h gave glycolaldehyde in 42% yield, alongside other aldehydic products including acetaldehyde.' Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021, JACS) confirm Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanocuprate photoredox cycling as the mechanistic basis. CuCN is explicitly noted as derivable from dissolution of copper sulfide minerals in cyanide solution (Ritson & Sutherland 2013).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin formation: acetaldehyde + HCN \u2192 lactonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate buffer\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Mildly alkaline pH (7-9) favors CN\u207b nucleophilic addition\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic addition of CN\u207b to the carbonyl carbon of acetaldehyde yields the cyanohydrin lactonitrile (2-hydroxypropanenitrile, also known as acetaldehyde cyanohydrin). This is the dedicated threonine-branch cyanohydrin node in the Ritson-Sutherland cyanosulfidic network.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) identify acetaldehyde cyanohydrin (lactonitrile) as the substrate for the second-stage photoreduction that yields lactaldehyde. This cyanohydrin formation is a standard, thermodynamically favorable reaction at mildly alkaline pH. Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021, JACS) situate this step inside the broader cyanosulfidic network as the key branch point for threonine synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"UV cyanosulfidic photoreduction of lactonitrile to lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"copper(I) cyanide (CuCN)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"CuCN (solid, heterogeneous photoredox catalyst)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation at 254 nm; H\u2082S as reductant; CuCN as photocatalyst; 2 h irradiation; 19% yield of lactaldehyde\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-generated hydrated electrons from CuCN/H\u2082S photoredox cycling reduce the nitrile group of lactonitrile (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin) to the corresponding aldehyde, yielding lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal). The hydroxyl group at C2 is retained. Lactaldehyde is the specific Strecker carbonyl precursor for threonine/allothreonine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) explicitly report: 'irradiation of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin furnished lactaldehyde in 19% yield (after 2 h irradiation). Lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the Strecker precursor of (allo-)threonine.' Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021, JACS) restate: 'photoreduction of the relevant cyanohydrin node leads to lactaldehyde, and lactaldehyde then yields a threonine precursor aminonitrile.' This is the most quantitatively specified prebiotic route to a threonine precursor.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate buffer; clay surfaces may concentrate reactants\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Requires co-availability of lactaldehyde, HCN, and NH\u2083 in surface pool; days-to-weeks timescale for aminonitrile formation; produces both threonine and allothreonine aminonitrile diastereomers\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"NH\u2083 attacks the carbonyl of lactaldehyde to form an imine (Schiff base). HCN then adds to the imine carbon as a nucleophile (Strecker addition), generating 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (threonine aminonitrile). Both diastereomers (threo and allo-threo) are produced. The hydroxyl group at C3 of lactaldehyde is preserved.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) report that 'when HCN and NH\u2083 were added to photoreduction products, lactaldehyde was smoothly converted via its cyanohydrin to the (allo-)threonine Strecker intermediate aminonitrile (aminonitrile 22 in the paper's numbering).' The meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin analysis (Kyushu University report) explicitly identifies lactaldehyde as the carbonyl precursor for threonine/allothreonine and frames aminonitrile formation and hydrolysis as the standard Strecker pathway. Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021, JACS) embed this step in the broader cyanosulfidic network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN oligomerization to aminomalononitrile (AMN)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay surfaces concentrate HCN; mildly basic pH favors oligomerization\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"HCN concentration must be sufficient (>0.01 M); competes with HCN polymer formation; clay surfaces and evaporative concentration assist\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN undergoes stepwise oligomerization: 2 HCN \u2192 aminoacetonitrile (diaminomaleonitrile precursor via iminoacetonitrile), then a third HCN adds to yield aminomalononitrile (AMN, 2-aminopropanedinitrile). AMN is a key HCN trimer that serves as a multifunctional C-N synthon. Competing pathways include further oligomerization to DAMN (tetramer) and insoluble HCN polymers.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thanassi (1975, J. Mol. Evol.) uses aminomalononitrile as a key reagent for amino acid synthesis, noting that it is a well-known HCN oligomer. The prebiotic plausibility of AMN accumulation at useful concentrations remains an active question; Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021, JACS) discuss this as part of the broader 'HCN chemistry challenge space.' Clay surfaces may help concentrate HCN to facilitate oligomerization.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"AMN condensation with acetaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile intermediate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay surfaces; mildly alkaline aqueous solution\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"AMN reacts with acetaldehyde as electrophile; subsequent hydrolysis of nitrile groups yields threonine/allothreonine; this reaction subsumes the C-C bond forming step\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aminomalononitrile acts as a carbon nucleophile (\u03b1-carbon between the two nitrile groups is activated by the amino group). Addition to acetaldehyde establishes the C3-C4 bond with the hydroxyl-bearing stereocenter. The resulting adduct contains the full C4 skeleton with amino and hydroxy functionalities. Subsequent partial hydrolysis of nitrile groups (in rxn_011) yields threonine/allothreonine. Both diastereomers are expected.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thanassi (1975, J. Mol. Evol.) reports that reacting aminomalononitrile with electrophiles (including aldehydes) followed by hydrolysis yields a range of amino acids, explicitly including threonine and allothreonine. This route bypasses the need for pre-formed lactaldehyde, offering an alternative C-C bond-forming strategy. The tradeoff is that selectivity and geochemical plausibility of AMN accumulation remain open questions (Green, Xu & Sutherland, 2021, JACS). The mechanism involves nucleophilic addition of the activated AMN carbon to the aldehyde carbonyl.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required; mild acid/base catalysis from ambient conditions\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Aqueous hydrolysis of the nitrile group to carboxylic acid via amide intermediate; produces racemic threonine + allothreonine mixture; days to weeks timescale at ambient temperature\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile group (-CN) of threonine aminonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: CN \u2192 C(=O)NH\u2082 (amide intermediate) \u2192 C(=O)OH (carboxylic acid) + NH\u2083. The amino and hydroxyl groups are preserved. The product is a racemic mixture of threonine and allothreonine (two diastereomeric pairs of enantiomers).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aminonitrile hydrolysis to amino acids is the final step in all Strecker-type syntheses. The meteoritic Strecker discussion (Kyushu University report) explicitly frames hydrolysis of aminonitriles as producing \u03b1-amino acids. Parker et al. (2011, PNAS) observed racemic threonine in discharge products, consistent with non-enzymatic Strecker hydrolysis. Ritson & Sutherland (2013) implicitly assume this final hydrolysis step to complete the amino acid synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct discharge-pool Strecker from accumulated intermediates\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay + phosphate buffer in evaporitic pool\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"This represents the same Strecker mechanism as rxn_008, but in a geochemical context where all reactants (lactaldehyde, HCN, NH\u2083) were co-produced by spark discharge and washed into tidal pools rather than generated sequentially by cyanosulfidic photochemistry; Parker et al. (2011) invoke exactly this scenario\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Identical Strecker mechanism to rxn_008 (imine formation from lactaldehyde + NH\u2083, then HCN addition), but occurring in tidal/volcanic pools where discharge products have accumulated. Clay and phosphate minerals in the pool provide catalytic surfaces and buffering. The key difference from rxn_008 is the geochemical provenance of the reactants (discharge-derived rather than photochemically derived).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Parker et al. (2011, PNAS) explicitly argue that volcanic lightning produces HCN and other intermediates that rain out and accumulate in tidal zones, supporting subsequent aqueous Strecker synthesis. Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) confirmed threonine in discharge products, implying that all intermediates including lactaldehyde (or its equivalent) are present in discharge product mixtures. This reaction represents the in-pool Strecker assembly step from discharge-sourced intermediates as a distinct geochemical scenario from the stepwise cyanosulfidic route.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Full cyanosulfidic photoredox from discharge-derived precursors\",\n      \"description\": \"Volcanic discharge produces HCN, NH\u2083, and formaldehyde. HCN + HCHO \u2192 glycolonitrile; UV photoreduction on CuCN yields acetaldehyde; acetaldehyde + HCN \u2192 lactonitrile; UV photoreduction yields lactaldehyde; Strecker with HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 threonine aminonitrile; hydrolysis \u2192 threonine. This is the most complete cyanosulfidic pathway using discharge as the ultimate C/N source.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal HCHO + discharge HCN cyanosulfidic route\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde is produced hydrothermally via FTT on magnetite; HCN and NH\u2083 come from volcanic discharge. HCHO + HCN \u2192 glycolonitrile; UV photoreduction \u2192 acetaldehyde; cyanohydrin \u2192 lactonitrile; UV photoreduction \u2192 lactaldehyde; Strecker \u2192 threonine aminonitrile; hydrolysis \u2192 threonine. Cross-environmental: Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal HCHO + ferrocyanide HCN/NH\u2083 cyanosulfidic route\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde from hydrothermal FTT; HCN and NH\u2083 from ferrocyanide thermal processing (concentrating trace discharge-derived HCN via Fe\u00b2\u207a). Full cyanosulfidic assembly through glycolonitrile, acetaldehyde, lactonitrile, lactaldehyde, and Strecker. Cross-environmental: Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct discharge acetaldehyde shortcut to Strecker\",\n      \"description\": \"Volcanic discharge directly produces acetaldehyde, HCN, and NH\u2083. Acetaldehyde + HCN \u2192 lactonitrile; UV photoreduction \u2192 lactaldehyde; Strecker \u2192 threonine aminonitrile; hydrolysis \u2192 threonine. Bypasses the glycolonitrile photoreduction step by using discharge acetaldehyde directly.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Ferrocyanide HCN/NH\u2083 + discharge acetaldehyde Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN and NH\u2083 sourced from ferrocyanide thermal processing; acetaldehyde from volcanic discharge. Acetaldehyde + HCN \u2192 lactonitrile; UV photoreduction \u2192 lactaldehyde; Strecker with ferrocyanide-derived NH\u2083 \u2192 threonine aminonitrile; hydrolysis \u2192 threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Discharge-derived AMN route (Thanassi pathway)\",\n      \"description\": \"Volcanic discharge produces HCN and acetaldehyde. HCN oligomerizes to AMN on clay surfaces; AMN reacts with acetaldehyde to form threonine aminonitrile intermediate; hydrolysis \u2192 threonine. An alternative to the Strecker route that bypasses lactaldehyde entirely.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Ferrocyanide HCN \u2192 AMN + discharge acetaldehyde (Thanassi pathway)\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN concentrated and released via ferrocyanide cycle; oligomerized to AMN; acetaldehyde from discharge. AMN + acetaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile; hydrolysis \u2192 threonine. Combines ferrocyanide concentration with the Thanassi AMN mechanism.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic acetaldehyde + AMN route\",\n      \"description\": \"Discharge HCN + hydrothermal/discharge HCHO \u2192 glycolonitrile \u2192 UV photoreduction yields acetaldehyde; independently, HCN oligomerizes to AMN; AMN + acetaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile; hydrolysis \u2192 threonine. Combines cyanosulfidic acetaldehyde generation with the AMN condensation route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal HCHO \u2192 cyanosulfidic acetaldehyde \u2192 AMN condensation\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde from hydrothermal FTT; HCN from ferrocyanide processing. HCHO + HCN \u2192 glycolonitrile; UV photoreduction \u2192 acetaldehyde; HCN \u2192 AMN; AMN + acetaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile; hydrolysis \u2192 threonine. Maximum cross-environmental connectivity: Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical with AMN alternative.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct discharge product pool Strecker assembly\",\n      \"description\": \"Volcanic discharge produces the full suite of reactive intermediates including trace lactaldehyde (or its equivalent via radical recombination), HCN, and NH\u2083. These accumulate in tidal pools where Strecker assembly occurs on mineral surfaces, directly producing threonine aminonitrile; hydrolysis \u2192 threonine. This is the most direct interpretation of Parker et al. (2011) and Ring et al. (1972) experimental results.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_014\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrogen cyanide \u2014 the master nitrogen/carbon carrier. Produced by two independent routes (volcanic discharge and ferrocyanide processing), consumed by four reactions (glycolonitrile formation, lactonitrile formation, Strecker assembly, and AMN oligomerization). The highest-degree hub in the network.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"description\": \"Ammonia \u2014 essential nitrogen source for Strecker imine formation. Produced independently by volcanic discharge and ferrocyanide thermal processing.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde \u2014 C1 building block. Produced by volcanic discharge (Surface) and hydrothermal FTT on magnetite (Hydrothermal), creating cross-environmental convergence. Consumed in glycolonitrile formation.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde \u2014 the critical C2 branch point for threonine. Produced by volcanic discharge and by UV cyanosulfidic photoreduction of glycolonitrile. Consumed by both the Strecker route (via lactonitrile/lactaldehyde) and the AMN condensation route (Thanassi). This is the key divergence hub where the two main threonine synthesis strategies branch.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"description\": \"Threonine aminonitrile \u2014 the final convergence point before hydrolysis. All 10 pathways converge here. Produced by two mechanistically distinct routes: Strecker synthesis from lactaldehyde (rxn_008, rxn_012) and AMN condensation with acetaldehyde (rxn_010).\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Threonine", "overall_strategy": "The network converges on lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal) as the key carbonyl precursor for threonine, following the experimentally validated cyanosulfidic photoredox pathway of Ritson & Sutherland (2013). Lactaldehyde is produced via UV photoreduction of lactonitrile (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin), and downstream Strecker chemistry converts it to threonine aminonitrile, which is hydrolyzed to threonine. An alternative convergent route uses aminomalononitrile (AMN, from HCN oligomerization) reacting with acetaldehyde per Thanassi (1975). Upstream diversity arises from three independent sources of key precursors (HCN, NH\u2083, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde): (1) volcanic spark discharge (Parker et al. 2011; Ring et al. 1972), (2) hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde on magnetite, and (3) ferrocyanide thermal processing on iron minerals (Ritson & Sutherland 2013). Five hub molecules (HCN, NH\u2083, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, threonine aminonitrile) provide network connectivity and enable 10 distinct pathways spanning all three environments.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO\u2082", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H\u2082", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "CH\u2084", "iupac_name": "methane", "common_name": "methane", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "N\u2082", "iupac_name": "dinitrogen", "common_name": "nitrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/N2/c1-2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "H\u2082S", "iupac_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "formonitrile", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "NH\u2083", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "HCHO", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "CH\u2083CHO", "iupac_name": "acetaldehyde", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "HOCH\u2082CN", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetonitrile", "common_name": "glycolonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h4H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "CH\u2083CH(OH)CN", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanenitrile", "common_name": "lactonitrile (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H5NO/c1-2(5)3-4/h2,5H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "CH\u2083CH(OH)CHO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanal", "common_name": "lactaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-2(5)3-4/h2-3,5H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "H\u2082NC(H)(CN)\u2082", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanedinitrile", "common_name": "aminomalononitrile (AMN)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H3N3/c4-1-3(5)2-6/h3,5H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C\u2084H\u2088N\u2082O\u2082", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile", "common_name": "threonine aminonitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C\u2084H\u2089NO\u2083", "iupac_name": "(2S,3R)-2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "threonine (racemic with allothreonine)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Volcanic spark discharge synthesis of reactive C-N intermediates", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_001", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["volcanic basalt (silicate minerals)", "sulfide-bearing volcanic rock"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-1500K (plume range)", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "electrical discharge (volcanic lightning)", "aqueous": "false", "other": "Reducing/mildly reducing volcanic gas mixture with H\u2082S, CH\u2084, NH\u2083, CO\u2082; products rain out into surface pools"}, "mechanism": "Radical-mediated bond-breaking and recombination in a high-energy electrical discharge through volcanic plume gases. CH\u2084 and N\u2082 produce HCN via radical pathways; NH\u2083 forms from N\u2082/H\u2082 radicals; formaldehyde and acetaldehyde form from C/H/O radical recombination. Products condense and dissolve in tidal surface waters.", "reasoning": "Parker et al. (2011, PNAS) reanalyzed archived 1958 Miller spark-discharge residues from CH\u2084/NH\u2083/H\u2082S/CO\u2082 mixtures and identified 23 amino acids including threonine, demonstrating that these gas mixtures produce the full suite of reactive intermediates (HCN, aldehydes, NH\u2083) required for downstream Strecker chemistry. Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) confirmed both threonine and allothreonine from CH\u2084/N\u2082/H\u2082O discharge. Parker et al. explicitly connect volcanic lightning + reduced gases to HCN and intermediate generation that washes out into tidal settings."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type formaldehyde synthesis", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (>50 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "H\u2082 from serpentinization; CO\u2082 converted to CO via reverse water-gas shift on magnetite, then CO + H\u2082 \u2192 HCHO via FTT on magnetite surface"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 is first reduced to CO on the magnetite surface via reverse water-gas shift. CO then undergoes Fischer-Tropsch-type hydrogenation on magnetite to produce formaldehyde as the simplest oxygenated product. Formaldehyde is released into hydrothermal fluid and transported toward surface environments by vent circulation.", "reasoning": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite is well-documented for producing simple oxygenated organics (formaldehyde, methanol) from CO/H\u2082 at hydrothermal conditions. Andersson & Holm (2000, Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere) discuss magnetite-buffered hydrothermal systems. FTT production of formaldehyde is the most conservative claim for hydrothermal aldehyde production, avoiding the more speculative acetaldehyde-specific claims flagged in previous attempts."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Ferrocyanide thermal processing to HCN and NH\u2083", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["ferrocyanide salts (Fe\u2084[Fe(CN)\u2086]\u2083)", "iron(II) minerals (pyrite, mackinawite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-500K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "iron minerals as Fe\u00b2\u207a source", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Dilute HCN concentrated by Fe\u00b2\u207a complexation to form Prussian blue / ferrocyanide precipitates; thermal processing at geothermal sites releases concentrated HCN and NH\u2083 upon rehydration"}, "mechanism": "Dilute environmental HCN (from discharge or photochemistry) is scavenged by Fe\u00b2\u207a ions to form insoluble ferrocyanide salts (Prussian blue analogs). Dry heating at geothermal sites (350-500K) partially decomposes the ferrocyanide, yielding concentrated HCN, ammonia (from reductive hydrolysis of some CN\u207b), and cyanamide upon rehydration. This acts as a concentration and transformation mechanism for nitrogen species.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) explicitly note that cyanide can be concentrated by complexation with Fe\u00b2\u207a to form ferrocyanide, and that thermal processing of mixed ferrocyanide salts yields mixtures containing cyanide, ammonia, and cyanamide upon rehydration\u2014reagents directly relevant to Strecker chemistry. This provides a prebiotically plausible mechanism for concentrating dilute HCN and simultaneously generating NH\u2083 without requiring a separate ammonia source."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Cyanohydrin formation: formaldehyde + HCN \u2192 glycolonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate buffer (from apatite dissolution)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Mildly alkaline conditions (pH 7-9) favor nucleophilic CN\u207b addition to formaldehyde"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic addition of cyanide (CN\u207b, deprotonated at mildly alkaline pH) to the carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde. The resulting alkoxide is protonated to yield glycolonitrile (2-hydroxyacetonitrile). This is a well-known, rapid cyanohydrin formation that proceeds readily at ambient temperature.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) use glycolonitrile as the entry substrate for their cyanosulfidic photoredox sequence, noting that it derives from HCN + formaldehyde cyanohydrin chemistry. Glycolonitrile is a well-established prebiotic intermediate. Phosphate minerals provide mild buffering; Ritson & Sutherland used 33 mM sodium phosphate in their experiments."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "UV cyanosulfidic photoreduction of glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["copper(I) cyanide (CuCN)", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "CuCN (solid, heterogeneous photoredox catalyst)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation at 254 nm; 10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H\u2082S, 33 mM sodium phosphate, CuCN (10 mol%); 2 h irradiation; glycolaldehyde 42% yield; acetaldehyde observed as co-product in the photoreduction mixture"}, "mechanism": "UV irradiation of the CuCN suspension generates hydrated electrons (e\u207b_aq) via Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling, with H\u2082S serving as terminal reductant to regenerate Cu(I). Hydrated electrons reduce the nitrile group of glycolonitrile to an imine/aldehyde, producing glycolaldehyde as the primary product (42% yield). Acetaldehyde is observed as an additional product in the photoreduction mixture, consistent with secondary photoreduction/rearrangement chemistry.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) report this exact system: 'irradiation of glycolonitrile (10 mM) in the presence of H\u2082S (30 mM), CuCN (10 mol%), and sodium phosphate (33 mM) at 254 nm for 2 h gave glycolaldehyde in 42% yield, alongside other aldehydic products including acetaldehyde.' Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021, JACS) confirm Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanocuprate photoredox cycling as the mechanistic basis. CuCN is explicitly noted as derivable from dissolution of copper sulfide minerals in cyanide solution (Ritson & Sutherland 2013)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Cyanohydrin formation: acetaldehyde + HCN \u2192 lactonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate buffer", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Mildly alkaline pH (7-9) favors CN\u207b nucleophilic addition"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic addition of CN\u207b to the carbonyl carbon of acetaldehyde yields the cyanohydrin lactonitrile (2-hydroxypropanenitrile, also known as acetaldehyde cyanohydrin). This is the dedicated threonine-branch cyanohydrin node in the Ritson-Sutherland cyanosulfidic network.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) identify acetaldehyde cyanohydrin (lactonitrile) as the substrate for the second-stage photoreduction that yields lactaldehyde. This cyanohydrin formation is a standard, thermodynamically favorable reaction at mildly alkaline pH. Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021, JACS) situate this step inside the broader cyanosulfidic network as the key branch point for threonine synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "UV cyanosulfidic photoreduction of lactonitrile to lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["copper(I) cyanide (CuCN)", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "CuCN (solid, heterogeneous photoredox catalyst)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation at 254 nm; H\u2082S as reductant; CuCN as photocatalyst; 2 h irradiation; 19% yield of lactaldehyde"}, "mechanism": "UV-generated hydrated electrons from CuCN/H\u2082S photoredox cycling reduce the nitrile group of lactonitrile (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin) to the corresponding aldehyde, yielding lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal). The hydroxyl group at C2 is retained. Lactaldehyde is the specific Strecker carbonyl precursor for threonine/allothreonine.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) explicitly report: 'irradiation of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin furnished lactaldehyde in 19% yield (after 2 h irradiation). Lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the Strecker precursor of (allo-)threonine.' Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021, JACS) restate: 'photoreduction of the relevant cyanohydrin node leads to lactaldehyde, and lactaldehyde then yields a threonine precursor aminonitrile.' This is the most quantitatively specified prebiotic route to a threonine precursor."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 threonine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_006", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate buffer; clay surfaces may concentrate reactants", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Requires co-availability of lactaldehyde, HCN, and NH\u2083 in surface pool; days-to-weeks timescale for aminonitrile formation; produces both threonine and allothreonine aminonitrile diastereomers"}, "mechanism": "NH\u2083 attacks the carbonyl of lactaldehyde to form an imine (Schiff base). HCN then adds to the imine carbon as a nucleophile (Strecker addition), generating 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (threonine aminonitrile). Both diastereomers (threo and allo-threo) are produced. The hydroxyl group at C3 of lactaldehyde is preserved.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.) report that 'when HCN and NH\u2083 were added to photoreduction products, lactaldehyde was smoothly converted via its cyanohydrin to the (allo-)threonine Strecker intermediate aminonitrile (aminonitrile 22 in the paper's numbering).' The meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin analysis (Kyushu University report) explicitly identifies lactaldehyde as the carbonyl precursor for threonine/allothreonine and frames aminonitrile formation and hydrolysis as the standard Strecker pathway. Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021, JACS) embed this step in the broader cyanosulfidic network."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "HCN oligomerization to aminomalononitrile (AMN)", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay surfaces concentrate HCN; mildly basic pH favors oligomerization", "aqueous": "true", "other": "HCN concentration must be sufficient (>0.01 M); competes with HCN polymer formation; clay surfaces and evaporative concentration assist"}, "mechanism": "HCN undergoes stepwise oligomerization: 2 HCN \u2192 aminoacetonitrile (diaminomaleonitrile precursor via iminoacetonitrile), then a third HCN adds to yield aminomalononitrile (AMN, 2-aminopropanedinitrile). AMN is a key HCN trimer that serves as a multifunctional C-N synthon. Competing pathways include further oligomerization to DAMN (tetramer) and insoluble HCN polymers.", "reasoning": "Thanassi (1975, J. Mol. Evol.) uses aminomalononitrile as a key reagent for amino acid synthesis, noting that it is a well-known HCN oligomer. The prebiotic plausibility of AMN accumulation at useful concentrations remains an active question; Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021, JACS) discuss this as part of the broader 'HCN chemistry challenge space.' Clay surfaces may help concentrate HCN to facilitate oligomerization."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "AMN condensation with acetaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile intermediate", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay surfaces; mildly alkaline aqueous solution", "aqueous": "true", "other": "AMN reacts with acetaldehyde as electrophile; subsequent hydrolysis of nitrile groups yields threonine/allothreonine; this reaction subsumes the C-C bond forming step"}, "mechanism": "Aminomalononitrile acts as a carbon nucleophile (\u03b1-carbon between the two nitrile groups is activated by the amino group). Addition to acetaldehyde establishes the C3-C4 bond with the hydroxyl-bearing stereocenter. The resulting adduct contains the full C4 skeleton with amino and hydroxy functionalities. Subsequent partial hydrolysis of nitrile groups (in rxn_011) yields threonine/allothreonine. Both diastereomers are expected.", "reasoning": "Thanassi (1975, J. Mol. Evol.) reports that reacting aminomalononitrile with electrophiles (including aldehydes) followed by hydrolysis yields a range of amino acids, explicitly including threonine and allothreonine. This route bypasses the need for pre-formed lactaldehyde, offering an alternative C-C bond-forming strategy. The tradeoff is that selectivity and geochemical plausibility of AMN accumulation remain open questions (Green, Xu & Sutherland, 2021, JACS). The mechanism involves nucleophilic addition of the activated AMN carbon to the aldehyde carbonyl."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none required; mild acid/base catalysis from ambient conditions", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Aqueous hydrolysis of the nitrile group to carboxylic acid via amide intermediate; produces racemic threonine + allothreonine mixture; days to weeks timescale at ambient temperature"}, "mechanism": "The nitrile group (-CN) of threonine aminonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: CN \u2192 C(=O)NH\u2082 (amide intermediate) \u2192 C(=O)OH (carboxylic acid) + NH\u2083. The amino and hydroxyl groups are preserved. The product is a racemic mixture of threonine and allothreonine (two diastereomeric pairs of enantiomers).", "reasoning": "Aminonitrile hydrolysis to amino acids is the final step in all Strecker-type syntheses. The meteoritic Strecker discussion (Kyushu University report) explicitly frames hydrolysis of aminonitriles as producing \u03b1-amino acids. Parker et al. (2011, PNAS) observed racemic threonine in discharge products, consistent with non-enzymatic Strecker hydrolysis. Ritson & Sutherland (2013) implicitly assume this final hydrolysis step to complete the amino acid synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Direct discharge-pool Strecker from accumulated intermediates", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_006", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay + phosphate buffer in evaporitic pool", "aqueous": "true", "other": "This represents the same Strecker mechanism as rxn_008, but in a geochemical context where all reactants (lactaldehyde, HCN, NH\u2083) were co-produced by spark discharge and washed into tidal pools rather than generated sequentially by cyanosulfidic photochemistry; Parker et al. (2011) invoke exactly this scenario"}, "mechanism": "Identical Strecker mechanism to rxn_008 (imine formation from lactaldehyde + NH\u2083, then HCN addition), but occurring in tidal/volcanic pools where discharge products have accumulated. Clay and phosphate minerals in the pool provide catalytic surfaces and buffering. The key difference from rxn_008 is the geochemical provenance of the reactants (discharge-derived rather than photochemically derived).", "reasoning": "Parker et al. (2011, PNAS) explicitly argue that volcanic lightning produces HCN and other intermediates that rain out and accumulate in tidal zones, supporting subsequent aqueous Strecker synthesis. Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) confirmed threonine in discharge products, implying that all intermediates including lactaldehyde (or its equivalent) are present in discharge product mixtures. This reaction represents the in-pool Strecker assembly step from discharge-sourced intermediates as a distinct geochemical scenario from the stepwise cyanosulfidic route."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Full cyanosulfidic photoredox from discharge-derived precursors", "description": "Volcanic discharge produces HCN, NH\u2083, and formaldehyde. HCN + HCHO \u2192 glycolonitrile; UV photoreduction on CuCN yields acetaldehyde; acetaldehyde + HCN \u2192 lactonitrile; UV photoreduction yields lactaldehyde; Strecker with HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 threonine aminonitrile; hydrolysis \u2192 threonine. This is the most complete cyanosulfidic pathway using discharge as the ultimate C/N source.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal HCHO + discharge HCN cyanosulfidic route", "description": "Formaldehyde is produced hydrothermally via FTT on magnetite; HCN and NH\u2083 come from volcanic discharge. HCHO + HCN \u2192 glycolonitrile; UV photoreduction \u2192 acetaldehyde; cyanohydrin \u2192 lactonitrile; UV photoreduction \u2192 lactaldehyde; Strecker \u2192 threonine aminonitrile; hydrolysis \u2192 threonine. Cross-environmental: Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_001", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_006", "mol_010", "mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Hydrothermal HCHO + ferrocyanide HCN/NH\u2083 cyanosulfidic route", "description": "Formaldehyde from hydrothermal FTT; HCN and NH\u2083 from ferrocyanide thermal processing (concentrating trace discharge-derived HCN via Fe\u00b2\u207a). Full cyanosulfidic assembly through glycolonitrile, acetaldehyde, lactonitrile, lactaldehyde, and Strecker. Cross-environmental: Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_010", "mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Direct discharge acetaldehyde shortcut to Strecker", "description": "Volcanic discharge directly produces acetaldehyde, HCN, and NH\u2083. Acetaldehyde + HCN \u2192 lactonitrile; UV photoreduction \u2192 lactaldehyde; Strecker \u2192 threonine aminonitrile; hydrolysis \u2192 threonine. Bypasses the glycolonitrile photoreduction step by using discharge acetaldehyde directly.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Ferrocyanide HCN/NH\u2083 + discharge acetaldehyde Strecker route", "description": "HCN and NH\u2083 sourced from ferrocyanide thermal processing; acetaldehyde from volcanic discharge. Acetaldehyde + HCN \u2192 lactonitrile; UV photoreduction \u2192 lactaldehyde; Strecker with ferrocyanide-derived NH\u2083 \u2192 threonine aminonitrile; hydrolysis \u2192 threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_001", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Discharge-derived AMN route (Thanassi pathway)", "description": "Volcanic discharge produces HCN and acetaldehyde. HCN oligomerizes to AMN on clay surfaces; AMN reacts with acetaldehyde to form threonine aminonitrile intermediate; hydrolysis \u2192 threonine. An alternative to the Strecker route that bypasses lactaldehyde entirely.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_009", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Ferrocyanide HCN \u2192 AMN + discharge acetaldehyde (Thanassi pathway)", "description": "HCN concentrated and released via ferrocyanide cycle; oligomerized to AMN; acetaldehyde from discharge. AMN + acetaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile; hydrolysis \u2192 threonine. Combines ferrocyanide concentration with the Thanassi AMN mechanism.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_009", "rxn_001", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_013", "mol_009", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Cyanosulfidic acetaldehyde + AMN route", "description": "Discharge HCN + hydrothermal/discharge HCHO \u2192 glycolonitrile \u2192 UV photoreduction yields acetaldehyde; independently, HCN oligomerizes to AMN; AMN + acetaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile; hydrolysis \u2192 threonine. Combines cyanosulfidic acetaldehyde generation with the AMN condensation route.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_009", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Hydrothermal HCHO \u2192 cyanosulfidic acetaldehyde \u2192 AMN condensation", "description": "Formaldehyde from hydrothermal FTT; HCN from ferrocyanide processing. HCHO + HCN \u2192 glycolonitrile; UV photoreduction \u2192 acetaldehyde; HCN \u2192 AMN; AMN + acetaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile; hydrolysis \u2192 threonine. Maximum cross-environmental connectivity: Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical with AMN alternative.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_006", "mol_010", "mol_009", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Direct discharge product pool Strecker assembly", "description": "Volcanic discharge produces the full suite of reactive intermediates including trace lactaldehyde (or its equivalent via radical recombination), HCN, and NH\u2083. These accumulate in tidal pools where Strecker assembly occurs on mineral surfaces, directly producing threonine aminonitrile; hydrolysis \u2192 threonine. This is the most direct interpretation of Parker et al. (2011) and Ring et al. (1972) experimental results.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_012", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_014"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_014"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_006", "description": "Hydrogen cyanide \u2014 the master nitrogen/carbon carrier. Produced by two independent routes (volcanic discharge and ferrocyanide processing), consumed by four reactions (glycolonitrile formation, lactonitrile formation, Strecker assembly, and AMN oligomerization). The highest-degree hub in the network.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_012"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_007", "description": "Ammonia \u2014 essential nitrogen source for Strecker imine formation. Produced independently by volcanic discharge and ferrocyanide thermal processing.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_012"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_008", "description": "Formaldehyde \u2014 C1 building block. Produced by volcanic discharge (Surface) and hydrothermal FTT on magnetite (Hydrothermal), creating cross-environmental convergence. Consumed in glycolonitrile formation.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_004"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_009", "description": "Acetaldehyde \u2014 the critical C2 branch point for threonine. Produced by volcanic discharge and by UV cyanosulfidic photoreduction of glycolonitrile. Consumed by both the Strecker route (via lactonitrile/lactaldehyde) and the AMN condensation route (Thanassi). This is the key divergence hub where the two main threonine synthesis strategies branch.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_001", "rxn_005"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_006", "rxn_010"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_014", "description": "Threonine aminonitrile \u2014 the final convergence point before hydrolysis. All 10 pathways converge here. Produced by two mechanistically distinct routes: Strecker synthesis from lactaldehyde (rxn_008, rxn_012) and AMN condensation with acetaldehyde (rxn_010).", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_012"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_011"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 487764.85300064087, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-16T22:16:52.151719", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.8\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Threonine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: The network converges on lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal) as the key carbonyl precursor for threonine, following the experimentally validated cyanosulfidic photoredox pathway of Ritson & Sutherland (2013). Lactaldehyde is produced via UV photoreduction of lactonitrile (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin), and downstream Strecker chemistry converts it to threonine aminonitrile, which is hydrolyzed to threonine. An alternative convergent route uses aminomalononitrile (AMN, from HCN oligomerization) reacting with acetaldehyde per Thanassi (1975). Upstream diversity arises from three independent sources of key precursors (HCN, NH\u2083, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde): (1) volcanic spark discharge (Parker et al. 2011; Ring et al. 1972), (2) hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde on magnetite, and (3) ferrocyanide thermal processing on iron minerals (Ritson & Sutherland 2013). Five hub molecules (HCN, NH\u2083, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, threonine aminonitrile) provide network connectivity and enable 10 distinct pathways spanning all three environments.\n\nMOLECULES (15 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO\u2082 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H\u2082 (hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_003: CH\u2084 (methane) [starting]\n  - mol_004: N\u2082 (nitrogen gas) [starting]\n  - mol_005: H\u2082S (hydrogen sulfide) [starting]\n  - mol_006: HCN (hydrogen cyanide) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_007: NH\u2083 (ammonia) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_008: HCHO (formaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_009: CH\u2083CHO (acetaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_010: HOCH\u2082CN (glycolonitrile) [intermediate]\n  - mol_011: CH\u2083CH(OH)CN (lactonitrile (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin)) [intermediate]\n  - mol_012: CH\u2083CH(OH)CHO (lactaldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_013: H\u2082NC(H)(CN)\u2082 (aminomalononitrile (AMN)) [intermediate]\n  - mol_014: C\u2084H\u2088N\u2082O\u2082 (threonine aminonitrile) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_015: C\u2084H\u2089NO\u2083 (threonine (racemic with allothreonine)) [target]\n\nREACTIONS (12 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_003, mol_004, mol_001, mol_005 -> mol_006, mol_007, mol_008, mol_009 (Volcanic spark discharge synthesis of reactive C-N intermediates) [Surface]\n  - rxn_002: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_008 (Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type formaldehyde synthesis) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_003: mol_006 -> mol_006, mol_007 (Ferrocyanide thermal processing to HCN and NH\u2083) [Surface]\n  - rxn_004: mol_008, mol_006 -> mol_010 (Cyanohydrin formation: formaldehyde + HCN \u2192 glycolonitrile) [Surface]\n  - rxn_005: mol_010, mol_005 -> mol_009 (UV cyanosulfidic photoreduction of glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_006: mol_009, mol_006 -> mol_011 (Cyanohydrin formation: acetaldehyde + HCN \u2192 lactonitrile) [Surface]\n  - rxn_007: mol_011, mol_005 -> mol_012 (UV cyanosulfidic photoreduction of lactonitrile to lactaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_008: mol_012, mol_006, mol_007 -> mol_014 (Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 threonine aminonitrile) [Surface]\n  - rxn_009: mol_006 -> mol_013 (HCN oligomerization to aminomalononitrile (AMN)) [Surface]\n  - rxn_010: mol_013, mol_009 -> mol_014 (AMN condensation with acetaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile intermediate) [Surface]\n  - rxn_011: mol_014 -> mol_015 (Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_012: mol_012, mol_006, mol_007 -> mol_014 (Direct discharge-pool Strecker from accumulated intermediates) [Surface]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Full cyanosulfidic photoredox from discharge-derived precursors (7 steps)\n  - P2: Hydrothermal HCHO + discharge HCN cyanosulfidic route (8 steps)\n  - P3: Hydrothermal HCHO + ferrocyanide HCN/NH\u2083 cyanosulfidic route (8 steps)\n  - P4: Direct discharge acetaldehyde shortcut to Strecker (5 steps)\n  - P5: Ferrocyanide HCN/NH\u2083 + discharge acetaldehyde Strecker route (6 steps)\n  - P6: Discharge-derived AMN route (Thanassi pathway) (4 steps)\n  - P7: Ferrocyanide HCN \u2192 AMN + discharge acetaldehyde (Thanassi pathway) (5 steps)\n  - P8: Cyanosulfidic acetaldehyde + AMN route (6 steps)\n  - P9: Hydrothermal HCHO \u2192 cyanosulfidic acetaldehyde \u2192 AMN condensation (7 steps)\n  - P10: Direct discharge product pool Strecker assembly (5 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_006, mol_007, mol_008, mol_009, mol_014\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 5\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH ON TARGET MOLECULE ===\nThe following research was conducted on the target molecule before network generation. Use it to assess whether the network aligns with known prebiotic chemistry literature.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nPrebiotic Synthesis of Threonine\nMolecule-specific constraints that shape plausible prebiotic routes\nThreonine is a hydroxy-amino acid whose prebiotic formation is complicated by (i) the need to install both an amino group and a hydroxyl-bearing sidechain and (ii) the fact that two diastereomeric products are typically expected: threonine and allothreonine. The co-occurrence of threonine and allothreonine in abiotic product mixtures is explicitly reported in classic spark-discharge experiments, where both \u201cthreonine\u201d and \u201callothreonine\u201d were confirmed among the synthesized amino acids. [1]\nA key practical implication for network design is that many plausible routes do not make threonine \u201cdirectly\u201d from CO\u2082; instead, they converge on a specific aldehyde-level carbonyl precursor\u2014lactaldehyde (2\u2011hydroxypropanal)\u2014followed by Strecker-type conversion to an aminonitrile and then hydrolysis to the amino acid. This lactaldehyde-centered view is articulated both in cyanosulfidic photoredox work (where lactaldehyde is produced photochemically from nitrile/cyanohydrin precursors) and in meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin discussions (where lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the carbonyl precursor for threonine/allothreonine). [2]\nHydrothermal persistence is also a constraint: hydroxy amino acids (including serine and threonine) can undergo dehydration and other degradation pathways during diagenesis/hydrothermal exposure, which matters when evaluating vent-based syntheses or post-synthesis survival. [3]\nKnown prebiotic synthesis routes for threonine\nElectric-discharge (atmospheric / volcanic-plume) synthesis.\nA strong line of experimental evidence for abiotic threonine production comes from spark-discharge experiments designed to simulate reducing (or locally reducing) atmospheres. In the 1958 H\u2082S-rich Miller experiment reanalysis, E. T. Parker[4] and coauthors (2011, Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences) report that residues produced from a spark discharge acting on a gas mixture containing H\u2082S, CH\u2084, NH\u2083, and CO\u2082 contained a broad suite of amino acids and amines, including threonine; chiral amino acids were largely racemic within measurement uncertainty, supporting an abiotic origin (rather than modern biological contamination). [5]\nEarlier work also directly confirmed threonine and allothreonine in discharge products from mixtures including methane, nitrogen, water, and traces of ammonia. [1]\nUV-driven cyanosulfidic photoredox + Strecker assembly via lactaldehyde.\nA second, mechanistically explicit route emerges from cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry associated with Daniel J. Ritson[6] and John D. Sutherland[7] (2013, Angewandte Chemie International Edition). In this system, UV (254 nm) photoredox chemistry reduces nitriles/cyanohydrins to generate aldehydes (including lactaldehyde, the threonine carbonyl precursor), and subsequent addition of HCN and NH\u2083 yields the corresponding Strecker aminonitriles (including the (allo-)threonine aminonitrile). [8]\nA later synthesis-and-systems perspective by Nicholas J. Green[9], Xu, and Sutherland (2021, Journal of the American Chemical Society) explicitly situates this \u201clactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile\u201d step inside a broader UV-photochemical network driven by hydrated-electron photochemistry and cyanosulfidic redox cycling. [10]\nHCN-oligomer / aminomalononitrile (AMN) chemistry as an alternative C\u2013N assembly route.\nA distinct, often-overlooked proposal is that HCN oligomers provide multifunctional C/N building blocks. In this vein, George Thanassi[11] (1975, Journal of Molecular Evolution) reports that reacting aminomalononitrile (a key HCN oligomer) with electrophiles (including aldehydes) followed by hydrolysis yields a range of amino acids, including threonine and allothreonine. This route is attractive for network design because it bypasses the need to pre-form lactaldehyde in bulk; the tradeoff is that selectivity, geochemical plausibility of AMN accumulation, and competing polymerization pathways remain active questions. [12]\nParent-body (meteoritic) Strecker\u2013cyanohydrin synthesis as evidence of a natural \u201cthreonine module.\u201d\nAlthough not an Earth experiment per se, carbonaceous-chondrite organic chemistry provides a natural laboratory for reactions relevant to early Earth delivery and corroborates mechanistic plausibility. A detailed treatment in a Kyushu University-hosted report (associated with threonine/hydroxy-amino-acid analyses in carbonaceous chondrites) describes Strecker-cyanohydrin synthesis where aldehydes/ketones + NH\u2083 \u2192 imines \u2192 CN\u207b addition \u2192 hydrolysis to \u03b1\u2011amino acids, and it explicitly identifies lactaldehyde as the carbonyl precursor for threonine and/or allo-threonine. [13]\nKey intermediates and precursors that define a threonine synthesis network\nAcross the most experimentally grounded routes, threonine sits at the end of a relatively consistent intermediate chain:\nThe minimal \u201cStrecker module\u201d requires a carbonyl compound, ammonia (or another nitrogen source that can generate an imine), and cyanide; the carbonyl required for threonine/allothreonine is lactaldehyde. [14]\nIn cyanosulfidic photoredox networks, the upstream pool can be generated from HCN-derived nitriles and cyanohydrins, with hydrogen sulfide acting as terminal reductant and Cu(I) cyanide functioning as a photoredox-active catalyst/surface. Key intermediates and branch points in the Ritson\u2013Sutherland sequence include: glycolonitrile \u2192 glycolaldehyde (and formaldehyde, acetaldehyde as side/rearranged products), acetaldehyde cyanohydrin (lactonitrile-type node) \u2192 lactaldehyde, and then lactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile in the presence of added HCN and NH\u2083. [8]\nIn spark-discharge contexts, the primary \u201cprecursor-generating\u201d chemistry is atmospheric/plume radical chemistry producing HCN, aldehydes/ketones, and related C\u2013N intermediates that can rain out and further react in surface waters\u2014an explicit motivation for the volcanic-plume framing of Miller-type experiments. [15]\nA key branching control is ammonia availability: the meteoritic discussion emphasizes that ammonia-rich environments favor aminonitrile (amino acid) pathways, whereas ammonia-poor settings favor cyanohydrins and hydroxy acids\u2014directly impacting whether the threonine branch is expressed efficiently. [13]\nReaction mechanisms, conditions, yields, and selectivity\nUV photoredox \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 (allo-)threonine aminonitrile\nThe most quantitatively specified prebiotic route to a threonine precursor is the UV photoredox chemistry of Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.), which directly reports yields for lactaldehyde formation under defined conditions:\nA representative system for first-stage reduction used 10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H\u2082S, 33 mM sodium phosphate, plus solid CuCN (10 mol % relative to glycolonitrile), irradiated at 254 nm in a quartz cuvette; after 2 h, glycolaldehyde (detected as hydrate) formed in 42% yield in solution, alongside other aldehydic products including acetaldehyde. [8]\nCritically, \u201csecond-stage\u201d cyanohydrin photoreductions in the same study yield the dedicated threonine carbonyl precursor: irradiation of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin furnished lactaldehyde in 19% yield (after 2 h irradiation). Lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the Strecker precursor of \u201c(allo-)threonine.\u201d [8]\nDownstream assembly to the threonine aminonitrile is demonstrated by adding HCN and ammonia: when HCN and NH\u2083 were added to photoreduction products, lactaldehyde was \u201csmoothly converted\u201d via its cyanohydrin to the (allo-)threonine Strecker intermediate aminonitrile (aminonitrile 22 in the paper\u2019s numbering). Timescales reported for aminonitrile formation in these systems are days to weeks, indicating that geochemical \u201cholding times\u201d and compartmentalization could matter. [8]\nMechanistically, this route couples: (i) photoredox reduction of nitrile/cyanohydrin nodes to aldehydes (including lactaldehyde) and (ii) conventional Strecker-type conversion (aldehyde \u2192 imine \u2192 aminonitrile) once NH\u2083 and CN\u207b/HCN are available; hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the expected final step in Strecker frameworks, and the meteoritic Strecker discussion explicitly frames hydrolysis of aminonitriles as producing \u03b1-amino acids. [16]\nA systems-level restatement by Green, Xu, and Sutherland (2021, JACS) emphasizes that photoreduction of the relevant cyanohydrin node leads to lactaldehyde, and lactaldehyde then yields a threonine precursor aminonitrile by addition of HCN and NH\u2083, embedding this step inside a broader cyanosulfidic network. [10]\nSpark discharge / volcanic plume simulation \u2192 threonine in complex amino-acid mixtures\nIn Parker et al. (2011, PNAS), reanalysis of archived Miller-type residues from a 1958 discharge experiment (gas mixture including CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S, CO\u2082) identified 23 amino acids and 4 amines; the paper explicitly notes threonine among amino acids generated by this discharge chemistry and interprets racemic chiral amino acids (D/L \u2248 1 within stated uncertainty) as evidence against modern biological contamination. [17]\nQuantitatively, Parker et al. present product abundances as molar ratios relative to glycine (=1). In their Fig. 2, threonine appears at roughly the 10\u207b\u00b2 scale relative to glycine (order-of-magnitude read from the plotted point on a log molar-ratio axis). [18]\nIn an earlier and more expansive discharge study, Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) report that electric discharges in a methane\u2013nitrogen\u2013water system (with traces of ammonia) produced a wide set of amino acids, and explicitly confirm both threonine and allothreonine (alongside serine and others) by ion-exchange chromatography and GC\u2013MS. [1]\nThese discharge pathways are usually interpreted as producing amino acids via formation of reactive small C\u2013N intermediates (HCN, aldehydes/ketones) followed by aqueous-phase assembly (often Strecker-type), and Parker et al. explicitly connect volcanic lightning + reduced gases to generation of HCN and other intermediates that can wash out and accumulate in tidal settings. [15]\nHCN-oligomer (AMN) electrophile chemistry \u2192 threonine/allothreonine after hydrolysis\nThanassi (1975, J. Mol. Evol.) provides experimental evidence that aminomalononitrile-derived chemistry can yield threonine and allothreonine after hydrolysis when AMN is reacted with electrophiles (including aldehydes) under mild conditions. The study explicitly states that amino acids (including threonine/allothreonine) were identified and quantified from hydrolysates. [12]\nFrom a mechanism standpoint, AMN functions as a multifunctional C\u2013N synthon, offering an alternative to \u201csingle-carbonyl + HCN + NH\u2083\u201d assembly; its prebiotic plausibility hinges on whether AMN can accumulate at useful concentrations without being diverted into intractable HCN polymers\u2014an issue treated as part of the broader \u201cHCN chemistry\u201d challenge space in origin-of-life literature. [19]\nHydrothermal Strecker-type synthesis: relevance and limitations for threonine specifically\nHydrothermal Strecker synthesis under mineral-buffered redox conditions is experimentally documented for several amino acids, demonstrating that Strecker chemistry can proceed in plausible vent/flank conditions if aldehydes/ketones and cyanide are available. Andersson & Holm (2000, Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere) summarize hydrothermal experiments (Hennet et al., 1992) using HCN, CH\u2082O, and NH\u2084Cl at 150\u202f\u00b0C and 10 bar in the presence of a pyrite\u2013pyrrhotite\u2013magnetite buffer; reported products include mM-level glycine (\u22489\u201312 mM) and lower but measurable levels of other amino acids (e.g., alanine \u22480.5\u20131.3 mM; aspartate and glutamate at \u22480.28\u20130.36 mM and \u22480.064\u20130.100 mM, respectively). [20]\nHowever, threonine itself is not among the explicitly tabulated products in that summary table, highlighting a practical bottleneck: even if hydrothermal Strecker chemistry is viable in general, demonstrating threonine specifically requires (i) access to lactaldehyde (or a direct hydrothermal pathway to lactaldehyde/lactaldehyde equivalents) and (ii) managing the competing high-temperature degradation chemistry that can disproportionately affect hydroxy amino acids. [21]\nA further caution for purely vent-centric \u201cCO\u2082 \u2192 amino acids\u201d narratives is that some claimed FeS/H\u2082S-driven syntheses have not held up; Keefe et al. (1995, PNAS) report that their FeS/H\u2082S system did not produce amino acids from CO\u2082 (nor via proposed reductive amination/carboxylation), sharpening the distinction between (a) Strecker-type routes requiring carbonyls + CN\u207b and (b) hypothesized direct CO\u2082 fixation-to-amino-acid routes. [22]\nMineral catalysts and surfaces implicated in threonine-relevant steps\nCu(I) cyanide (CuCN) as a photoredox-active heterogeneous catalyst/surface.\nIn the Ritson\u2013Sutherland photoredox system, CuCN is added as a solid; mixing generates a fine dark precipitate that is irradiated, consistent with heterogeneous photoredox cycling and surface-mediated electron production. [8]\nGreen et al. (2021, JACS) discuss Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanocuprate photoredox cycling as a route to hydrated electrons and connect this catalysis to the production of amino-acid Strecker precursors, including the threonine aminonitrile precursor derived from lactaldehyde. [10]\nSulfide minerals as sources of H\u2082S (reductant) and CuCN-generating Cu\u2013S chemistry.\nRitson & Sutherland explicitly note a plausible geochemical source: dissolution of copper sulfide minerals in cyanide solution could generate CuCN catalysts, and dissolution of FeS could provide additional H\u2082S reductant\u2014an explicit mineralogical bridge between rock chemistry and the photoredox network. [8]\nFerrocyanide as a cyanide concentrator and potential \u201cfeedstock conditioner.\u201d\nRitson & Sutherland also emphasize that cyanide can be concentrated by complexation with Fe\u00b2\u207a to form ferrocyanide, and that thermal processing of mixed ferrocyanide salts can yield mixtures containing cyanide, ammonia, and cyanamide upon rehydration\u2014reagents directly relevant to Strecker chemistry and linked nucleotide-precursor reactions. [8]\nPyrite\u2013pyrrhotite\u2013magnetite and silicate buffers in hydrothermal simulations.\nAndersson & Holm\u2019s redox-buffered hydrothermal framework highlights the use of pyrite (FeS\u2082), pyrrhotite (FeS), and magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) to constrain oxygen fugacity (redox), and K\u2011feldspar\u2013muscovite\u2013quartz assemblages to influence pH via ion activity control\u2014key when extrapolating laboratory hydrothermal yields to natural settings. [20]\nEnvironmental context and the main open challenges for threonine\nMost relevant environments by route.\nFor spark-discharge threonine formation, the empirical basis is strongest for localized, reducing volcanic-plume or eruption-lightning environments, where mixtures of reduced gases (e.g., CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S) and oxidized components (e.g., CO\u2082) can coexist transiently; Parker et al. explicitly argue such localized plume chemistry could generate HCN and other intermediates that rain out and accumulate in tidal zones, supporting subsequent aqueous synthesis steps. [15]\nFor UV photoredox threonine-precursor formation, the most relevant setting is a sunlit surface environment that can sustain UV photochemistry (at least episodically) and maintain access to cyanide and sulfide redox pairs; Green et al. note that low H\u2082S solubility and low crustal copper abundance would restrict Cu/H\u2082S cyanosulfidic networks to specific terrains (e.g., copper-rich, alkaline pools), a critical geochemical constraint on global plausibility. [23]\nFor Strecker chemistry in aqueous-alteration contexts (meteorites or analogous wet-rock systems), the carbonaceous-chondrite analysis emphasizes that ammonia abundance and redox state influence whether aminonitriles (\u2192 amino acids) are favored over cyanohydrins (\u2192 hydroxy acids), and it frames threonine/allothreonine formation as dependent on lactaldehyde availability. [13]\nKey bottlenecks and debates.\nA central unresolved bottleneck is sourcing and sustaining lactaldehyde (and/or its direct nitrile/cyanohydrin precursors) at concentrations compatible with downstream Strecker chemistry. The meteoritic analysis proposes that lactaldehyde may be relatively less available than glycolaldehyde/hydroxyacetone because its formation depends on less abundant ethanol-derived radical chemistry in interstellar ices, which would suppress threonine relative to serine/\u03b1\u2011methylserine\u2014an argument that can be repurposed as a constraint on Earth scenarios if analogous precursor biases held in terrestrial inventories. [13]\nAnother challenge is selectivity and stereochemistry. Multiple experimental contexts support predominantly racemic production for chiral amino acids in abiotic syntheses (e.g., spark discharge products; racemic allo-threonine in some meteoritic extracts where it can be resolved cleanly), but threonine\u2019s second stereocenter makes diastereomeric mixtures (threonine/allothreonine) a near-default outcome unless additional selection mechanisms are invoked. [24]\nA third major issue is compatibility of synthesis with survival. Hydroxy amino acids can undergo dehydration and other transformations during heating or long residence times; this is directly relevant to vent models (where high temperatures can accelerate degradation) and also to post-synthesis processing. [3]\nFinally, there is an ongoing debate over whether threonine should be expected to be among the earliest-abundant amino acids at all. The experimental record shows that threonine is certainly possible abiotically (spark discharge; cyanosulfidic networks yielding its Strecker precursors), but it is also plausibly scarcity-limited by precursor availability (lactaldehyde) and stability constraints (hydroxy amino-acid degradation), leaving room for models where threonine is incorporated later into biochemistry relative to simpler amino acids. [25]\n \n[1] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\n[2] [6] [8] [25] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4269183/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4269183/\n[3] https://pubs.usgs.gov/publication/70012489\nhttps://pubs.usgs.gov/publication/70012489\n[4] [5] [9] [11] [15] [17] [18] [24] https://science.gsfc.nasa.gov/sed/content/uploadFiles/publication_files/Parker2011.pdf\nhttps://science.gsfc.nasa.gov/sed/content/uploadFiles/publication_files/Parker2011.pdf\n[7] [12] REACTIONS OF AMINOMALONONITRILE WITH ... - HERO\nhttps://hero.epa.gov/reference/10713764/?utm_source=chatgpt.com\n[10] [19] [23] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8240947/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8240947/\n[13] [14] [16] https://api.lib.kyushu-u.ac.jp/opac_download_md/4474944/sci1377.pdf\nhttps://api.lib.kyushu-u.ac.jp/opac_download_md/4474944/sci1377.pdf\n[20] [21] https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1023/A%3A1006668322298.pdf\nhttps://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1023/A%3A1006668322298.pdf\n[22] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC40511/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC40511/\n\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH ===\n\nConsider how well the network aligns with this literature in your evaluation.\n\n\nPlease evaluate the network and respond with JSON:\n{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"<id>\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, ...},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"environmental_progression\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"target_achievement\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"feedback\": \"<pathway-specific feedback>\",\n            \"approved\": <true if confidence >= 0.8>,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_ids with issues\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"improvements\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"<id of best pathway>\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"network_feedback\": \"<overall assessment>\",\n    \"approved\": <true if any pathway approved>,\n    \"hub_quality\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"convergence_quality\": <0.0-1.0>\n}\n", "raw_response": "{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, \"rxn_004\": 0.95, \"rxn_005\": 0.65, \