gh Fischer-Tropsch HCHO synthesis (rxn_002). While FTT HCHO production on magnetite is plausible, the specific evidence for formaldehyde as a stable FTT product at hydrothermal conditions is less robust than for methane or simple hydrocarbons. The magnetite mineral agent should be explicit in the reaction description. The cross-environmental HCHO feeding into surface cyanohydrin chemistry is a nice convergent feature. Same rxn_005 issue as P1.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Explicitly name magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) as the mineral catalyst in rxn_002\", \"Specify temperature and pressure for FTT synthesis\", \"Add glycolaldehyde intermediate to resolve rxn_005\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_002\": 0.68, \"rxn_003\": 0.58, \"rxn_004\": 0.95, \"rxn_005\": 0.65, \"rxn_006\": 0.95, \"rxn_007\": 0.90, \"rxn_008\": 0.92, \"rxn_011\": 0.90},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.76,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.78,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.80,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.88,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.79,\n            \"feedback\": \"Combines hydrothermal HCHO and ferrocyanide-sourced HCN/NH\u2083. The ferrocyanide processing step (rxn_003) has a stoichiometric issue: HCN \u2192 HCN + NH\u2083 implies HCN is both consumed and regenerated, which does not represent the actual chemistry. In reality, ferrocyanide [Fe(CN)\u2086]\u2074\u207b is formed from Fe\u00b2\u207a + 6 HCN, then thermal processing releases HCN and NH\u2083 as distinct products. A ferrocyanide intermediate should be modeled explicitly. The concept is well-grounded in Ritson & Sutherland (2013) but the representation is flawed.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Introduce ferrocyanide as an explicit intermediate\", \"Fix rxn_003 stoichiometry: Fe\u00b2\u207a + HCN \u2192 ferrocyanide \u2192 HCN + NH\u2083 + cyanamide\", \"Specify iron mineral involvement in ferrocyanide formation\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, \"rxn_006\": 0.95, \"rxn_007\": 0.90, \"rxn_008\": 0.92, \"rxn_011\": 0.90},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.88,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.88,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.68,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.92,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.85,\n            \"feedback\": \"The shortest well-supported Strecker route: spark discharge produces CH\u2083CHO directly, which undergoes cyanohydrin formation \u2192 UV photoreduction \u2192 Strecker. Chemically clean and avoids the problematic rxn_005 glycolonitrile step entirely. Bypasses hydrothermal stage, which weakens environmental diversity but is actually more faithful to the literature evidence. The 5-step path is efficient and plausible. Supported by Parker et al. (2011) for discharge products and Ritson & Sutherland (2013) for the downstream cyanosulfidic and Strecker steps.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Add CuCN as mineral catalyst in rxn_007\", \"Could note that discharge also produces HCN and NH\u2083 needed for rxn_008\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_003\": 0.58, \"rxn_001\": 0.85, \"rxn_006\": 0.95, \"rxn_007\": 0.90, \"rxn_008\": 0.92, \"rxn_011\": 0.90},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.82,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.80,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.70,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.90,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.80,\n            \"feedback\": \"Similar to P4 but sources HCN/NH\u2083 from ferrocyanide processing. The ferrocyanide step has the same stoichiometric representation issue (rxn_003). However, the concept of using ferrocyanide as a cyanide concentrator is well-supported by Ritson & Sutherland (2013). If the ferrocyanide step were properly represented, this would be a strong pathway.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Fix ferrocyanide stoichiometry and introduce explicit intermediate\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, \"rxn_009\": 0.85, \"rxn_010\": 0.78, \"rxn_011\": 0.90},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.82,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.65,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.80,\n            \"feedback\": \"The Thanassi (1975) AMN route is the most concise alternative pathway. AMN from HCN oligomerization condenses with discharge-derived acetaldehyde to ultimately yield threonine aminonitrile. Thanassi explicitly reports threonine/allothreonine from this chemistry. The main concern is AMN accumulation: competing polymerization of HCN may limit AMN concentrations, an open issue noted in the literature. rxn_010 specifics (mechanism of AMN + acetaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile) could be more detailed. Only Surface and Biochemical environments used.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Elaborate the mechanism of AMN-acetaldehyde condensation\", \"Note competing HCN polymerization as a yield-limiting factor\", \"Consider adding a hydrothermal precursor step for environmental breadth\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_003\": 0.58, \"rxn_009\": 0.85, \"rxn_001\": 0.85, \"rxn_010\": 0.78, \"rxn_011\": 0.90},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.78,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.78,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.68,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.77,\n            \"feedback\": \"Combines ferrocyanide HCN source with AMN route. Inherits both the rxn_003 stoichiometry issue and the AMN accumulation concern. The dual sourcing concept is sound but the representation needs refinement.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_010\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Fix ferrocyanide step\", \"Elaborate AMN condensation mechanism\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, \"rxn_004\": 0.95, \"rxn_005\": 0.65, \"rxn_009\": 0.85, \"rxn_010\": 0.78, \"rxn_011\": 0.90},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.80,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.78,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.68,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.78,\n            \"feedback\": \"A hybrid route using cyanosulfidic acetaldehyde production and AMN condensation. This combines two independent C\u2013N assembly strategies, which is creative but also compounds uncertainties (rxn_005 product issue + AMN accumulation concern). The pathway represents genuine chemical diversity in the network.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Fix glycolonitrile photoreduction product\", \"Specify whether both AMN and acetaldehyde are generated in same pool or require mixing\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_002\": 0.68, \"rxn_004\": 0.95, \"rxn_005\": 0.65, \"rxn_009\": 0.85, \"rxn_010\": 0.78, \"rxn_011\": 0.90},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.76,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.75,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.78,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.83,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.76,\n            \"feedback\": \"The longest convergent route combining hydrothermal HCHO, cyanosulfidic acetaldehyde production, and AMN condensation. Provides the best environmental progression (Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical) but accumulates multiple chemical uncertainties. The environmental flow is the strongest feature.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Specify magnetite catalyst\", \"Fix glycolonitrile product\", \"Consider whether 7-step pathway is realistic for prebiotic accumulation\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, \"rxn_012\": 0.82, \"rxn_011\": 0.90},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.84,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.80,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.62,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.88,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.80,\n            \"feedback\": \"The most direct route: spark discharge products accumulate in a pool where Strecker assembly occurs, followed by hydrolysis. rxn_012 is essentially identical to rxn_008 but contextualized as direct from discharge product pool. This is plausible if lactaldehyde is present in the discharge product mixture, but lactaldehyde was not explicitly identified in Parker et al. (2011) product lists. The pathway assumes discharge produces all necessary intermediates including lactaldehyde, which is an extrapolation. Still, the general concept of Strecker assembly from a complex discharge product pool is well-supported.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Clarify how lactaldehyde arises in the discharge product pool\", \"Note that rxn_012 is mechanistically identical to rxn_008 and could be merged\", \"Add evidence for lactaldehyde in discharge product mixtures\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": 0.83,\n    \"network_feedback\": \"This is a well-designed synthesis network that faithfully captures the major experimentally validated routes to prebiotic threonine. The network's greatest strengths are: (1) strong literature alignment with Ritson & Sutherland 2013, Parker et al. 2011, and Thanassi 1975; (2) effective use of five hub molecules creating genuine convergence; (3) the lactaldehyde-centric strategy correctly identified as the key intermediate per literature consensus; and (4) multiple independent precursor sources providing redundancy. Key weaknesses: (a) rxn_005 conflates glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde production\u2014glycolaldehyde should be an explicit intermediate; (b) rxn_003 has incorrect stoichiometry for ferrocyanide processing and needs a ferrocyanide intermediate node; (c) mineral agents (CuCN for photoreduction, magnetite for FTT) are mentioned in the strategy text but not explicit in reaction specifications; (d) the network is heavily Surface-environment-weighted with only one true hydrothermal reaction, though this is actually consistent with the literature which shows limited hydrothermal evidence for threonine specifically; (e) rxn_012 is essentially a duplicate of rxn_008. The network correctly notes racemic threonine/allothreonine as the expected product. Pathway P4 is the strongest because it avoids the problematic rxn_005 and uses the most experimentally supported steps. Overall, the network represents a credible and literature-grounded proposal for prebiotic threonine synthesis.\",\n    \"approved\": true,\n    \"hub_quality\": 0.88,\n    \"convergence_quality\": 0.85\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.85, "rxn_004": 0.95, "rxn_005": 0.65, "rxn_006": 0.95, "rxn_007": 0.9, "rxn_008":